ork, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n || 18\n|-\n| 2015<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015September9StevensonAlexandra\">{{cite news|last1=Stevenson|first1=Alexandra|last2=Bray|first2=Chad|title=K.K.R. Takes 24.9% Stake in Hedge Fund Marshall Wace|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/business/dealbook/kkr-marshall-wace-deal.html|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=9 September 2015|location=New York, N.Y., United States|page=B5|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 22\n|-\n| 2016<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2016December9FortadoLindsay\">{{cite news|last1=Fortado|first1=Lindsay|title=Marshall Wace partners profit as performance fees jump|url=https://www.ft.com/content/7832a836-bd80-11e6-8b45-b8b81dd5d080|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=9 December 2016|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 25\n|-\n| 2017<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2017April23FortadoLindsay\" /> || 29\n|-\n| 2019<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2019February27FletcherLaurence\" /> || 39\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\nBefore starting the fund, Paul Marshall was Head of European Equities at [[Mercury Asset Management]], and Ian Wace was Head of Equities Trading at [[Deutsche Bank]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=6259133&privcapId=3734281|title=Company Overview of Marshall Wace LLP |publisher=Bloomberg|date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|mwam.com}}\n* [http://www.aima.org/ AIMA]\n* [http://www.hfsb.org/ Hedge Fund Standards Board]\n\n{{Hedge funds}}\n\n[[Category:Hedge fund firms in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hedge funds]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Investment management companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{More references|date=April 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name           = Marshall Wace\n| logo           = Marshall-wace-logo.png\n| logo_size      = 240px\n| logo_alt       = \n| type           = [[Limited liability partnership|LLP]]\n| industry       = [[Financial services]]\n| founded        = {{Start date and age|1997}}<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015September9StevensonAlexandra\" />\n| founders       = {{plainlist|style=text-indent:-1em; margin-left:1em;|\n* \u2022 [[Paul Marshall (financier)|Paul Marshall]]<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010September23\">{{cite news|title=British Minister Faces City\u2019s Wrath After Speech|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/09/23/u-k-minister-faces-citys-wrath-after-speech/|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=23 September 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref><br/><small>(CIO & Chairman)</small><ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2014July16StevensonAlexandra\">{{cite news|last1=Stevenson|first1=Alexandra|last2=Goldstein|first2=Matthew|title=Some Top Money Managers Push for Fed to Start Raising Interest Rates|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/16/some-top-money-managers-push-for-fed-to-start-raising-interest-rates/|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=16 July 2014|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n* \u2022 [[Ian Wace]]<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2013April29WerdigierJulia\">{{cite news|last1=Werdigier|first1=Julia|title=Financiers\u2019 Charity Gala Goes the Way of Canap\u00e9s|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/04/29/financiers-charity-gala-goes-the-way-of-canaps/|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=29 April 2013|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref><br/><small>(CEO & chief risk officer)</small><ref name=\"FinancialTimes2016December9FortadoLindsay\" />\n}}\n|  location       = [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n|  num_employees  = \n|  products       = Investment products\n|  revenue        = \n|  operating_income=\n|  net_income     = \n|  homepage       = {{URL|www.mwam.com}}\n| aum                = [[United States Dollar|US$]] 27.1&nbsp;billion<br/>(as of June 30, 2019)<ref name=\"PensionsAndInvestments2019September16\">{{cite news|title=The largest managers of hedge funds (P&I Sep 2019)|url=https://www.pionline.com/special-report-hedge-funds/largest-managers-hedge-funds|accessdate=15 October 2019|agency=Crain Communications Inc|issue=Special Report Hedge Funds|publisher=Pensions & Investments|date=16 September 2019|location=United States|language=English|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Marshall Wace LLP''' is a [[hedge fund]] in [[London]] that was founded by [[Paul Marshall (financier)|Paul Marshall]] and [[Ian Wace]] in 1997. Marshall is chairman and chief investment officer, and Wace is chief executive officer & chief risk officer.\n\n==Overview==\nIn 1997 Marshall and Wace launch Marshall Wace managing $50m; $25m from George Soros and $25m sourced via family and friends.<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2017April23FortadoLindsay\" />\n\nThe firm manages more than $40bn as of 2019<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2019February27FletcherLaurence\">{{cite news|last1=Fletcher|first1=Laurence|title=Hedge fund Marshall Wace hits jackpot with bets on struggling trio|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cba2c084-3a9f-11e9-b856-5404d3811663|accessdate=18 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|issue=Financial Services|publisher=Financial Times|date=27 February 2019|location=London|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and operates from fund management offices in [[London]], [[New York City|New York]]<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2017July16\">{{cite news|title=Chiki Gupta, Brandon Brahm|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/16/fashion/weddings/chiki-gupta-brandon-brahm.html|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|publisher=New York Times|date=16 July 2017|location=United States|page=ST12|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015September9StevensonAlexandra\" /> The head office in London is on Sloane Street.\n\nMarshall Wace was a founder member of the [[Hedge Fund Standards Board]] (HFSB) and is a member of the Alternative Investment Management Association (AIMA).\n\nIn August 2014, Marshall Wace made \u20ac27 million from going short on the [http://www.etftrends.com/2014/08/espirito-santo-still-haunting-portugal-etf/ collapse] of the Portuguese bank Banco Espirito Santo.\n\nIn 2015 [[Kohlberg Kravis Roberts]] agreed to buy a 24.9 percent stake in Marshall Wace.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015September9StevensonAlexandra\" />\n\n==Investment Approach==\nMarshall Wace manages a number of fundamental long short equity funds. The investment process for each uses [[fundamental analysis]] that seeks to identify companies which are substantially mispriced on an absolute or relative basis. Managers have the ability to shift from value to growth, from small to medium to large capitalization stocks, and switch from a net long position to a net short position. Managers can also use futures and options to hedge.\n\n==Products==\nIn addition to its fundamental long/short equity strategies, Marshall Wace runs a proprietary [[alpha capture system]] called TOPS (Trade Optimised Portfolio System), which polls the investment ideas of equity sell-side practitioners (generalists, sector specialists, strategists, and economists) around the world and uses algorithms to analyse and optimise this information into liquid equity portfolios.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2012July15MorgensonjulyGretchen\">{{cite news|last1=Morgensonjuly|first1=Gretchen|title=Surveys Give Big Investors an Early View From Analysts|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/16/business/in-surveys-hedge-funds-see-early-views-of-stock-analysts.html|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=15 July 2012|location=United States|page=A1|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nMost of Marshall Wace's investors are major institutions. However, a number of its funds are [[UCITS]]-compliant vehicles.<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2010December15AhmedAzam\">{{cite news|last1=Ahmed|first1=Azam|title=Paulson\u2019s New Highly Regulated Hedge Fund|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/12/15/paulsons-new-highly-regulated-hedge-fund/|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=15 December 2010|location=United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In addition to the funds Marshall Wace runs itself, a significant proportion of the money it manages for clients resides in [[separately managed account]]s.\n\n==Assets under management==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ \n! Year !! AUM in Bil.<br />USD$\n|- \n| 1997<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2017April23FortadoLindsay\">{{cite news|last1=Fortado|first1=Lindsay|title=Sir Paul Marshall, co-founder Marshall Wace, backing Brexit|url=https://www.ft.com/content/5ab5fb78-2437-11e7-8691-d5f7e0cd0a16|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=23 April 2017|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || .05\n|- \n| 2006<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2006November13MackintoshJames\">{{cite news|last1=Mackintosh|first1=James|title=Marshall Wace aims for \u20ac1.5bn listing|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f9ae939c-7363-11db-9bac-0000779e2340|accessdate=18 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|issue=Financials|publisher=Financial Times|date=13 November 2006|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 4.3\n|- \n| 2007<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2007January14HelenThomas\">{{cite news|last1=Helen|first1=Thomas|title=Marshall Wace co-founder defends methodology|url=https://ftalphaville.ft.com/2007/01/15/1802/marshall-wace-co-founder-defends-methodology/|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|issue=Alphaville|publisher=Financial Times|date=14 January 2007|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 11\n|- \n| 2008<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2008March9MackintoshJames\">{{cite news|last1=Mackintosh|first1=James|title=Marshall Wace raises \u20ac2bn for new fund|url=https://www.ft.com/content/19cb7554-ee0c-11dc-a5c1-0000779fd2ac|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|issue=Financials|publisher=Financial Times|date=9 March 2008|location=London|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 15\n|- \n| 2009<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2009March17MackintoshJames\">{{cite news|last1=Mackintosh|first1=James|title=GLG Partners loses top spot in chart|url=https://www.ft.com/content/f10546c6-131d-11de-a170-0000779fd2ac|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|issue=Financials Services|publisher=Financial Times|date=17 March 2009|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 6.3\n|- \n| 2010<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2010August15JonesSam\">{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Sam|title=Marshall Wace investors poised to wind up listed fund|url=https://www.ft.com/content/822299ee-a88f-11df-86dd-00144feabdc0|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=15 August 2010|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 6\n|- \n| 2014<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2014April25AgnewHarriet\">{{cite news|last1=Agnew|first1=Harriet|last2=Alloway|first2=Tracy|title=Marshall Wace buys controlling stake in Eaglewood Capital|url=https://www.ft.com/content/aa197bf8-cc84-11e3-bd33-00144feabdc0|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=25 April 2014|location=New York, N.Y., United States|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n || 18\n|-\n| 2015<ref name=\"NewYorkTimes2015September9StevensonAlexandra\">{{cite news|last1=Stevenson|first1=Alexandra|last2=Bray|first2=Chad|title=K.K.R. Takes 24.9% Stake in Hedge Fund Marshall Wace|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/business/dealbook/kkr-marshall-wace-deal.html|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=The New York Times Company|issue=DealBook|publisher=New York Times|date=9 September 2015|location=New York, N.Y., United States|page=B5|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 22\n|-\n| 2016<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2016December9FortadoLindsay\">{{cite news|last1=Fortado|first1=Lindsay|title=Marshall Wace partners profit as performance fees jump|url=https://www.ft.com/content/7832a836-bd80-11e6-8b45-b8b81dd5d080|accessdate=17 May 2019|agency=Nikkei|publisher=Financial Times|date=9 December 2016|language=English|url-access=subscription}}</ref> || 25\n|-\n| 2017<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2017April23FortadoLindsay\" /> || 29\n|-\n| 2019<ref name=\"FinancialTimes2019February27FletcherLaurence\" /> || 39\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\nBefore starting the fund, Paul Marshall was Head of European Equities at [[Mercury Asset Management]], and Ian Wace was Head of Equities Trading at [[Deutsche Bank]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=6259133&privcapId=3734281|title=Company Overview of Marshall Wace LLP |publisher=Bloomberg|date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|mwam.com}}\n* [http://www.aima.org/ AIMA]\n* [http://www.hfsb.org/ Hedge Fund Standards Board]\n\n{{Hedge funds}}\n\n[[Category:Hedge fund firms in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hedge funds]]\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Investment management companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Bamboo10Bamboo", "label": "safe", "comment": "reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marshall_Wace"}
{"title_page": "Covert racism", "text_new": "{{Short description|Type of racist behavior}}{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=November 2013}}\n{{globalize|article|the United States of America|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Covert racism''' is a form of [[racism|racial discrimination]] that is disguised and subtle, rather than public or obvious. Concealed in the fabric of society, covert racism discriminates against individuals through often evasive or seemingly passive methods.<ref> {{cite book|last=Coates |first=Rodney |title=Covert Racism |editor-last=Coates |editor-first=Rodney |location=Lieden, The Netherlands |publisher=Brill |year=2007}}</ref>  Covert, racially biased decisions are often hidden or rationalized with an explanation that society is more willing to accept. These racial biases cause a variety of problems that work to empower the suppressors while diminishing the rights and powers of the oppressed. Covert racism often works subliminally, and often much of the discrimination is being done subconsciously.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pierce |first1=Chester |title=The Black Seventies |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/blackseventies00barb |chapter-url-access=registration |chapter=Offensive Mechanisms |editor-last=Barbour |editor-first=Floyd |location=Boston, Massachusetts |publisher=Porter Sargent Publisher |year=1970 }}</ref>\n\n==History in the U.S.==\nWith the long history of slavery in the United States, racism has always been an issue. The enslavement of millions of Africans along with the huge influx of immigrants throughout its history has allowed great diversity, but has created racial segregation.  With the abolition of slavery, different forms of [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] were implemented, including [[Jim Crow laws]] and the later American political structures which invited extreme segregation within cities and the suburbanization of the white working and middle class.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weir |first=Margaret |url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst;jsessionid=LW5GB3d5NfJQPgJlKpVMxFcxppJWLnDyqbM8P9gR4xnQ2vCnprnT!-1784052340!351573012?docId=5000217817 |title=Race And Urban Poverty: Comparing Europe And America |publisher=Brookings Review |date=Summer 1993 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>  As overt and obvious racial discrimination became illegal and less and less apparent, the idea that the nation was homogenizing became popular. It was thought that as the U.S. accepted more immigrants from different cultures a sort of \"[[melting pot]]\" would occur and unify everyone under one creed. Along with this, ideologies formed that every group of immigrants goes through the same discrimination. Groups were thought to eventually assimilate, but racism remained and is still present today.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4931534.stm | work=BBC News | title='Melting pot' America | date=May 12, 2006 | accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhen black [[G.I. (military)|G.I.]]s returned home from the [[Vietnam War]], they were denied the money promised to them to support their education and help them buy homes. While only 9.5% of soldiers serving in Vietnam were black, they comprised nearly 20% of front line troops, and 25% or more of airborne divisions. Black servicemen were twice as likely to re-enlist in the Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force and three times as likely to re-enlist in the Army as their white counterparts, not for any sense of adventure, but because they found the monetary rewards to be promising and they were treated as equals or near equals.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UtoDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA31&dq=problems+of+black+G.I.s#v=onepage&q=problems%20of%20black%20G.I.s&f=false |title=Ebony - Google Boeken |date= August 1968|accessdate=December 22, 2011|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company }}</ref>\n\n==Racially constructed barriers==\n{{Main|Racial segregation in the United States}}\n{{Main|Residential segregation}}\n\nIn the 1950s, shortly after [[World War II]], urban areas were overtly divided into blocks by race. Blocks occupied by minorities were close to toxic dumps, busy highways, and other undesirable locations throughout cities. Whites lived away from these areas and often realtors would not be able to show properties to whites within these areas. Landlords could choose to not rent apartments to certain minority groups, maintaining segregation. Until the late 1960s, the government sanctioned discrimination in housing markets by promulgating rules preventing blacks from receiving mortgages insured by the [[Federal Housing Administration]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Weir |first=Margaret |url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst?docId=5000217817 |title=Race And Urban Poverty: Comparing Europe And America |publisher=[[Brookings Review]] |date=Summer 1993 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> FHA loans, a Federal Mortgage programme, goes to the white majority and reaches few minorities. In a study done in Syracuse between 1996 and 2000, of the 2,169 FHA loans issued, only 29 (or 1.3 percent) went to predominantly minority neighborhoods, compared with 1,694 (or 78.1 percent) that went to white neighborhoods and 446 (or 20 percent) that went to integrated neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-86148585.html |accessdate=January 20, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sieh |first=Maureen |url=http://syracusethenandnow.org/Redlining/NewRedlining/FHA_Goes_To_WellToDo.htm |title=Few FHA loans go to minorities, study says |publisher=The Post-Standard |date=May 21, 2002 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> \n\n[[Mortgage discrimination]] played a significant part in the real estate bubble that popped during the later part of 2008. It was found that minorities were disproportionately steered by lenders into subprime loans.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nasiripour |first=Shahien |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/10/01/minorities-more-likely-to_n_306870.html |title=Minorities More Likely To Be Denied Refinancing |publisher=Huffington Post |date=October 1, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> The division of neighborhoods into school districts that avoid integration and end up investing on the \"whiteness\" of their neighborhoods, and the resulting residential and social segregation of whites from blacks in the United States, creates a socialization process that limits whites' chances for developing meaningful relationships with blacks and other minorities. The wealthy also control some of these divisions, which results in the minorities being excluded due to the low levels of income in most minority neighborhoods. The segregation experienced by whites from blacks fosters segregated lifestyles and leads them to develop positive views about themselves and negative views about blacks.<ref>''[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.689.4374&rep=rep1&type=pdf \"Every Place Has a Ghetto...\": The Significance of Whites' Social and Residential Segregation]''  Eduardo Bonilla-Silva and  David G. Embrick ''Symbolic Interaction'' Summer 2007, Vol. 30, No. 3, Pages 323-345</ref> Many blacks and Latinos have been discriminated against when applying for jobs because of stereotypes about work ethic based on race, and having a name that sounds \"black\" can sometimes lead to that person being denied an interview.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/12/business/economic-scene-sticks-stones-can-break-bones-but-wrong-name-can-make-job-hard.html?pagewanted=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Economic Scene; Sticks and stones can break bones, but the wrong name can make a job hard to find | first=Alan B. | last=Krueger | date=December 12, 2002 | accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>  Minorities are less likely to obtain key information regarding job interviews and are often denied access to high-paying jobs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eserver.org/courses/spring95/76-100g/DennisFela.html |title=Worries Facing Minority Education |publisher=[[Eserver.org]] |date=1995-05-05 |accessdate=December 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225235736/http://eserver.org/courses/spring95/76-100g/DennisFela.html |archive-date=February 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMinorities are also denied access to a quality education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wce.wwu.edu/Resources/CEP/METT/2006/African%20American%20Strategic%20Plan.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613001027/http://www.wce.wwu.edu/Resources/CEP/METT/2006/African%20American%20Strategic%20Plan.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-13 }}</ref> This is usually because many poor areas also predominantly consist of minorities. This means that there is often a lack of funding in schools.  The levels of poverty and lack of educational opportunities perpetuate themselves, creating a vicious cycle.  Racial stereotypes emerge and these populations are further disenfranchised by individuals who do not help or do not care.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corsi |first=Jerome |url=https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0965638340/vdare |title=Paved with Good Intentions: The Failure of Race Relations in Contemporary America (9780965638340): Jared Taylor: Books |date= |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> In the new [[Civil Rights Project]] report from [[UCLA]], dated January 2009, it stated that schools are more segregated today than they were in the 1950s. Millions of non-white students are locked into \"dropout factory\" high schools, where huge percentages do not graduate, and few are well prepared for college or a future in the U.S. economy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.projectcensored.org/top-stories/articles/2-us-schools-are-more-segregated-today-than-in-the-1950s-source/ |title=US Schools are More Segregated Today than in the 1950s |publisher=Project Censored |accessdate=December 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125131514/http://www.projectcensored.org/top-stories/articles/2-us-schools-are-more-segregated-today-than-in-the-1950s-source/ |archivedate=November 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nA majority of the prison population in the U.S. consists of racial minorities. According to the [[Center for American Progress]], black men are approximately seven times more likely to be incarcerated than whites, and spend on average ten months longer in prison.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawthorne |first=Alexandra |url=http://www.americanprogress.org/issues/2009/04/black_men_recession.html |title=Weathering the Storm: Black Men in the Recession |publisher=Center for American Progress |date=April 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> Since the beating of [[Rodney King]] (1991) was videotaped and was broadcast around the world, local and federal law-enforcement agencies have opened investigations to determine whether or not there is a pattern of police brutality not only in Los Angeles but around the country.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/18/us/seven-minutes-los-angeles-special-report-videotaped-beating-officers-puts-full.html?sec=&spon= | work=The New York Times | title=Seven Minutes In Los Angeles - A special report.; Videotaped Beating by Officers Puts Full Glare on Brutality Issue | first1=Richard W. | last1=Stevenson | first2=Timothy | last2=Egan | date=March 18, 1991 | accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Demographic differences in healthcare===\n{{Main|Health disparities|Race and health}}\nIn the [[United States]], health disparities are well documented in ethnic minorities such as [[African American]]s, [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]], [[Asian American]]s, and [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanics]].<ref>Goldberg, J., Hayes, W., and Huntley, J. [http://www.healthpolicyohio.org/publications/healthdisparities.html \"Understanding Health Disparities.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515210412/http://www.healthpolicyohio.org/publications/healthdisparities.html |date=2008-05-15 }} Health Policy Institute of Ohio (November 2004), page 3.</ref> When compared to [[White American|whites]], these minority groups have higher incidence of chronic diseases, higher mortality, and poorer health outcomes. Among the disease-specific examples of racial and ethnic disparities in the United States is the cancer incidence rate among African Americans, which is 25% higher than among whites.<ref name=\"APHA\">American Public Health Association (APHA), Eliminating Health Disparities: Toolkit (2004).</ref> In addition, adult African Americans and Hispanics have approximately twice the risk as whites of developing diabetes. Minorities also have higher rates of [[cardiovascular disease]], [[HIV/AIDS]], and [[infant mortality]] than whites.<ref name=\"APHA\"/> Caucasian Americans have much lower life expectancy than Asian Americans.<ref name=\"eight\">{{cite web |url=http://www.diverseeducation.com/artman/publish/article_6370.shtml |title=Study: Race, Location Affects Longevity |publisher=Associated Press |date=September 16, 2006 |accessdate=December 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228170227/http://diverseeducation.com/artman/publish/article_6370.shtml |archivedate=February 28, 2009 }}</ref> A 2001 study found large racial differences exist in healthy life expectancy at lower levels of education.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Crimmins EM, Saito Y |title=Trends in healthy life expectancy in the United States, 1970\u20131990: gender, racial, and educational differences |journal=Soc Sci Med |volume=52 |issue=11 |pages=1629\u201341 |date=June 2001 |pmid=11327137 |doi= 10.1016/S0277-9536(00)00273-2}}</ref>\n\nPublic spending is highly correlated with age; average per capita public spending for seniors was more than five times that for children ($6,921 versus $1,225).  Average public spending for non-Hispanic blacks ($2,973) was slightly higher than that for whites ($2,675), while spending for Hispanics ($1,967) was significantly lower than the population average ($2,612).  Total public spending is also strongly correlated with self-reported health status ($13,770 for those reporting \"poor\" health versus $1,279 for those reporting \"excellent\" health).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/cgi/reprint/hlthaff.27.5.w349v1 |title=The Distribution Of Public Spending For Health Care In The United States, 2002 |publisher=Content.healthaffairs.org |date=2008-07-29 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere is a great deal of research into inequalities in health care. In some cases, these inequalities are caused by income disparities that result in lack of health insurance and other barriers to receiving services.<ref>[http://www.kff.org/uninsured/7705.cfm \"How Trends in the Health Care System Affect Low-Income Adults: Identifying Access Problems and Financial Burdens\"], Issue Brief: Kaiser Commission on Medicaid and the Uninsured, December 21, 2007. Retrieved February 26, 2008.</ref> In other cases, inequalities in health care reflect a [[systemic bias]] in the way medical procedures and treatments are prescribed for different ethnic groups. Raj Bhopal writes that the history of [[Scientific racism|racism in science]] and medicine shows that people and institutions behave according to the ethos of their times.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Bhopal R |title=Spectre of racism in health and health care: lessons from history and the United States |journal=BMJ |volume=316 |issue=7149 |pages=1970\u20133 |date=June 1998 |pmid=9641943 |pmc=1113412 |doi=10.1136/bmj.316.7149.1970}}</ref> Nancy Krieger wrote that racism underlies unexplained inequities in health care, including treatment for heart disease,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0002-8703(84)90656-2 |author=Oberman A, Cutter G |title=Issues in the natural history and treatment of coronary heart disease in black populations: surgical treatment |journal=Am. Heart J. |volume=108 |issue=3 Pt 2 |pages=688\u201394 |date=September 1984 |pmid=6332513 }}</ref> [[kidney failure]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archinte.1988.00380060069016 |author=Kjellstrand CM |title=Age, sex, and race inequality in renal transplantation |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=148 |issue=6 |pages=1305\u20139 |date=June 1988 |pmid=3288159 }}</ref> [[bladder cancer]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2105/AJPH.79.6.772 |author=Mayer WJ, McWhorter WP |title=Black/white differences in non-treatment of bladder cancer patients and implications for survival |journal=Am J Public Health |volume=79 |issue=6 |pages=772\u20135 |date=June 1989 |pmid=2729474 |pmc=1349641 }}</ref> and [[pneumonia]].<ref>Yergan J, Flood AB, LoGerfo JP, Diehr P. Relationship between patient race and the intensity of hospital services. Med Care. 1987;25:592\u2013603.</ref> [[Raj Bhopal]] writes that these inequalities have been documented in numerous studies. The consistent and repeated findings were that black Americans received less health care than white Americans, particularly when the care involved expensive new technology.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/jama.263.17.2344 |title=Black-white disparities in health care |journal=JAMA |volume=263 |issue=17 |pages=2344\u20136 |date=May 1990 |pmid=2182918 |author1=Council on Ethical Judicial Affairs }}</ref>  A 2008 study has found that when minority and white patients use the same hospital, they are given the same standard of care.<ref>Darrell J. Gaskin, Christine S. Spencer, Patrick Richard, Gerard F. Anderson, [[Neil R. Powe]], and Thomas A. LaVeist, [http://content.healthaffairs.org/cgi/reprint/27/2/518?ijkey=KSQtLI48Rtqmo&keytype=ref&siteid=healthaff \"Do Hospitals Provide Lower-Quality Care To Minorities Than To Whites?,\"] Health Affairs, March/April 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.commonwealthfund.org/publications/publications_show.htm?doc_id=672918 \"In the Literature: Do Hospitals Provide Lower-Quality Care To Minorities Than To Whites?,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316012830/http://www.commonwealthfund.org/publications/publications_show.htm?doc_id=672918 |date=2008-03-16 }} The [[Commonwealth Fund]], March 11, 2008</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n*[[Ethnopluralism]]\n*[[Institutional racism]]\n*[[Internalized racism]]\n*[[Laissez-faire racism]]\n*[[Microaggression]]\n*[[Micro-inequity]]\n*[[Passive-aggressive behavior]]\n*[[Race card]]\n*[[Racial discrimination]]\n*[[Racial segregation]]\n*[[Redlining]]\n*[[Second-class citizen]]\n*[[White flight]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book| url=https://archive.org/details/arroganceofraceh00fred| url-access=registration| quote=George M. Fredrickson.| title=The arrogance of race: historical perspectives on slavery, racism, and social inequality| publisher=Wesleyan University Press| year= 1988| isbn= 978-0-8195-6217-3| author1=Fredrickson, George M }}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=v6uf-LNCtCcC&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=racebending&source=bl&ots=tWcKVWLUbV&sig=tyfzhOdTgPCp6zZhE3tB2I_ypqg&hl=en&ei=SWlJS8qVF4rw0gTrrdnrAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CBEQ6AEwAzjoAg#v=onepage&q=&f=false Race Bending: \"Mixed\" Youth Practicing Strategic Racialization in California Race Talk Dilemma in an American School by Mica Pollock.]\n*[http://search.barnesandnoble.com/booksearch/isbninquiry.asp?ean=9789087902773& In RACISTS BEWARE: UNCOVERING RACIAL POLITICS IN THE POSTMODERN SOCIETY, Dei identifies and subjects to close scrutiny the new race-bending logics of what he calls \"postmodern\" societies]\n*[http://hjb.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/28/2/267 Hispanic Journal of Behavioral Sciences Transnational Media Literacy Analytic Reflections on a Program With Latina Teens Lucila Vargas University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill ]\n*[https://litigation-essentials.lexisnexis.com/webcd/app?action=DocumentDisplay&crawlid=1&doctype=cite&docid=86+Denv.+U.L.+Rev.+709&srctype=smi&srcid=3B15&key=8d7bd5c76700a12fe3af60e5d0c9db28 2009 Denver University Law Review, Article: Hillary Clinton, Sarah Palin, and Michelle Obama: Performing Gender, Race, and Class on the Campaign Trail]\n*Kleg, M. (1993). [https://books.google.com/books?id=aaMuQHO04I0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Hate, Prejudice, and Racism]. Albany: State University of New York Press.\n*Berreby, David. Sept./Oct. 2000. Race Counts. From \"The Sciences\".\n*Brodkin, Karen. 1998. [https://archive.org/details/howjewsbecamewhi00brod How Jews Became White Folks]. Rutgers University Press.\n*Coates, Rodney D. 2007. Covert Racism:Theories, Institutions.  Brill Press. \n*Dyer, Richard. 1994. White. Routledge.\n*Gallagher, Charles A. 2003. [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=sTzRKLqcmbUC&oi=fnd&pg=PA145&dq=%22Playing+the+White+Ethnic+Card:+Using+Ethnic+Identity+to+Deny+Contemporary+Racism%22&ots=4zWWOfzbwe&sig=L-pMa3TJaGioYI6To39ssNXQ2_c#v=onepage&q=%22Playing%20the%20White%20Ethnic%20Card%3A%20Using%20Ethnic%20Identity%20to%20Deny%20Contemporary%20Racism%22&f=false Playing the White Ethnic Card: Using Ethnic Identity to Deny Contemporary Racism]. Routledge.\n*Lipsitz, George. 1998.  The Possessive Investment in Whiteness. Temple University Press.\n*{{cite book | last1 = Pierce | first1 = Chester M. | authorlink1 = Chester Middlebrook Pierce | title = The Black Seventies | chapter = Offensive Mechanisms | editors = Floyd B. Barbour | publisher = Porter Sargent | year = 1970 |oclc=108950}}\n*Jared Taylor. 2004 Edition. Paved with Good Intentions: The Failure of Race Relations in Contemporary America\n\n{{Racism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Covert Racism}}\n[[Category:Definition of racism controversy]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Type of racist behavior}}{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=November 2013}}\n{{globalize|article|the United States of America|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Covert racism''' is a form of [[racism|racial discrimination]] that is disguised and subtle, rather than public or obvious. Concealed in the fabric of society, covert racism discriminates against individuals through often evasive or seemingly passive methods.<ref> {{cite book|last=Coates |first=Rodney |title=Covert Racism |editor-last=Coates |editor-first=Rodney |location=Lieden, The Netherlands |publisher=Brill |year=2007}}</ref>  Covert, racially biased decisions are often hidden or rationalized with an explanation that society is more willing to accept. These racial biases cause a variety of problems that work to empower the suppressors while diminishing the rights and powers of the oppressed. Covert racism often works subliminally, and often much of the discrimination is being done subconsciously.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pierce |first1=Chester |title=The Black Seventies |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/blackseventies00barb |chapter-url-access=registration |chapter=Offensive Mechanisms |editor-last=Barbour |editor-first=Floyd |location=Boston, Massachusetts |publisher=Porter Sargent Publisher |year=1970 }}</ref>\n\n==History in the U.S.==\nWith the long history of slavery in the United States, racism has always been an issue. The enslavement of millions of Africans along with the huge influx of immigrants throughout its history has allowed great diversity, but has created racial segregation.  With the abolition of slavery, different forms of [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] were implemented, including [[Jim Crow laws]] and the later American political structures which invited extreme segregation within cities and the suburbanization of the white working and middle class.<ref>{{cite web|last=Weir |first=Margaret |url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst;jsessionid=LW5GB3d5NfJQPgJlKpVMxFcxppJWLnDyqbM8P9gR4xnQ2vCnprnT!-1784052340!351573012?docId=5000217817 |title=Race And Urban Poverty: Comparing Europe And America |publisher=Brookings Review |date=Summer 1993 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>  As overt and obvious racial discrimination became illegal and less and less apparent, the idea that the nation was homogenizing became popular. It was thought that as the U.S. accepted more immigrants from different cultures a sort of \"[[melting pot]]\" would occur and unify everyone under one creed. Along with this, ideologies formed that every group of immigrants goes through the same discrimination. Groups were thought to eventually assimilate, but racism remained and is still present today.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/4931534.stm | work=BBC News | title='Melting pot' America | date=May 12, 2006 | accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhen black [[G.I. (military)|G.I.]]s returned home from the [[Vietnam War]], they were denied the money promised to them to support their education and help them buy homes. While only 9.5% of soldiers serving in Vietnam were black, they comprised nearly 20% of front line troops, and 25% or more of airborne divisions. Black servicemen were twice as likely to re-enlist in the Navy, Marine Corps and Air Force and three times as likely to re-enlist in the Army as their white counterparts, not for any sense of adventure, but because they found the monetary rewards to be promising and they were treated as equals or near equals.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=UtoDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA31&dq=problems+of+black+G.I.s#v=onepage&q=problems%20of%20black%20G.I.s&f=false |title=Ebony - Google Boeken |date= August 1968|accessdate=December 22, 2011|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company }}</ref>\n\n==Racially constructed barriers==\n{{Main|Racial segregation in the United States}}\n{{Main|Residential segregation}}\n\nIn the 1950s, shortly after [[World War II]], urban areas were overtly divided into blocks by race. Blocks occupied by minorities were close to toxic dumps, busy highways, and other undesirable locations throughout cities. Whites lived away from these areas and often realtors would not be able to show properties to whites within these areas. Landlords could choose to not rent apartments to certain minority groups, maintaining segregation. Until the late 1960s, the government sanctioned discrimination in housing markets by promulgating rules preventing blacks from receiving mortgages insured by the [[Federal Housing Administration]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Weir |first=Margaret |url=https://www.questia.com/googleScholar.qst?docId=5000217817 |title=Race And Urban Poverty: Comparing Europe And America |publisher=[[Brookings Review]] |date=Summer 1993 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> FHA loans, a Federal Mortgage programme, goes to the white majority and reaches few minorities. In a study done in Syracuse between 1996 and 2000, of the 2,169 FHA loans issued, only 29 (or 1.3 percent) went to predominantly minority neighborhoods, compared with 1,694 (or 78.1 percent) that went to white neighborhoods and 446 (or 20 percent) that went to integrated neighborhoods.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G1-86148585.html |accessdate=January 20, 2010 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sieh |first=Maureen |url=http://syracusethenandnow.org/Redlining/NewRedlining/FHA_Goes_To_WellToDo.htm |title=Few FHA loans go to minorities, study says |publisher=The Post-Standard |date=May 21, 2002 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> \n\n[[Mortgage discrimination]] played a significant part in the real estate bubble that popped during the later part of 2008. It was found that minorities were disproportionately steered by lenders into subprime loans.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nasiripour |first=Shahien |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/10/01/minorities-more-likely-to_n_306870.html |title=Minorities More Likely To Be Denied Refinancing |publisher=Huffington Post |date=October 1, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> The division of neighborhoods into school districts that avoid integration and end up investing on the \"whiteness\" of their neighborhoods, and the resulting residential and social segregation of whites from blacks in the United States, creates a socialization process that limits whites' chances for developing meaningful relationships with blacks and other minorities. The wealthy also control some of these divisions, which results in the minorities being excluded due to the low levels of income in most minority neighborhoods. The segregation experienced by whites from blacks fosters segregated lifestyles and leads them to develop positive views about themselves and negative views about blacks.<ref>''[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.689.4374&rep=rep1&type=pdf \"Every Place Has a Ghetto...\": The Significance of Whites' Social and Residential Segregation]''  Eduardo Bonilla-Silva and  David G. Embrick ''Symbolic Interaction'' Summer 2007, Vol. 30, No. 3, Pages 323-345</ref> Many blacks and Latinos have been discriminated against when applying for jobs because of stereotypes about work ethic based on race, and having a name that sounds \"black\" can sometimes lead to that person being denied an interview.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/12/12/business/economic-scene-sticks-stones-can-break-bones-but-wrong-name-can-make-job-hard.html?pagewanted=1 | work=The New York Times | title=Economic Scene; Sticks and stones can break bones, but the wrong name can make a job hard to find | first=Alan B. | last=Krueger | date=December 12, 2002 | accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>  Minorities are less likely to obtain key information regarding job interviews and are often denied access to high-paying jobs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eserver.org/courses/spring95/76-100g/DennisFela.html |title=Worries Facing Minority Education |publisher=[[Eserver.org]] |date=1995-05-05 |accessdate=December 22, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120225235736/http://eserver.org/courses/spring95/76-100g/DennisFela.html |archive-date=February 25, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nMinorities are also denied access to a quality education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wce.wwu.edu/Resources/CEP/METT/2006/African%20American%20Strategic%20Plan.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613001027/http://www.wce.wwu.edu/Resources/CEP/METT/2006/African%20American%20Strategic%20Plan.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-13 }}</ref> This is usually because many poor areas also predominantly consist of minorities. This means that there is often a lack of funding in schools.  The levels of poverty and lack of educational opportunities perpetuate themselves, creating a vicious cycle.  Racial stereotypes emerge and these populations are further disenfranchised by individuals who do not help or do not care.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corsi |first=Jerome |url=https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0965638340/vdare |title=Paved with Good Intentions: The Failure of Race Relations in Contemporary America (9780965638340): Jared Taylor: Books |date= |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> In the new [[Civil Rights Project]] report from [[UCLA]], dated January 2009, it stated that schools are more segregated today than they were in the 1950s. Millions of non-white students are locked into \"dropout factory\" high schools, where huge percentages do not graduate, and few are well prepared for college or a future in the U.S. economy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.projectcensored.org/top-stories/articles/2-us-schools-are-more-segregated-today-than-in-the-1950s-source/ |title=US Schools are More Segregated Today than in the 1950s |publisher=Project Censored |accessdate=December 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125131514/http://www.projectcensored.org/top-stories/articles/2-us-schools-are-more-segregated-today-than-in-the-1950s-source/ |archivedate=November 25, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nA majority of the prison population in the U.S. consists of racial minorities. According to the [[Center for American Progress]], black men are approximately seven times more likely to be incarcerated than whites, and spend on average ten months longer in prison.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cawthorne |first=Alexandra |url=http://www.americanprogress.org/issues/2009/04/black_men_recession.html |title=Weathering the Storm: Black Men in the Recession |publisher=Center for American Progress |date=April 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref> Since the beating of [[Rodney King]] (1991) was videotaped and was broadcast around the world, local and federal law-enforcement agencies have opened investigations to determine whether or not there is a pattern of police brutality not only in Los Angeles but around the country.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/03/18/us/seven-minutes-los-angeles-special-report-videotaped-beating-officers-puts-full.html?sec=&spon= | work=The New York Times | title=Seven Minutes In Los Angeles - A special report.; Videotaped Beating by Officers Puts Full Glare on Brutality Issue | first1=Richard W. | last1=Stevenson | first2=Timothy | last2=Egan | date=March 18, 1991 | accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Demographic differences in healthcare===\n{{Main|Health disparities|Race and health}}\nIn the [[United States]], health disparities are well documented in ethnic minorities such as [[African American]]s, [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]], [[Asian American]]s, and [[Hispanics in the United States|Hispanics]].<ref>Goldberg, J., Hayes, W., and Huntley, J. [http://www.healthpolicyohio.org/publications/healthdisparities.html \"Understanding Health Disparities.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080515210412/http://www.healthpolicyohio.org/publications/healthdisparities.html |date=2008-05-15 }} Health Policy Institute of Ohio (November 2004), page 3.</ref> When compared to [[White American|whites]], these minority groups have higher incidence of chronic diseases, higher mortality, and poorer health outcomes. Among the disease-specific examples of racial and ethnic disparities in the United States is the cancer incidence rate among African Americans, which is 25% higher than among whites.<ref name=\"APHA\">American Public Health Association (APHA), Eliminating Health Disparities: Toolkit (2004).</ref> In addition, adult African Americans and Hispanics have approximately twice the risk as whites of developing diabetes. Minorities also have higher rates of [[cardiovascular disease]], [[HIV/AIDS]], and [[infant mortality]] than whites.<ref name=\"APHA\"/> Caucasian Americans have much lower life expectancy than Asian Americans.<ref name=\"eight\">{{cite web |url=http://www.diverseeducation.com/artman/publish/article_6370.shtml |title=Study: Race, Location Affects Longevity |publisher=Associated Press |date=September 16, 2006 |accessdate=December 22, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228170227/http://diverseeducation.com/artman/publish/article_6370.shtml |archivedate=February 28, 2009 }}</ref> A 2001 study found large racial differences exist in healthy life expectancy at lower levels of education.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Crimmins EM, Saito Y |title=Trends in healthy life expectancy in the United States, 1970\u20131990: gender, racial, and educational differences |journal=Soc Sci Med |volume=52 |issue=11 |pages=1629\u201341 |date=June 2001 |pmid=11327137 |doi= 10.1016/S0277-9536(00)00273-2}}</ref>\n\nPublic spending is highly correlated with age; average per capita public spending for seniors was more than five times that for children ($6,921 versus $1,225).  Average public spending for non-Hispanic blacks ($2,973) was slightly higher than that for whites ($2,675), while spending for Hispanics ($1,967) was significantly lower than the population average ($2,612).  Total public spending is also strongly correlated with self-reported health status ($13,770 for those reporting \"poor\" health versus $1,279 for those reporting \"excellent\" health).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/cgi/reprint/hlthaff.27.5.w349v1 |title=The Distribution Of Public Spending For Health Care In The United States, 2002 |publisher=Content.healthaffairs.org |date=2008-07-29 |accessdate=December 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThere is a great deal of research into inequalities in health care. In some cases, these inequalities are caused by income disparities that result in lack of health insurance and other barriers to receiving services.<ref>[http://www.kff.org/uninsured/7705.cfm \"How Trends in the Health Care System Affect Low-Income Adults: Identifying Access Problems and Financial Burdens\"], Issue Brief: Kaiser Commission on Medicaid and the Uninsured, December 21, 2007. Retrieved February 26, 2008.</ref> In other cases, inequalities in health care reflect a [[systemic bias]] in the way medical procedures and treatments are prescribed for different ethnic groups. Raj Bhopal writes that the history of [[Scientific racism|racism in science]] and medicine shows that people and institutions behave according to the ethos of their times.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Bhopal R |title=Spectre of racism in health and health care: lessons from history and the United States |journal=BMJ |volume=316 |issue=7149 |pages=1970\u20133 |date=June 1998 |pmid=9641943 |pmc=1113412 |doi=10.1136/bmj.316.7149.1970}}</ref> Nancy Krieger wrote that racism underlies unexplained inequities in health care, including treatment for heart disease,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0002-8703(84)90656-2 |author=Oberman A, Cutter G |title=Issues in the natural history and treatment of coronary heart disease in black populations: surgical treatment |journal=Am. Heart J. |volume=108 |issue=3 Pt 2 |pages=688\u201394 |date=September 1984 |pmid=6332513 }}</ref> [[kidney failure]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archinte.1988.00380060069016 |author=Kjellstrand CM |title=Age, sex, and race inequality in renal transplantation |journal=Arch. Intern. Med. |volume=148 |issue=6 |pages=1305\u20139 |date=June 1988 |pmid=3288159 }}</ref> [[bladder cancer]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2105/AJPH.79.6.772 |author=Mayer WJ, McWhorter WP |title=Black/white differences in non-treatment of bladder cancer patients and implications for survival |journal=Am J Public Health |volume=79 |issue=6 |pages=772\u20135 |date=June 1989 |pmid=2729474 |pmc=1349641 }}</ref> and [[pneumonia]].<ref>Yergan J, Flood AB, LoGerfo JP, Diehr P. Relationship between patient race and the intensity of hospital services. Med Care. 1987;25:592\u2013603.</ref> [[Raj Bhopal]] writes that these inequalities have been documented in numerous studies. The consistent and repeated findings were that black Americans received less health care than white Americans, particularly when the care involved expensive new technology.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/jama.263.17.2344 |title=Black-white disparities in health care |journal=JAMA |volume=263 |issue=17 |pages=2344\u20136 |date=May 1990 |pmid=2182918 |author1=Council on Ethical Judicial Affairs }}</ref>  One recent study has found that when minority and white patients use the same hospital, they are given the same standard of care.<ref>Darrell J. Gaskin, Christine S. Spencer, Patrick Richard, Gerard F. Anderson, [[Neil R. Powe]], and Thomas A. LaVeist, [http://content.healthaffairs.org/cgi/reprint/27/2/518?ijkey=KSQtLI48Rtqmo&keytype=ref&siteid=healthaff \"Do Hospitals Provide Lower-Quality Care To Minorities Than To Whites?,\"] Health Affairs, March/April 2008</ref><ref>[http://www.commonwealthfund.org/publications/publications_show.htm?doc_id=672918 \"In the Literature: Do Hospitals Provide Lower-Quality Care To Minorities Than To Whites?,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080316012830/http://www.commonwealthfund.org/publications/publications_show.htm?doc_id=672918 |date=2008-03-16 }} The [[Commonwealth Fund]], March 11, 2008</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=18em|\n*[[Ethnopluralism]]\n*[[Institutional racism]]\n*[[Internalized racism]]\n*[[Laissez-faire racism]]\n*[[Microaggression]]\n*[[Micro-inequity]]\n*[[Passive-aggressive behavior]]\n*[[Race card]]\n*[[Racial discrimination]]\n*[[Racial segregation]]\n*[[Redlining]]\n*[[Second-class citizen]]\n*[[White flight]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book| url=https://archive.org/details/arroganceofraceh00fred| url-access=registration| quote=George M. Fredrickson.| title=The arrogance of race: historical perspectives on slavery, racism, and social inequality| publisher=Wesleyan University Press| year= 1988| isbn= 978-0-8195-6217-3| author1=Fredrickson, George M }}\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=v6uf-LNCtCcC&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=racebending&source=bl&ots=tWcKVWLUbV&sig=tyfzhOdTgPCp6zZhE3tB2I_ypqg&hl=en&ei=SWlJS8qVF4rw0gTrrdnrAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CBEQ6AEwAzjoAg#v=onepage&q=&f=false Race Bending: \"Mixed\" Youth Practicing Strategic Racialization in California Race Talk Dilemma in an American School by Mica Pollock.]\n*[http://search.barnesandnoble.com/booksearch/isbninquiry.asp?ean=9789087902773& In RACISTS BEWARE: UNCOVERING RACIAL POLITICS IN THE POSTMODERN SOCIETY, Dei identifies and subjects to close scrutiny the new race-bending logics of what he calls \"postmodern\" societies]\n*[http://hjb.sagepub.com/cgi/content/abstract/28/2/267 Hispanic Journal of Behavioral Sciences Transnational Media Literacy Analytic Reflections on a Program With Latina Teens Lucila Vargas University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill ]\n*[https://litigation-essentials.lexisnexis.com/webcd/app?action=DocumentDisplay&crawlid=1&doctype=cite&docid=86+Denv.+U.L.+Rev.+709&srctype=smi&srcid=3B15&key=8d7bd5c76700a12fe3af60e5d0c9db28 2009 Denver University Law Review, Article: Hillary Clinton, Sarah Palin, and Michelle Obama: Performing Gender, Race, and Class on the Campaign Trail]\n*Kleg, M. (1993). [https://books.google.com/books?id=aaMuQHO04I0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false Hate, Prejudice, and Racism]. Albany: State University of New York Press.\n*Berreby, David. Sept./Oct. 2000. Race Counts. From \"The Sciences\".\n*Brodkin, Karen. 1998. [https://archive.org/details/howjewsbecamewhi00brod How Jews Became White Folks]. Rutgers University Press.\n*Coates, Rodney D. 2007. Covert Racism:Theories, Institutions.  Brill Press. \n*Dyer, Richard. 1994. White. Routledge.\n*Gallagher, Charles A. 2003. [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=sTzRKLqcmbUC&oi=fnd&pg=PA145&dq=%22Playing+the+White+Ethnic+Card:+Using+Ethnic+Identity+to+Deny+Contemporary+Racism%22&ots=4zWWOfzbwe&sig=L-pMa3TJaGioYI6To39ssNXQ2_c#v=onepage&q=%22Playing%20the%20White%20Ethnic%20Card%3A%20Using%20Ethnic%20Identity%20to%20Deny%20Contemporary%20Racism%22&f=false Playing the White Ethnic Card: Using Ethnic Identity to Deny Contemporary Racism]. Routledge.\n*Lipsitz, George. 1998.  The Possessive Investment in Whiteness. Temple University Press.\n*{{cite book | last1 = Pierce | first1 = Chester M. | authorlink1 = Chester Middlebrook Pierce | title = The Black Seventies | chapter = Offensive Mechanisms | editors = Floyd B. Barbour | publisher = Porter Sargent | year = 1970 |oclc=108950}}\n*Jared Taylor. 2004 Edition. Paved with Good Intentions: The Failure of Race Relations in Contemporary America\n\n{{Racism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Covert Racism}}\n[[Category:Definition of racism controversy]]\n[[Category:Racism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Devgirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDemographic differences in healthcare:specificity. also 2008 is not particularly recent", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covert_racism"}
{"title_page": "Gillender Building", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Gillender Building\n|image              = Gillender Building1900.jpg\n|caption            = The Gillender Building in April 1910. The larger structure on the right is the Hanover Bank Building, built in 1903 and demolished in 1931.\n|location           = [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]], [[New York City]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|40.70757|-74.01050|display=inline,title}}\n|status             = Demolished\n|start_date         = 1896\n|completion_date    = 1897\n|demolished_date    = 1910\n|building_type      = Office\n|antenna_spire      =\n|roof               = {{convert|273|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|top_floor          =\n|floor_count        = 20\n|elevator_count     =\n|cost               = $500,000\n|floor_area         = {{cvt|26|x|73|ft}}\n|architect          = Charles I. Berg,<br />Edward H. Clark\n|structural_engineer=\n|main_contractor    = Charles T. Willis Company\n|developer          =\n|owner              = Helen Gillender Asinari\n|management         =\n|references         =\n}}\nThe '''Gillender Building''' was an early 20-story, 273-foot-tall (83 m)<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">17 floors in the main tower volume and three floors in the [[cupola]]</ref> [[Early skyscrapers|skyscraper]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. It stood on the northwest corner of [[Wall Street]] and [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]], on a narrow strip of land along Nassau Street measuring only {{convert|26|\u00d7|73|ft}}. At the time of its completion in 1897, the Gillender Building was, depending on [[List of tallest buildings in the world#Ranking criteria and alternatives|ranking methods]], the fourth- or eighth-tallest structure in New York.<ref name=KOR219/>\n\nThe Gillender Building was designed by Charles I. Berg and Edward H. Clark. Upon completion, it was praised as an engineering novelty, and was quoted by some as \"one of the wonders of the city\".<ref name=Apr10/> It attracted attention for a visible disproportion of height and footprint which commanded a relatively low rentable area, and was deemed economically obsolete from the start.<ref name=\"KOR221\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=221}}</ref>\n\nAfter thirteen years of uneventful existence, the Gillender Building was sold in December 1909 for a record price of {{Convert|822|$/ft2|$/m2|abbr=}} of land,{{efn|$822 per square foot is most quoted figure ({{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=221}}, {{harvnb|ps=.|Silver|2000|p=210}}, The Skyscraper Museum Virtual Archive). {{harvnb|ps=.|Willis|1995|p=150}}, provides a marginally different figure of $820 per square foot}} and was demolished between April and June 1910 to make way for the 41-story [[Bankers Trust]] tower at [[14 Wall Street]]. The press referred to the Gillender Building's demolition as the first time when a modern skyscraper was torn down to be replaced with a taller and larger one. At the time, the Gillender Building was the [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings|tallest building ever demolished voluntarily]].\n\n==Site==\nThe Gillender Building stood on the northwest corner of [[Wall Street]] and [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]], on a narrow strip measuring {{Convert|26|ft||abbr=}} on Wall Street and {{Convert|73|ft||abbr=}} on Nassau Street.<ref name=\"SSO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_01.htm|title=Introduction and History of the Bankers Trust|publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref>{{efn|Contemporary ''New York Times'' articles reported marginally different footprint of {{convert|25|x|74|feet}}<ref name=Apr10/>}}<ref name=\"METRIC1\">A measurement of {{cvt|7.6|x|22.25|m}} is given by {{harvnb|ps=.|Whitehand|Larkham|1992|p=121}}</ref> The site is occupied by the 41-story [[Bankers Trust]] tower at [[14 Wall Street]], which occupies both the site of the Gillender Building and the adjoining seven-story Stevens Building at 12-14 Wall Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997|ps=.|p=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century, the area north of Wall Street was occupied by John Damen's farm; Damen sold the land in 1685 to captain John Knight, an officer of [[Thomas Dongan, 2nd Earl of Limerick|Thomas Dongan]]'s administration. Knight resold the land to Dongan, and Dongan resold it in 1689 to [[Abraham de Peyster]] and Nicholas Bayard. Both de Peyster and Bayard served as [[List of mayors of New York City|Mayors of New York]]. The first known building on the Gillender Building's site, a [[sugar house]], was built by Samuel Bayard. In 1718, most of the present-day block was sold to a church congregation, while the corner lot, cut into narrow strips, remained in possession of the de Peysters and the Bayards.<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">See the 18th century map and corresponding notes in {{harvnb|ps=.|''The New York Times'' April 10, 1910}}</ref> In 1773, de Peyster sold the corner lot to the Verplanck family for less than $1,500; the Verplanck mansion later housed Wall Street banks.<ref name=\"Apr10\" />\n\nThe second [[New York City Hall]], erected in 1700 and torn down in 1816,<ref name=\"Apr10\" /> stood on the site present-day [[Federal Hall]] and occupied the eastern side of present-day Nassau Street, which historically curved around the City Hall. It was straightened after the demolition of the second City Hall, but its early route was retained in the placement of the corner buildings (including the Gillender Building but not 14 Wall Street) which were set back from the street, providing a wider than usual sidewalk.<ref name=\"Apr10\" /> In 1816, the corner lot was owned by Charles Gardner, who sold the property in 1817 for $11,200; it was further resold in 1835 for $47,500 and in 1849 for $55,000. [[Charles Frederick Briggs]] and [[Edgar Allan Poe]] operated the offices of the ''[[Broadway Journal]]'' on this site from 1844 until 1845.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Wolfe|2008|p=26}}</ref> From 1849 until December 1909, the lot remained in the hands of a single family.<ref name=\"Apr10\" /> Adjacent lots were owned by the Sampson family since 1840; in 1880, this property was developed into the Stevens Building.<ref name=\"July7\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe Gillender Building was designed by Charles I. Berg and Edward H. Clark. It belonged to \"a series of elegant towers in various [[Neoclassical architecture|classical]] modes erected in New York in the 1890s\"<ref name=\"COND\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moma.org/collection/details.php?theme_id=10194&section_id=T079156|title=Skyscraper. Part 2. History and development|author=Condit|first=Gary W.|publisher=Grove Art Online / Museum of Modern Art, NY|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> and is considered \"a notable example\" of its period along with the Central Bank Building ([[William Birkmire]], 1897, demolished) and the [[American Surety Building]] ([[Bruce Price]], 1894\u20131896, extant).<ref name=\"COND\" />Berg and Clerk followed the Italian rule of triple vertical partitioning: expensive decoration was limited to the three bottom floors (what the pedestrians see from the street) and the upper two floors and the crowning tower. Massive [[cornice]]s above the second and third floors visually separated the lower levels from the clean wall surface stretching above up until the fourteenth floor; starting from the ninth floor, it gradually re-acquired ornaments and arched windows as if in anticipation of the ornate [[Italian Baroque]] cupola above.<ref name=\"KOR219\" />\n\nThe Gillender Building cost $500,000 to construct<ref name=\"KOR219\" /><ref name=\"Apr30\" /> and attracted attention due to the disproportion of its height and footprint.<ref name=\"Dec16\">{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/12/16/101819554.pdf|title=$822 a Square Foot, Record Land Price. Sale of Northwest Corner of Wall and Nassau Streets Passes Old $700 Mark|date=December 16, 1909|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-21|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The new structure occupied {{convert|26|\u00d7|73|ft}},<ref name=\"METRIC1\" /> ruling out efficient space plans. [[Quicksand]] under the site required use of [[Foundation (engineering)|foundations]] made of [[Deep foundation|caisson]].<ref name=\"SSO1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_a00.htm|title=History of the Bankers Trust. April 1910|publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> These caissons consumed the underground space that could be otherwise used by [[bank vault]]s or retail storage, further reducing the building's value.<ref name=\"SSO1\" /> Its rentable area (30,000&nbsp;square feet or 2,790&nbsp;square&nbsp;meters) was on par with [[Manhattan]]'s 1897 average for pre-skyscraper buildings (26,300 square feet or 2,400 square meters) and lower than the area of adjacent six-story Stevens Building.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Whitehand|Larkham|1992|p=124}}</ref> The disproportion was made more evident in 1903, when the new Hanover National Bank Building, built on the same Nassau Street block and being only marginally taller, dwarfed the slender Gillender Building.<ref name=\"SSO\" />\n\nStructurally, it was based on fully wind-braced [[steel frame]] with masonry infill.<ref name=\"KOR220\" /> The main volume of the tower rose to {{convert|219|ft|m}} without setbacks, with a three-story [[cupola]] crown reaching {{convert|273|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"KOR220\" /> ''The New York Times'' erroneously called Gillender the \"highest office structure in the world\".<ref name=\"KOR221\" /><ref name=\"Apr30\" /><ref group=\"lower-alpha\">The [[Manhattan Life Insurance Building]] (1894) was taller at {{convert|348|ft|m}}.</ref> \n\n==Construction==\nIn 1896, Helen L. Gillender Asinari,{{efn|Granddaughter of George Lovett, who purchased the site in 1849<ref name=\"Apr10\"/>}} owner of a six-story office building on the corner of Wall and Nassau Streets, decided to replace it with a {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=on}} tall tower, capitalizing on a tenfold increase in land value.<ref name=Dec16/> The building was most likely named after Helen's father, millionaire [[tobacco]] merchant Eccles Gillender (1810\u20131877).<ref name=QA>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E6DF153CF937A35755C0A9669C8B63&sec=&spon=&&scp=4&sq=gillender%20building&st=cse |title=Streetscapes/Readers' Questions; Building's Name, Gallery's Photo, Complex's Origin |author=Gray |first=Christopher |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 3, 2000}}</ref> According to media, Helen Gillender had hurried to build the new tower prior to the anticipated enactment of new, stricter [[building code]]s, which led to the shortcomings of the building's design,<ref name=QA/><ref name=\"rer19091218\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 18, 1909|title=Record Price for Manhattan Land|url=https://rerecord.library.columbia.edu/pdf_files/ldpd_7031148_044_25.pdf|journal=The Real Estate Record: Real estate record and builders' guide|volume=84|page=|pages=1128|via=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|number=2179}}</ref> even though the regulations did not come into effect until 1916.<ref name=QA/> An alternative version presented by Joseph Korom<ref name=KOR219>{{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=219}}</ref> attributes construction of the Gillender Building to Augustus Teophilus Gillender (born 1843), principal partner in a law firm.<ref name=KOR219/>\n\nThe construction contract was awarded to the Charles T. Willis Company, while [[Hecla Iron Works]], Atlas Cement Company, and the Okonite Company of Passaic were principal suppliers.<ref name=KOR220>{{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=220}}</ref> Advertised as fully [[Fireproofing|fireproof]] and as the most modern tower on the market,<ref name=\"KOR221\" /> the Gillender Building was occupied by financial firms through its short lifetime and was perceived as economically obsolete from the start.<ref name=\"KOR221\" /> There were no notable incidents other than two [[lightning]] strikes in its spire in July 1897 and May 1900; the latter \"sent splinters flying in every direction\" without casualties.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1900/06/01/101058007.pdf |title=Bolt Destroys Second Flag Pole Erected in the Same Spot |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 1, 1900}}</ref>\n\n==Takeover==\n[[File:Detroit Photographic Company (0610).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Gillender Building]]\n[[File:NYC pano 1902 centered Gillender Bldg.jpg|240px|right|thumb|New York skyline in 1902. Gillender Building in the center, behind the [[Trinity Church, New York|Trinity Church]].]]\nIn 1909, financial institutions began rapidly expanding their properties within the Financial District. The [[Bankers Trust|Bankers Trust Company]] joined the process after the [[Bank of Montreal]], the [[Fourth National Bank of New York|Fourth National Bank]], and the [[The Guardian Life Insurance Company of America|Germania Life Insurance Company]]  acquired their properties on Wall and Nassau Streets.<ref name=July7/> Bankers Trust, which was established in 1902, had been a tenant at the Gillender Building for six years<ref name=Z146>{{harvnb|ps=.|Ward|Zunz|1992|p=146}}</ref><ref name=Jan2/> and their choice of site was motivated by its location near the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=Z146/> The company, with [[J. P. Morgan]] on the board,<ref name=Z146/> grew rapidly and intended to land itself permanently in the \"vortex of America's financial life\".<ref name=Z147>{{harvnb|ps=.|Ward|Zunz|1992|p=147}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1909, Bankers Trust signed a long-term lease agreement with the Sampson family, owners of the Stevens Building;<ref name=July7/> the company preferred leasing over purchasing due to the high price of land on Wall Street.<ref name=Z147/> Located on the same block as the Gillender Building, the L-shaped, seven-story Stevens Building wrapped around it and possessed far longer facades on both Wall and Nassau Streets.<ref name=July7>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/07/07/101890349.pdf |title=New Office Building for Wall Street. Sixteen-Story Structure, Costing $1,500,000, to Go Up on the Stevens Site |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=July 9, 1909}}</ref> Initially, the press reported that Bankers Trust planned to build a 16-story office building wrapping around the Gillender Building, with the two bottom floors outfitted to be \"one of the finest banking rooms in the city\".<ref name=July7/> Later, it was disclosed that the trust had been negotiating purchase of Gillender Building since April 1909;<ref name=Dec16/> the deal would have consolidated enough land for a new tower with {{convert|94|ft|m}} frontage facing Wall Street and {{convert|102|ft|m}} on Nassau Street.<ref name=Apr30/>\n\nIn December 1909, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported a new record set: The Manhattan Trust Company, a bank connected to Bankers Trust through common control by J. P. Morgan,<ref name=ABS/> acquired the Gillender Building from Helen Gillender Asinari, paying approximately $1,500,000 for the {{convert|1825|sqft|m2|abbr=|adj=on}} property ({{Inflation|index=US|value=1,500,000|start_year=1909|r=-3|fmt=eq}}), or {{Convert|822|$/ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Dec16\" /><ref name=\"rer19091218\" /> This was considered a record amount for land in New York City: the previous record was for [[1 Wall Street]], the land under which had sold for {{Convert|558.65|$/ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"rer19091218\" /> The land had been worth $55,000 sixty years earlier ({{Inflation|index=US|value=55,000|start_year=1903|r=-3|fmt=eq}}).<ref name=Apr10/> Negotiations had progressed since April 1909 and the sale was virtually closed in November.<ref name=Dec16/>\n\nOn January 2, 1910, the press reported that the Manhattan Trust had resold the building to Bankers Trust, which had completed land acquisition for its large corner property.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\"/><ref name=Jan2>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/01/02/105072302.pdf |title=Gillender Building Resold |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=January 2, 1910}}</ref> By April 1910, the final cash price paid to Manhattan Trust was adjusted to $1,250,000;<ref name=Apr10>{{cite news |title=New Bankers' Trust Company Tower Sets Building and Realty Records |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/04/10/102037556.pdf |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=April 10, 1910 |ref={{harvid|''The New York Times'' April 10, 1910}}}}</ref> in exchange for the $250,000 difference, the Manhattan Trust retained long-term lease rights for the ground floor \"and some other space in the building\".<ref name=Jan2/> This brought nominal cash price per foot on par or below the earlier record ($700 per square foot for a lot on the corner of Wall Street and [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]).<ref name=Dec16/> Contemporaries agreed that the Manhattan Trust and Bankers Trust acted in accord and that the latter targeted Gillender Building from the start.<ref name=Jan2/> Bankers Trust absorbed Manhattan Trust Company in February 1912.<ref name=ABS>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/02/21/100519178.pdf |title=Bankers' Absorbs Manhattan |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=February 21, 1912}}</ref>\n\nThe press anticipated the upcoming demolition of the Gillender Building \"as the first time when such a high-class office building representing the best type of fire-proof construction\" would be torn down<ref name=Apr30/> and \"one of the largest building operations ever undertaken in New York\".<ref name=Apr10/> Bankers Trust publicized the drafts by [[Trowbridge & Livingston]] to build a 39-story{{efn|32 rentable floors and 7 storage floors in the pyramidal top; two underground [[bank vault]] floors and one underground [[mechanical floor]]<ref name=Apr10/>}} tower that, when announced, would be New York City's third tallest building after the [[Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Tower]] and the [[Singer Building]].<ref name=Apr10/> At the time, the Gillender Building was the [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings|tallest building ever demolished voluntarily]].<ref name=\"KOR221\" />\n\n==Demolition==\n[[File:BankersTrust outline 1912.svg|right|thumb|241px|Gillender and Stevens buildings (in red) and the Bankers Trust Building that replaced them, looking from the [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]] elevation]]\nDemolition of the Stevens Building commenced in the beginning of April 1910.<ref name=Apr10/> The contract to demolish the Gillender Building was awarded to Jacob Volk, known for his work on the [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson#History|McAdoo Tunnel]],<ref name=Apr30/> who himself claimed experience in demolishing 900 buildings.<ref name=June3>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/06/03/104937119.pdf |title=Breaking Records in House Wrecking. The 20-Story Gillender Building Fast Coming Down Before the Contractor's Attacks |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 3, 1910}}</ref> Initially, Volk subscribed to complete the job in 35 days and pay a $500 penalty for each day delayed.<ref name=Apr30/> The schedule was later extended to 45 days.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1910/06/03/archives/breaking-records-in-housewrecking-the-20story-gillender-building.html|title=Breaking Records in House-Wrecking; The 20-Story Gillender Building Fast Coming Down Before the Contractor's Attacks|date=1910-06-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building's tenants remained in the tower until the wrecking crews arrived on-site.<ref name=Apr30/> Demolition commenced April 29, 1910,<ref name=Apr30>{{cite news |title=Skyscraper Going: Higher One Coming. Razing 20-Story Gillender Building to Make Room for 32-Story Bankers' Trust Home |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B03E4D71539E433A25753C3A9629C946196D6CF |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=April 30, 1910}}</ref> and was officially completed June 16, 1910, one day ahead of schedule.<ref name=Jun17/> It cost Bankers Trust $50,000 plus $500 for advance completion; the contractor also received all the scrap valued at $25,000.<ref name=Jun17/>\n\nDemolition was preceded with erection of a massive timber canopy over the sidewalks and a wire mesh over the street to protect people from falling debris. Inside, elevator shafts were converted into garbage chutes for the torn partitions and exterior masonry scrap. By May 2, the top [[belvedere (structure)|belvedere]] was dismantled completely and most of the cupola masonry was removed, exposing its steel skeleton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16268.htm |title=Demolition process: May 5, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> By the end of May, most of the Stevens Building was torn down; the Gillender Building's masonry walls were removed down to the seventh floor and steel skeleton was down to eleventh floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16361.htm |title=Demolition process: May 31, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> By June 12, all that remained of Gillender Building was a single level of its steel frame visible above protective scaffoulding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16392.htm |title=Demolition process: June 12, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> In the following four days, the ground was completely cleared; work on its underground foundations commenced a month later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16502.htm |title=Foundation work: July 19, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> The [[granite]] slabs from the Gillender Building were recycled into tombstones of the [[Green-Wood Cemetery]] in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Silver|2000|p=210}}</ref>\n\nTwo hundred and fifty men were involved in the demolition project during the daytime, and a hundred during the night.<ref name=\":0\" /> Of these, two [[Italian American|Italian]] workers were injured by falling girders, one of whom subsequently died in the hospital.<ref name=\"KOR221\" /><ref name=Jun17/>\n\n<blockquote>\nThe famous Gillender Building, which when erected twelve years ago on the northwest corner of Nassau and Wall Streets was called the tallest skyscraper in the world, its tower rising some 300&nbsp;feet above the streets, has gone the way of other landmarks.<br />\n\u2013 ''The New York Times'', June 17, 1910<ref name=Jun17>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/06/17/105081626.pdf |title=Gillender Building Down |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 17, 1910}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe Bankers Trust Company Building, now known as [[14 Wall Street]], was completed in 1912, becoming the tallest banking building in the world.<ref name=SSO/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> The bank occupied only the three lower floors; its main operations were housed elsewhere in less expensive offices.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Willis|1995|p=150}}</ref> In 1931, Bankers Trust acquired and demolished the adjacent Hanover, Astor, and Pine Street Buildings, and replaced them with an annex to the original Bankers Trust Building. The annex was completed in 1933, tripling its rentable area.<ref name=SSO/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> Helen Gillender Asinari had died a year earlier, in 1932.<ref name=QA/>\n\n{{gallery\n|File:Gillender Building1896d.jpg|Top floors and spire\n|File:Gillender Building1896c.jpg|Higher elevations\n|File:Gillender Building1896b.jpg|Midsections\n|File:Gillender Building1896a.jpg|Lower sections\n|File:Gillender Building1896.jpg|Final demolition\n}}\n\n==In media==\nThe Gillender Building is the site of a final scene in [[Jed Rubenfeld]]'s ''[[The Interpretation of Murder]]'', a 2006 novel reconstructing [[Sigmund Freud]]'s 1909 visit to New York. The narrator and Nora Acton (linked to Freud's case study of ''Dora'') meet for the last time in the Gillender cupola, watch the New York skyline, well aware that the building will be soon torn down.<ref>{{cite book |author=Rubenfeld |first=Jed |title=The Interpretation of Murder |year=2006 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=978-0-312-42705-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oZwJtMKJoKsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jed+Rubenfeld |pp=425-429}}</ref>\n\nIn [[M. K. Hobson]]'s ''Hotel Astarte'', The Warlock \"had his fingernails polished by a mute Chinese woman he kept in locked in a small room in his office on the top floor of the Gillender Building on Wall Street\". The story is set in June 1910 and October 1929, when the Gillender Building had already been dismantled.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Hobson |first=M. K. |title=Hotel Astarte |journal=[[Realms of Fantasy]] |date=June 2007 |url=http://www.demimonde.com/SFWA/astarte.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020105459/http://www.demimonde.com/SFWA/astarte.html |archivedate=October 20, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1949.pdf|title=14 Wall Street|date=January 14, 1997|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997}}}}\n* {{cite book |author=Korom |first=Joseph |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JVzYO1TyZ6AC |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JVzYO1TyZ6AC/page/n218 219] |quote=Gillender Building. |title=The American Skyscraper, 1850\u20131940 |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-8283-2188-4 |publisher=Branden Books |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |author=Silver |first=Nathan |title=Lost New York |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-618-05475-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lDXAg0nh-OgC&pg=PA210&dq=Gillender+Building |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Landscape of Modernity: Essays on New York City, 1900-1940 |author1=Ward |first1=David |author2=Zunz |first2=Olivier |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year=1992 |id={{ISBN|9780871549006}} | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cp3sdg5nEvoC | isbn=978-0-87154-900-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Urban Landscapes: International Perspectives |author1=Whitehand |first1=J. W. R. |author2=Larkham |first2=Peter J. |publisher=Routledge |year=1992 |isbn=978-0-415-07074-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E4oElpcDld0C&pg=PA124&dq=Gillender+Building |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ITT7GXSQnIC&pg=PA150&dq=Gillender+Building |author=Willis |first=Carol |title=Form Follows Finance: Skyscrapers and Skylines in New York and Chicago |publisher=Princeton Architectural Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-1-56898-044-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IufPkFnxoQgC&pg=PA26&dq=Gillender+Building |title=Literary Haunts & Homes; American Authors |author=Wolfe |first=Theodore F. |publisher=Read Books |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4437-0773-2 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_01.htm |title=Photo archive of Gillender and Bankers Trust buildings |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200110210059/https://www.skyscraper.org/EXHIBITIONS/WALL_STREET/14_wall.php|archive-date=2020-01-10|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://digitalgallery.nypl.org/nypldigital/dgkeysearchresult.cfm?word=Gillender%20Building%20(New%20York%2C%20N.Y.)&s=3&notword=&f=2 |title=Historical images of the Gillender Building |publisher=[[New York Public Library]] |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}\n\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1910]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1897]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Wall Street]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Short description|Office skyscraper in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{Infobox building\n|name               = Gillender Building\n|image              = Gillender Building1900.jpg\n|caption            = The Gillender Building in April 1910. The larger structure on the right is the Hanover Bank Building, built in 1903 and demolished in 1931.\n|location           = [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]], [[New York City]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|40.70757|-74.01050|display=inline,title}}\n|status             = Demolished\n|start_date         = 1896\n|completion_date    = 1897\n|demolished_date    = 1910\n|building_type      = Office\n|antenna_spire      =\n|roof               = {{convert|273|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n|top_floor          =\n|floor_count        = 20\n|elevator_count     =\n|cost               = $500,000\n|floor_area         = {{cvt|26|x|73|ft}}\n|architect          = Charles I. Berg,<br />Edward H. Clark\n|structural_engineer=\n|main_contractor    = Charles T. Willis Company\n|developer          =\n|owner              = Helen Gillender Asinari\n|management         =\n|references         =\n}}\nThe '''Gillender Building''' was an early 20-story, 273-foot-tall (83 m)<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">17 floors in the main tower volume and three floors in the [[cupola]]</ref> [[Early skyscrapers|skyscraper]] in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. It stood on the northwest corner of [[Wall Street]] and [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]], on a narrow strip of land along Nassau Street measuring only {{convert|26|\u00d7|73|ft}}. At the time of its completion in 1897, the Gillender Building was, depending on [[List of tallest buildings in the world#Ranking criteria and alternatives|ranking methods]], the fourth- or eighth-tallest structure in New York.<ref name=KOR219/>\n\nThe Gillender Building was designed by Charles I. Berg and Edward H. Clark. Upon completion, it was praised as an engineering novelty, and was quoted by some as \"one of the wonders of the city\".<ref name=Apr10/> It attracted attention for a visible disproportion of height and footprint which commanded a relatively low rentable area, and was deemed economically obsolete from the start.<ref name=\"KOR221\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=221}}</ref>\n\nAfter thirteen years of uneventful existence, the Gillender Building was sold in December 1909 for a record price of {{Convert|822|$/ft2|$/m2|abbr=}} of land,{{efn|$822 per square foot is most quoted figure ({{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=221}}, {{harvnb|ps=.|Silver|2000|p=210}}, The Skyscraper Museum Virtual Archive). {{harvnb|ps=.|Willis|1995|p=150}}, provides a marginally different figure of $820 per square foot}} and was demolished between April and June 1910 to make way for the 41-story [[Bankers Trust]] tower at [[14 Wall Street]]. The press referred to the Gillender Building's demolition as the first time when a modern skyscraper was torn down to be replaced with a taller and larger one. At the time, the Gillender Building was the [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings|tallest building ever demolished voluntarily]].\n\n==Site==\nThe Gillender Building stood on the northwest corner of [[Wall Street]] and [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]], on a narrow strip measuring {{Convert|26|ft||abbr=}} on Wall Street and {{Convert|73|ft||abbr=}} on Nassau Street.<ref name=\"SSO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_01.htm|title=Introduction and History of the Bankers Trust|publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref>{{efn|Contemporary ''New York Times'' articles reported marginally different footprint of {{convert|25|x|74|feet}}<ref name=Apr10/>}}<ref name=\"METRIC1\">A measurement of {{cvt|7.6|x|22.25|m}} is given by {{harvnb|ps=.|Whitehand|Larkham|1992|p=121}}</ref> The site is occupied by the 41-story [[Bankers Trust]] tower at [[14 Wall Street]], which occupies both the site of the Gillender Building and the adjoining seven-story Stevens Building at 12-14 Wall Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997|ps=.|p=2}}</ref>\n\nIn the 17th century, the area north of Wall Street was occupied by John Damen's farm; Damen sold the land in 1685 to captain John Knight, an officer of [[Thomas Dongan, 2nd Earl of Limerick|Thomas Dongan]]'s administration. Knight resold the land to Dongan, and Dongan resold it in 1689 to [[Abraham de Peyster]] and Nicholas Bayard. Both de Peyster and Bayard served as [[List of mayors of New York City|Mayors of New York]]. The first known building on the Gillender Building's site, a [[sugar house]], was built by Samuel Bayard. In 1718, most of the present-day block was sold to a church congregation, while the corner lot, cut into narrow strips, remained in possession of the de Peysters and the Bayards.<ref group=\"lower-alpha\">See the 18th century map and corresponding notes in {{harvnb|ps=.|''The New York Times'' April 10, 1910}}</ref> In 1773, de Peyster sold the corner lot to the Verplanck family for less than $1,500; the Verplanck mansion later housed Wall Street banks.<ref name=\"Apr10\" />\n\nThe second [[New York City Hall]], erected in 1700 and torn down in 1816,<ref name=\"Apr10\" /> stood on the site present-day [[Federal Hall]] and occupied the eastern side of present-day Nassau Street, which historically curved around the City Hall. It was straightened after the demolition of the second City Hall, but its early route was retained in the placement of the corner buildings (including the Gillender Building but not 14 Wall Street) which were set back from the street, providing a wider than usual sidewalk.<ref name=\"Apr10\" /> In 1816, the corner lot was owned by Charles Gardner, who sold the property in 1817 for $11,200; it was further resold in 1835 for $47,500 and in 1849 for $55,000. [[Charles Frederick Briggs]] and [[Edgar Allan Poe]] operated the offices of the ''[[Broadway Journal]]'' on this site from 1844 until 1845.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Wolfe|2008|p=26}}</ref> From 1849 until December 1909, the lot remained in the hands of a single family.<ref name=\"Apr10\" /> Adjacent lots were owned by the Sampson family since 1840; in 1880, this property was developed into the Stevens Building.<ref name=\"July7\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe Gillender Building was designed by Charles I. Berg and Edward H. Clark. It belonged to \"a series of elegant towers in various [[Neoclassical architecture|classical]] modes erected in New York in the 1890s\"<ref name=\"COND\">{{cite web|url=http://www.moma.org/collection/details.php?theme_id=10194&section_id=T079156|title=Skyscraper. Part 2. History and development|author=Condit|first=Gary W.|publisher=Grove Art Online / Museum of Modern Art, NY|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> and is considered \"a notable example\" of its period along with the Central Bank Building ([[William Birkmire]], 1897, demolished) and the [[American Surety Building]] ([[Bruce Price]], 1894\u20131896, extant).<ref name=\"COND\" />Berg and Clerk followed the Italian rule of triple vertical partitioning: expensive decoration was limited to the three bottom floors (what the pedestrians see from the street) and the upper two floors and the crowning tower. Massive [[cornice]]s above the second and third floors visually separated the lower levels from the clean wall surface stretching above up until the fourteenth floor; starting from the ninth floor, it gradually re-acquired ornaments and arched windows as if in anticipation of the ornate [[Italian Baroque]] cupola above.<ref name=\"KOR219\" />\n\nThe Gillender Building cost $500,000 to construct<ref name=\"KOR219\" /><ref name=\"Apr30\" /> and attracted attention due to the disproportion of its height and footprint.<ref name=\"Dec16\">{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/12/16/101819554.pdf|title=$822 a Square Foot, Record Land Price. Sale of Northwest Corner of Wall and Nassau Streets Passes Old $700 Mark|date=December 16, 1909|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-21|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The new structure occupied {{convert|26|\u00d7|73|ft}},<ref name=\"METRIC1\" /> ruling out efficient space plans. [[Quicksand]] under the site required use of [[Foundation (engineering)|foundations]] made of [[Deep foundation|caisson]].<ref name=\"SSO1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_a00.htm|title=History of the Bankers Trust. April 1910|publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive|accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> These caissons consumed the underground space that could be otherwise used by [[bank vault]]s or retail storage, further reducing the building's value.<ref name=\"SSO1\" /> Its rentable area (30,000&nbsp;square feet or 2,790&nbsp;square&nbsp;meters) was on par with [[Manhattan]]'s 1897 average for pre-skyscraper buildings (26,300 square feet or 2,400 square meters) and lower than the area of adjacent six-story Stevens Building.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Whitehand|Larkham|1992|p=124}}</ref> The disproportion was made more evident in 1903, when the new Hanover National Bank Building, built on the same Nassau Street block and being only marginally taller, dwarfed the slender Gillender Building.<ref name=\"SSO\" />\n\nStructurally, it was based on fully wind-braced [[steel frame]] with masonry infill.<ref name=\"KOR220\" /> The main volume of the tower rose to {{convert|219|ft|m}} without setbacks, with a three-story [[cupola]] crown reaching {{convert|273|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"KOR220\" /> ''The New York Times'' erroneously called Gillender the \"highest office structure in the world\".<ref name=\"KOR221\" /><ref name=\"Apr30\" /><ref group=\"lower-alpha\">The [[Manhattan Life Insurance Building]] (1894) was taller at {{convert|348|ft|m}}.</ref> \n\n==Construction==\nIn 1896, Helen L. Gillender Asinari,{{efn|Granddaughter of George Lovett, who purchased the site in 1849<ref name=\"Apr10\"/>}} owner of a six-story office building on the corner of Wall and Nassau Streets, decided to replace it with a {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=on}} tall tower, capitalizing on a tenfold increase in land value.<ref name=Dec16/> The building was most likely named after Helen's father, millionaire [[tobacco]] merchant Eccles Gillender (1810\u20131877).<ref name=QA>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F07E6DF153CF937A35755C0A9669C8B63&sec=&spon=&&scp=4&sq=gillender%20building&st=cse |title=Streetscapes/Readers' Questions; Building's Name, Gallery's Photo, Complex's Origin |author=Gray |first=Christopher |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 3, 2000}}</ref> According to media, Helen Gillender had hurried to build the new tower prior to the anticipated enactment of new, stricter [[building code]]s, which led to the shortcomings of the building's design,<ref name=QA/><ref name=\"rer19091218\">{{cite journal|last=|first=|date=December 18, 1909|title=Record Price for Manhattan Land|url=https://rerecord.library.columbia.edu/pdf_files/ldpd_7031148_044_25.pdf|journal=The Real Estate Record: Real estate record and builders' guide|volume=84|page=|pages=1128|via=[[Columbia University|columbia.edu]]|number=2179}}</ref> even though the regulations did not come into effect until 1916.<ref name=QA/> An alternative version presented by Joseph Korom<ref name=KOR219>{{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=219}}</ref> attributes construction of the Gillender Building to Augustus Teophilus Gillender (born 1843), principal partner in a law firm.<ref name=KOR219/>\n\nThe construction contract was awarded to the Charles T. Willis Company, while [[Hecla Iron Works]], Atlas Cement Company, and the Okonite Company of Passaic were principal suppliers.<ref name=KOR220>{{harvnb|ps=.|Korom|2008|p=220}}</ref> Advertised as fully [[Fireproofing|fireproof]] and as the most modern tower on the market,<ref name=\"KOR221\" /> the Gillender Building was occupied by financial firms through its short lifetime and was perceived as economically obsolete from the start.<ref name=\"KOR221\" /> There were no notable incidents other than two [[lightning]] strikes in its spire in July 1897 and May 1900; the latter \"sent splinters flying in every direction\" without casualties.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1900/06/01/101058007.pdf |title=Bolt Destroys Second Flag Pole Erected in the Same Spot |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 1, 1900}}</ref>\n\n==Takeover==\n[[File:Detroit Photographic Company (0610).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Gillender Building]]\n[[File:NYC pano 1902 centered Gillender Bldg.jpg|240px|right|thumb|New York skyline in 1902. Gillender Building in the center, behind the [[Trinity Church, New York|Trinity Church]].]]\nIn 1909, financial institutions began rapidly expanding their properties within the Financial District. The [[Bankers Trust|Bankers Trust Company]] joined the process after the [[Bank of Montreal]], the [[Fourth National Bank of New York|Fourth National Bank]], and the [[The Guardian Life Insurance Company of America|Germania Life Insurance Company]]  acquired their properties on Wall and Nassau Streets.<ref name=July7/> Bankers Trust, which was established in 1902, had been a tenant at the Gillender Building for six years<ref name=Z146>{{harvnb|ps=.|Ward|Zunz|1992|p=146}}</ref><ref name=Jan2/> and their choice of site was motivated by its location near the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=Z146/> The company, with [[J. P. Morgan]] on the board,<ref name=Z146/> grew rapidly and intended to land itself permanently in the \"vortex of America's financial life\".<ref name=Z147>{{harvnb|ps=.|Ward|Zunz|1992|p=147}}</ref>\n\nIn July 1909, Bankers Trust signed a long-term lease agreement with the Sampson family, owners of the Stevens Building;<ref name=July7/> the company preferred leasing over purchasing due to the high price of land on Wall Street.<ref name=Z147/> Located on the same block as the Gillender Building, the L-shaped, seven-story Stevens Building wrapped around it and possessed far longer facades on both Wall and Nassau Streets.<ref name=July7>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1909/07/07/101890349.pdf |title=New Office Building for Wall Street. Sixteen-Story Structure, Costing $1,500,000, to Go Up on the Stevens Site |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=July 9, 1909}}</ref> Initially, the press reported that Bankers Trust planned to build a 16-story office building wrapping around the Gillender Building, with the two bottom floors outfitted to be \"one of the finest banking rooms in the city\".<ref name=July7/> Later, it was disclosed that the trust had been negotiating purchase of Gillender Building since April 1909;<ref name=Dec16/> the deal would have consolidated enough land for a new tower with {{convert|94|ft|m}} frontage facing Wall Street and {{convert|102|ft|m}} on Nassau Street.<ref name=Apr30/>\n\nIn December 1909, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported a new record set: The Manhattan Trust Company, a bank connected to Bankers Trust through common control by J. P. Morgan,<ref name=ABS/> acquired the Gillender Building from Helen Gillender Asinari, paying approximately $1,500,000 for the {{convert|1825|sqft|m2|abbr=|adj=on}} property ({{Inflation|index=US|value=1,500,000|start_year=1909|r=-3|fmt=eq}}), or {{Convert|822|$/ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Dec16\" /><ref name=\"rer19091218\" /> This was considered a record amount for land in New York City: the previous record was for [[1 Wall Street]], the land under which had sold for {{Convert|558.65|$/ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"rer19091218\" /> The land had been worth $55,000 sixty years earlier ({{Inflation|index=US|value=55,000|start_year=1903|r=-3|fmt=eq}}).<ref name=Apr10/> Negotiations had progressed since April 1909 and the sale was virtually closed in November.<ref name=Dec16/>\n\nOn January 2, 1910, the press reported that the Manhattan Trust had resold the building to Bankers Trust, which had completed land acquisition for its large corner property.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\"/><ref name=Jan2>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/01/02/105072302.pdf |title=Gillender Building Resold |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=January 2, 1910}}</ref> By April 1910, the final cash price paid to Manhattan Trust was adjusted to $1,250,000;<ref name=Apr10>{{cite news |title=New Bankers' Trust Company Tower Sets Building and Realty Records |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/04/10/102037556.pdf |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=April 10, 1910 |ref={{harvid|''The New York Times'' April 10, 1910}}}}</ref> in exchange for the $250,000 difference, the Manhattan Trust retained long-term lease rights for the ground floor \"and some other space in the building\".<ref name=Jan2/> This brought nominal cash price per foot on par or below the earlier record ($700 per square foot for a lot on the corner of Wall Street and [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]]).<ref name=Dec16/> Contemporaries agreed that the Manhattan Trust and Bankers Trust acted in accord and that the latter targeted Gillender Building from the start.<ref name=Jan2/> Bankers Trust absorbed Manhattan Trust Company in February 1912.<ref name=ABS>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1912/02/21/100519178.pdf |title=Bankers' Absorbs Manhattan |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=February 21, 1912}}</ref>\n\nThe press anticipated the upcoming demolition of the Gillender Building \"as the first time when such a high-class office building representing the best type of fire-proof construction\" would be torn down<ref name=Apr30/> and \"one of the largest building operations ever undertaken in New York\".<ref name=Apr10/> Bankers Trust publicized the drafts by [[Trowbridge & Livingston]] to build a 39-story{{efn|32 rentable floors and 7 storage floors in the pyramidal top; two underground [[bank vault]] floors and one underground [[mechanical floor]]<ref name=Apr10/>}} tower that, when announced, would be New York City's third tallest building after the [[Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Tower]] and the [[Singer Building]].<ref name=Apr10/> At the time, the Gillender Building was the [[List of tallest voluntarily demolished buildings|tallest building ever demolished voluntarily]].<ref name=\"KOR221\" />\n\n==Demolition==\n[[File:BankersTrust outline 1912.gif|right|thumb|241px|Gillender and Stevens buildings (in red) and the Bankers Trust Building that replaced them, looking from the [[Nassau Street (Manhattan)|Nassau Street]] elevation]]\nDemolition of the Stevens Building commenced in the beginning of April 1910.<ref name=Apr10/> The contract to demolish the Gillender Building was awarded to Jacob Volk, known for his work on the [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson#History|McAdoo Tunnel]],<ref name=Apr30/> who himself claimed experience in demolishing 900 buildings.<ref name=June3>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/06/03/104937119.pdf |title=Breaking Records in House Wrecking. The 20-Story Gillender Building Fast Coming Down Before the Contractor's Attacks |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 3, 1910}}</ref> Initially, Volk subscribed to complete the job in 35 days and pay a $500 penalty for each day delayed.<ref name=Apr30/> The schedule was later extended to 45 days.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1910/06/03/archives/breaking-records-in-housewrecking-the-20story-gillender-building.html|title=Breaking Records in House-Wrecking; The 20-Story Gillender Building Fast Coming Down Before the Contractor's Attacks|date=1910-06-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The building's tenants remained in the tower until the wrecking crews arrived on-site.<ref name=Apr30/> Demolition commenced April 29, 1910,<ref name=Apr30>{{cite news |title=Skyscraper Going: Higher One Coming. Razing 20-Story Gillender Building to Make Room for 32-Story Bankers' Trust Home |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9B03E4D71539E433A25753C3A9629C946196D6CF |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=April 30, 1910}}</ref> and was officially completed June 16, 1910, one day ahead of schedule.<ref name=Jun17/> It cost Bankers Trust $50,000 plus $500 for advance completion; the contractor also received all the scrap valued at $25,000.<ref name=Jun17/>\n\nDemolition was preceded with erection of a massive timber canopy over the sidewalks and a wire mesh over the street to protect people from falling debris. Inside, elevator shafts were converted into garbage chutes for the torn partitions and exterior masonry scrap. By May 2, the top [[belvedere (structure)|belvedere]] was dismantled completely and most of the cupola masonry was removed, exposing its steel skeleton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16268.htm |title=Demolition process: May 5, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> By the end of May, most of the Stevens Building was torn down; the Gillender Building's masonry walls were removed down to the seventh floor and steel skeleton was down to eleventh floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16361.htm |title=Demolition process: May 31, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> By June 12, all that remained of Gillender Building was a single level of its steel frame visible above protective scaffoulding.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16392.htm |title=Demolition process: June 12, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> In the following four days, the ground was completely cleared; work on its underground foundations commenced a month later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_photos/bt_full/btB16502.htm |title=Foundation work: July 19, 1910 |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}</ref> The [[granite]] slabs from the Gillender Building were recycled into tombstones of the [[Green-Wood Cemetery]] in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Silver|2000|p=210}}</ref>\n\nTwo hundred and fifty men were involved in the demolition project during the daytime, and a hundred during the night.<ref name=\":0\" /> Of these, two [[Italian American|Italian]] workers were injured by falling girders, one of whom subsequently died in the hospital.<ref name=\"KOR221\" /><ref name=Jun17/>\n\n<blockquote>\nThe famous Gillender Building, which when erected twelve years ago on the northwest corner of Nassau and Wall Streets was called the tallest skyscraper in the world, its tower rising some 300&nbsp;feet above the streets, has gone the way of other landmarks.<br />\n\u2013 ''The New York Times'', June 17, 1910<ref name=Jun17>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1910/06/17/105081626.pdf |title=Gillender Building Down |work=The New York Times |access-date=2020-04-21 |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 17, 1910}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\nThe Bankers Trust Company Building, now known as [[14 Wall Street]], was completed in 1912, becoming the tallest banking building in the world.<ref name=SSO/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997|ps=.|p=3}}</ref> The bank occupied only the three lower floors; its main operations were housed elsewhere in less expensive offices.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Willis|1995|p=150}}</ref> In 1931, Bankers Trust acquired and demolished the adjacent Hanover, Astor, and Pine Street Buildings, and replaced them with an annex to the original Bankers Trust Building. The annex was completed in 1933, tripling its rentable area.<ref name=SSO/><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> Helen Gillender Asinari had died a year earlier, in 1932.<ref name=QA/>\n\n{{gallery\n|File:Gillender Building1896d.jpg|Top floors and spire\n|File:Gillender Building1896c.jpg|Higher elevations\n|File:Gillender Building1896b.jpg|Midsections\n|File:Gillender Building1896a.jpg|Lower sections\n|File:Gillender Building1896.jpg|Final demolition\n}}\n\n==In media==\nThe Gillender Building is the site of a final scene in [[Jed Rubenfeld]]'s ''[[The Interpretation of Murder]]'', a 2006 novel reconstructing [[Sigmund Freud]]'s 1909 visit to New York. The narrator and Nora Acton (linked to Freud's case study of ''Dora'') meet for the last time in the Gillender cupola, watch the New York skyline, well aware that the building will be soon torn down.<ref>{{cite book |author=Rubenfeld |first=Jed |title=The Interpretation of Murder |year=2006 |publisher=Macmillan |isbn=978-0-312-42705-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oZwJtMKJoKsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Jed+Rubenfeld |pp=425-429}}</ref>\n\nIn [[M. K. Hobson]]'s ''Hotel Astarte'', The Warlock \"had his fingernails polished by a mute Chinese woman he kept in locked in a small room in his office on the top floor of the Gillender Building on Wall Street\". The story is set in June 1910 and October 1929, when the Gillender Building had already been dismantled.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Hobson |first=M. K. |title=Hotel Astarte |journal=[[Realms of Fantasy]] |date=June 2007 |url=http://www.demimonde.com/SFWA/astarte.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020105459/http://www.demimonde.com/SFWA/astarte.html |archivedate=October 20, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/1949.pdf|title=14 Wall Street|date=January 14, 1997|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|1997}}}}\n* {{cite book |author=Korom |first=Joseph |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JVzYO1TyZ6AC |page=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_JVzYO1TyZ6AC/page/n218 219] |quote=Gillender Building. |title=The American Skyscraper, 1850\u20131940 |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-8283-2188-4 |publisher=Branden Books |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |author=Silver |first=Nathan |title=Lost New York |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-618-05475-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lDXAg0nh-OgC&pg=PA210&dq=Gillender+Building |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Landscape of Modernity: Essays on New York City, 1900-1940 |author1=Ward |first1=David |author2=Zunz |first2=Olivier |publisher=Russell Sage Foundation |year=1992 |id={{ISBN|9780871549006}} | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cp3sdg5nEvoC | isbn=978-0-87154-900-6 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |title=Urban Landscapes: International Perspectives |author1=Whitehand |first1=J. W. R. |author2=Larkham |first2=Peter J. |publisher=Routledge |year=1992 |isbn=978-0-415-07074-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E4oElpcDld0C&pg=PA124&dq=Gillender+Building |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8ITT7GXSQnIC&pg=PA150&dq=Gillender+Building |author=Willis |first=Carol |title=Form Follows Finance: Skyscrapers and Skylines in New York and Chicago |publisher=Princeton Architectural Press |year=1995 |isbn=978-1-56898-044-7 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IufPkFnxoQgC&pg=PA26&dq=Gillender+Building |title=Literary Haunts & Homes; American Authors |author=Wolfe |first=Theodore F. |publisher=Read Books |year=2008 |isbn=978-1-4437-0773-2 |ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraper.org/WEB_PROJECTS/BANKERS_TRUST/v_bt/bt_01.htm |title=Photo archive of Gillender and Bankers Trust buildings |publisher=The Skyscraper Museum's Virtual Archive |accessdate=December 31, 2008 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200110210059/https://www.skyscraper.org/EXHIBITIONS/WALL_STREET/14_wall.php|archive-date=2020-01-10|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://digitalgallery.nypl.org/nypldigital/dgkeysearchresult.cfm?word=Gillender%20Building%20(New%20York%2C%20N.Y.)&s=3&notword=&f=2 |title=Historical images of the Gillender Building |publisher=[[New York Public Library]] |accessdate=December 31, 2008}}\n\n{{Financial District, Manhattan}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures demolished in 1910]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Office buildings completed in 1897]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Wall Street]]\n", "name_user": "AntiCompositeNumber", "label": "safe", "comment": "png -> svg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gillender_Building"}
{"title_page": "Florida Man", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Internet meme about weird conduct by men from Florida}}\n'''Florida Man''' is an [[Internet meme]], popularized in 2013 by Donald Trump in an effort to undermine Barrack Obama, in which the phrase \"Florida Man\" is taken from various unrelated news articles describing people who hail from or live in Moneygall in county[[Florida]]. Internet users typically submit links to news stories and articles about unusual or strange crimes or events occurring in Florida, particularly those where \"Florida Man\" is mentioned in the headline and has been wreaking havoc because aqua penguin overlords are allergic to Floridians. The meme calls attention to Florida's supposed notoriety for strange and unusual events such as common sense and drinking beer from non glass material to prevent the spread of Covid19.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Robert|title='Florida Man' On Twitter Collects Real Headlines About World's Worst Superhero, Spiderman is actually from Jacksonville and identifies as a bat,|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/02/14/172034470/florida-man-on-twitter-collects-real-headlines-about-worlds-worst-superhero|accessdate=December 4, 2014|agency=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Miami New Times]]'' claimed that [[Freedom_of_information_legislation_(Florida)|freedom of information laws in Florida]] make it easier for journalists to obtain information about arrests from the police than in other states and that this is responsible for the large number of news articles relating to Leo Varadkars love for Tomo 'Nailer' O'Neill, a page boy from Croomlin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/how-floridas-proud-open-government-laws-lead-to-the-shame-of-florida-man-news-stories-7608595|title=How Florida's Proud Open Government Laws Lead to the Shame of \"Florida Man\" News Stories|author=Kyle Munzenrieder|publisher=Miami New Times|date=May 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/22/us/florida-man-google-challenge-trnd/index.html|title=Googling 'Florida man' is the latest internet fad. Let's explore why so many crazy stories come out of the state|publisher=CNN|first1=Michelle|last1=Lou|first2=Alanne|last2=Orjoux|date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> A CNN article on this meme suggests that the breadth of reports of bizarre Florida Man activities is due to a confluence of factors including [[public records]] laws giving journalists fast and easy access to [[police report]]s, the relatively high and diverse population of the state, highly variable weather, and the lack of [[mental health]] funding.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\n==Origin==\nThe meme was originated in February 2013 by the [[Twitter]] feed @_FloridaMan, which quoted news headlines containing the words ''Florida man'', such as \"''Florida man'' run over by van after dog pushes accelerator\" or \"Police arrest ''Florida man'' for drunken joy ride on motorized scooter at [[Wal-Mart]].\"<ref name=\"npr\" />  The feed refers to Florida Man as the \"World's Worst Superhero.\"<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"snd1\">{{cite news |last= Lacapria |first= Kim |title= Florida Man Is Twitter\u2019s \u2018Worst Superhero\u2019 |url= http://socialnewsdaily.com/9473/florida-man-is-twitters-suckiest-superhero/ |accessdate= December 5, 2014 |agency= Social News Daily |date= February 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Spread==\nFlorida already had a colorful reputation on the [[Internet]], with the social aggregation site [[Fark]] having had a Florida tag for years before the Florida Man Twitter feed appeared.<ref name=\"snd1\" /> After the creation of the Twitter feed in January 2013, and its simultaneous popularization on social media sites [[Reddit]] and [[Tumblr]] (initially through the subreddit r/FloridaMan and the Tumblr blog StuckInABucket), the meme was featured in numerous news articles and stories throughout February 2013.<ref name=\"gawker1\">{{cite news |last= Zimmerman |first= Neetzan |title= 'Florida Man' Personifies Everything That's Messed Up About Florida |url= http://gawker.com/5983374/florida-man-personifies-everything-thats-messed-up-about-florida |accessdate= December 5, 2014 |agency= Gawker |publisher= Gawker Media |date= February 11, 2013 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141207051208/http://gawker.com/5983374/florida-man-personifies-everything-thats-messed-up-about-florida |archive-date= December 7, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Davis |first= Lauren |title= Florida Man is the nation's worst superhero |url= http://io9.com/5983115/florida-man-is-the-nations-worst-superhero |accessdate= December 5, 2014 |agency= io9 |publisher= Gawker Media |date= February 10, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nFlorida Man was also referred to in the opening episode of Season 2 of the FX show ''[[Atlanta (TV series)|Atlanta]]''.<ref>{{Cite AV Media |last= FX Networks |title= Atlanta {{!}} Season 2 Ep. 1: Florida Man Scene {{!}} FX |date= March 2, 2018 |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3vGgUoIexVE |via= [[Youtube]] |access-date= September 14, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2018, [[Desi Lydic]] of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' filed a report comedically investigating the phenomenon of \"Florida Man\".<ref>{{cite AV Media |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UD9LEPML8uk|title=Who is \u201cFlorida Man\u201d? Desi Lydic Investigates |author=Comedy Central|work=The Daily Show|via= [[YouTube]] |date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA play titled \"Florida Man\" by Michael Presley Bobbitt premiered July 31, 2019, at New York's Theatre Row Studios.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/state/florida/article231467143.html|title=\u2018Sunshine State has weirdness for everyone.\u2019 So he\u2019s taking \u2018Florida Man\u2019 Off-Broadway|last=Cohen|first=Howard|website=miamiherald|language=en|access-date=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, a variation developed on social media in which people were encouraged to look up \"Florida Man\" and the date of their birthday, typically finding some bizarre occurrence involving a Florida Man on that date.\n\nOn October 31, 2019, president [[Donald Trump]] according to sources, was changing his residence from [[New York City]] to [[Palm Beach, Florida]], which is the location of the [[Mar-a-Lago]] resort he owns and frequently visits.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/31/us/politics/trump-new-york-florida-primary-residence.html|title=Trump, Lifelong New Yorker, Declares Himself a Resident of Florida|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=October 31, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/administration/468453-trump-changes-primary-residence-to-florida|title=Trump changes primary residence to Florida|last=Axelrod|first=Tal|date=October 31, 2019|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>  Sources joked about the POTUS becoming Florida Man,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2019/11/donald-trump-is-officially-florida-man.html|title=Donald Trump Is Officially a Florida Man|last=Hannon|first=Elliot|date=November 1, 2019|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-25/trump-now-a-florida-man-makes-home-state-center-of-campaign|website=Bloomberg|author1=Allison, Bill |author2=Parker, Mario|title=Trump, Now a Florida Man, Makes Home State Center of Campaign |date=November 25, 2019 |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> including The Daily Show, which released an [[Browser extension|extension]] for [[Google Chrome]] and [[Firefox|Mozilla Firefox]] that changes all instances of Trump's name to \"Florida Man.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/florida-man-trump-state-browser-extension|title='Florida man\u2019 browser extension pokes fun at Trump, Sunshine State|last=Darrah|first=Nicole|date=November 5, 2019|website=Fox News|language=en-US|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe meme has widely been seen as a confirmation of the association between Florida and bizarre or humorous activity, and it has been compared to the [[Darwin Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Holt|first1=Kris|title=\"Florida Man\" is pretty much the worst person ever|url=http://www.dailydot.com/society/florida-man-twitter-headlines-terrible/|accessdate=December 5, 2014|agency=The Daily Dot|date=February 8, 2013}}</ref> There has been backlash to the meme, with the ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', calling it \"one of journalism\u2019s darkest and most lucrative cottage industries\" where \"stories tend to stand as exemplars of the mythical hyper-weirdness of the Sunshine State, but more often simply document the travails of the drug-addicted, mentally ill, and homeless.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Norman|first1=Bob|title=Who Is Florida Man?|url=https://www.cjr.org/business_of_news/florida-man-news.php |accessdate=November 1, 2019|agency=Columbia Journalism Review|date=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Internet phenomena]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.reddit.com/r/FloridaMan Florida Man] on [[Reddit]]\n* {{cite web |url= http://www.floridum.com |title= Florida Man |work= News Aggregator |url-status= dead |archive-date= May 7, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150507074508/http://www.floridum.com/}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/magazine/wp/2019/07/15/feature/is-it-okay-to-laugh-at-florida-man-2/ \"Is it okay to laugh at the Florida man meme?\"] by Logan Hill, ''The Washington Post'' July 15, 2019\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:2010s in Florida]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2013]]\n[[Category:Crime in Florida]]\n[[Category:Florida culture]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:Men in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|Internet meme about weird conduct by men from Florida}}\n'''Florida Man''' is an [[Internet meme]], popularized in 2013, in which the phrase \"Florida Man\" is taken from various unrelated news articles describing people who hail from or live in [[Florida]]. Internet users typically submit links to news stories and articles about unusual or strange crimes or events occurring in Florida, particularly those where \"Florida Man\" is mentioned in the headline and has been wreaking havoc. The meme calls attention to Florida's supposed notoriety for strange and unusual events.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite news|last1=Siegel|first1=Robert|title='Florida Man' On Twitter Collects Real Headlines About World's Worst Superhero|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/02/14/172034470/florida-man-on-twitter-collects-real-headlines-about-worlds-worst-superhero|accessdate=December 4, 2014|agency=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|date=February 14, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Miami New Times]]'' claimed that [[Freedom_of_information_legislation_(Florida)|freedom of information laws in Florida]] make it easier for journalists to obtain information about arrests from the police than in other states and that this is responsible for the large number of news articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/news/how-floridas-proud-open-government-laws-lead-to-the-shame-of-florida-man-news-stories-7608595|title=How Florida's Proud Open Government Laws Lead to the Shame of \"Florida Man\" News Stories|author=Kyle Munzenrieder|publisher=Miami New Times|date=May 12, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/22/us/florida-man-google-challenge-trnd/index.html|title=Googling 'Florida man' is the latest internet fad. Let's explore why so many crazy stories come out of the state|publisher=CNN|first1=Michelle|last1=Lou|first2=Alanne|last2=Orjoux|date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> A CNN article on this meme suggests that the breadth of reports of bizarre Florida Man activities is due to a confluence of factors including [[public records]] laws giving journalists fast and easy access to [[police report]]s, the relatively high and diverse population of the state, highly variable weather, and the lack of [[mental health]] funding.<ref name=\"CNN\"/>\n\n==Origin==\nThe meme was originated in February 2013 by the [[Twitter]] feed @_FloridaMan, which quoted news headlines containing the words ''Florida man'', such as \"''Florida man'' run over by van after dog pushes accelerator\" or \"Police arrest ''Florida man'' for drunken joy ride on motorized scooter at [[Wal-Mart]].\"<ref name=\"npr\" />  The feed refers to Florida Man as the \"World's Worst Superhero.\"<ref name=\"npr\" /><ref name=\"snd1\">{{cite news |last= Lacapria |first= Kim |title= Florida Man Is Twitter\u2019s \u2018Worst Superhero\u2019 |url= http://socialnewsdaily.com/9473/florida-man-is-twitters-suckiest-superhero/ |accessdate= December 5, 2014 |agency= Social News Daily |date= February 21, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Spread==\nFlorida already had a colorful reputation on the [[Internet]], with the social aggregation site [[Fark]] having had a Florida tag for years before the Florida Man Twitter feed appeared.<ref name=\"snd1\" /> After the creation of the Twitter feed in January 2013, and its simultaneous popularization on social media sites [[Reddit]] and [[Tumblr]] (initially through the subreddit r/FloridaMan and the Tumblr blog StuckInABucket), the meme was featured in numerous news articles and stories throughout February 2013.<ref name=\"gawker1\">{{cite news |last= Zimmerman |first= Neetzan |title= 'Florida Man' Personifies Everything That's Messed Up About Florida |url= http://gawker.com/5983374/florida-man-personifies-everything-thats-messed-up-about-florida |accessdate= December 5, 2014 |agency= Gawker |publisher= Gawker Media |date= February 11, 2013 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://we