oord|32.88|N|74.92|E|}}.<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/12/Pulwama.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc - Pulwama]</ref> It has an average elevation of {{Convert|1630|m|abbr=on}}.\n\n==Education==\nPulwama is home to various educational institutions including\n*[[Government Degree College boys, Pulwama|Government Degree College boys  ]]\n*Islamic University Awantipora\n*AIIMS Medical College Pulwama\n*[[Womens college Pulwama]]\n*Skylark Paramedical college\n*Phoenix Paramedical College\n*District Hospital(Medical college Pulwama)\n*old district hospital\n*Dolphin paramedical college\n*KCEF law college\n*Maxwell college of education\n*Noorani paramedical college\n\n==Urban Area==\nPulwama city is divided into 35 wards making it largest muncipality in District followed by Pampore.Due to its dense congestion city has been divided into Old town and New town.Most of the government offices are located at Old town and most educational institutes are located in New town.Pulwama is home to various industrial areas such ss IGC Lassiopra,IGC Khrew and Industrial Estate Chatapora holds the states largest industries.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in Pulwama district (2011)\n|label1 = [[Islam]]\n|value1 = 98.59\n|color1 = Green\n|label2 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value2 = 1.63\n|color2 = Orange\n|label3 = [[Sikhism]]\n|value3 = 0.34\n|color3 = Yellow\n|label4 = [[Christianity]]\n|value4 = 0.17\n|color4 = Blue\n|label5 = [[Buddhism]]\n|value5 = 0.02\n|color5 = Gold\n|label6 = [[Jainism]]\n|value6 = 0.01\n|color6 = Maroon\n|label7 = Not Stated\n|value7 = 0.24\n|color7 = Grey\n}}\n\nAccording to [[2011 Census of India]], Pulwama had a population of 152,000 of which 74,070 are males while 78,370 are females. Population of Children with age of 0-6 is 3167 which is 17.17 % of total population of Pulwama. [[Human sex ratio|Female Sex Ratio]] is of 831 against state average of 889. Moreover Child Sex Ratio in Pulwama is around 718 compared to Jammu and Kashmir state average of 862. Literacy rate of Pulwama city is 91.18 % higher than state average of 67.16 %.<ref name=\"census2011.co.in\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/town/800026-pulwama-jammu-and-kashmir.html |title=Pulwama Population Census 2011 - 2019 |work=census2011.co.in |date= |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nMajority of the population follows [[Islam]], which consist of 98.59% of total population of town. Other minority religions are [[Hindu]] 1.63%, [[Sikh]] 0.34%, [[Christianity]] 0.17%, [[Buddhism]] 0.02% and [[Jain]]s are 0.01%. 0.24% people not stated their religion.<ref name=\"census2011.co.in\"/>\n\n==Other cities and towns==\n* [[Anantnag]]\n* [[Budgam]]\n* [[Pampore]]\n* [[Srinagar]]\n* [[Shopian]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Municipalities of Jammu and Kashmir}}\n{{Jammu and Kashmir topics}}\n{{Municipalities of Jammu and Kashmir}}\n{{Kashmir Valley}}\n[[Category:Cities and towns in India]]\n", "name_user": "FlyJet777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDemographics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulwama"}
{"title_page": "Gran Canaria", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish island of the Canary Islands}}\n{{redirect|Grand Canary|the novel by A. J. Cronin|Grand Canary (novel)|the film adaptation of the novel|Grand Canary (film)}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name                             = Gran Canaria\n|image_name                       = Gran Canaria wildfire (48590670831).jpg\n|image_caption                    =\n|map_image                        = File:Spain Canary Islands location map Gran Canaria.svg\n|native_name                      = \n|native_name_link                 =\n|location                         = [[Atlantic Ocean]]\n|coordinates                      = {{coord|27|58|N|15|36|W|display=it}}\n|archipelago                      = \n|total_islands                    = \n|major_islands                    = \n|area_km2                         = 1560.11\n|highest_mount                    = {{interlanguage link|Morro de la Agujereada|es}}\n| elevation_m                      = 1949\n| country_admin_divisions         = [[Spain]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1 = Region\n| country_admin_divisions_1       = [[Macaronesia]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2 = [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Community]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2       = [[Canary Islands]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_3 = [[Provinces of Spain|Province]]\n| country_admin_divisions_3       = [[Province of Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n|country_largest_city             = [[Las Palmas]]\n|country_largest_city_population  = 379,925\n|population                       = 851,231<ref>[http://www.ine.es/jaxi/tabla.do?path=/t20/e260/a2010/l0/&file=is01.px&type=pcaxis&L=0 Population referred to the January 1, 2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131145315/https://boe.es/boe/dias/2018/12/29/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-18083.pdf |date=31 January 2019 }}</ref>\n|population_as_of                 = 2019\n|density_km2                      = 545.6\n|ethnic_groups                    =\n}}\n[[File:Flag of Gran Canaria.svg|thumb|250px|Flag of Gran Canaria.]]\n'''Gran Canaria''' ({{IPAc-en|uk|\u02cc|\u0261|r|\u00e6|n|_|k|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u025b\u0259r|i|\u0259|,_|-|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0r|-}}, {{IPAc-en|us|\u02cc|\u0261|r|\u0251\u02d0|n|_|k|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0r|i|\u0259|,_|-|\u02c8|n|\u025b\u0259r|-}};<ref>\n{{cite book|last=Wells|first=John C.|year=2008|title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary|edition=3rd|publisher=Longman|isbn=978-1-4058-8118-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Roach|first=Peter|year=2011|title=Cambridge English Pronouncing Dictionary|edition=18th|place=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-15253-2}}</ref> {{IPA-es|\u0261\u027ea\u014b ka\u02c8na\u027eja}}), also '''Grand Canary Island''', is the second most populous of the [[Canary Islands]], an [[archipelago]] off the Atlantic coast of [[Northwest Africa]] which is part of [[Spain]]. {{As of|2019}} the island had a population of {{formatnum:851231}} that constitutes approximately 40% of the population of the archipelago. \n\nGran Canaria is located in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] about {{convert|150|km}} off the northwestern coast of [[Africa]] and about {{convert|1350|km|abbr=on}} from [[Europe]].<ref>[http://www.laspalmasgc.es/lpgc/idcplg?IdcService=SS_GET_PAGE&nodeId=137 Situaci\u00f3n y Clima. Ayuntamiento de Las Palmas de Gran Canaria.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629205852/http://www.laspalmasgc.es/lpgc/idcplg?IdcService=SS_GET_PAGE&nodeId=137 |date=2010-06-29 }}</ref> With an area of {{formatnum:1560}} km<sup>2</sup> ({{formatnum:602}} sq. mi)<ref>[http://www.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas.html ISTAC: ''Estad\u00edsticas de la Comunidad Aut\u00f3noma de Canarias''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114080725/http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas.html |date=2010-11-14 }} (Statistics for the Canaries) on ''gobiernodecanarias.org''.</ref> and an altitude of {{convert|1956|m|abbr=on}} at [[Morro de la Agujereada]], Gran Canaria is the third largest island of the archipelago in both area and altitude. Gran Canaria is also the third most populated island in Spain after [[Tenerife]] and [[Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boe.es/boe/dias/2018/12/29/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-18083.pdf|title=Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado|date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn [[Classical antiquity|antiquity]], Gran Canaria was populated by the North African [[Guanches|Canarii]], who may have arrived as early as 500 BC. The Canarii called the island '''Tamar\u00e1n''' ('land of the brave\").\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages|medieval period]], after over a century of European incursions and attempts at conquest, the island was conquered on April 29, 1483 by the [[Crown of Castile]], under [[Isabella I of Castile|Queen Isabella I]]. The conquest succeeded after a campaign that lasted five years, and it was an important step towards the expansion of the unified Spain.\n\nThe capital city of [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]] was founded on June 24, 1478, under the name \"Real de Las Palmas\", by [[Juan Rej\u00f3n]], head of the invading [[Crown of Castile|Castilian]] army. In 1492, [[Christopher Columbus]] anchored in the [[Port of Las Palmas]] (and spent some time on the island) on his first trip to the Americas. Las Palmas de Gran Canaria is, jointly with [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]], the capital of the [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of the Canary Islands.\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Gc01.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Topography of Gran Canaria]]\n[[File:Gran Canaria 3D version1.gif|thumb|left|Gran Canaria 3D]]\n\nGran Canaria is located in the [[Canary Islands]] archipelago southeast of [[Tenerife]] and west of [[Fuerteventura]]. The island is of [[volcano|volcanic]] origin, mostly made of [[fissure vent]]s. It has a round shape, with a diameter of approximately {{convert|50|km|abbr=on}} and a surface area of {{convert|1,560|km2|abbr=on}}. Gran Canaria's maximum elevation is {{convert|1,956|m}} at [[Morro de la Agujereada]], although the nearby [[Pico de las Nieves]] has traditionally been considered the island's tallest peak.\n\n=== Geology ===\nAbout 80% of the volume of the island was formed during the [[Miocene]] period eruptions, between 14 and 9 million years ago. This is called the \"Old Cycle\" and is estimated to have lasted some 200,000 years and have emitted about {{convert|1000|km3|abbr=on}}, mostly of fissural [[alkali basalt]]. This cycle continued with the emission of [[trachyte]]s, [[phonolite]]s and [[peralkaline]] rocks. This period was followed by one of erosion, which lasted some 4 million years.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes\">Ara\u00f1a, V and Carracedo, J.C: ''Canarian Volcanoes'', Volume 3: Gran Canaria, pp. 8, 24. Editorial Rueda, Madrid, 1978.</ref>\n\nA second cycle of volcanic eruptions, known as the \"Roque Nublo cycle\", took place between 4.5 and 3.4 million years ago. This shorter cycle emitted about {{convert|100|km3|abbr=on}}. Most of the inland peaks were formed by erosion from these materials. This period also started with fissural basalts, but ended with violent eruptions of [[pyroclastic flows]]. Some phonolitic features, like the Risco Blanco, were also formed in its last stages.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes\"/>\n\nThe third or recent cycle is held to have started some 2.8 million years ago and is considered to be still active. The last eruptions are held to have occurred some 3,500 years ago.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes\"/>\n\nThe changes in volume and, therefore, weight of the island have also caused the island to rise above the previous sea level during erosive periods and to sink during eruptive periods. Some of these \"fossil beaches\" can be seen in the cliff faces of the more eroded northern coast.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes_sealevel\">Oscillations of up to {{convert|400|m|ft|abbr=on}} in the level corresponding to sea level have occurred in geological history. The highest point known is in the Bay of El Confital, Las Palmas ({{convert|130|m|ft|disp=comma|abbr=on}} above current sea level) while subaerial materials have been extracted from a well at {{convert|230|m|ft|abbr=on}} below sea level in the area of La Aldea. Ara\u00f1a, V and Carracedo, J.C: ''Canarian Volcanoes'', Volume 3: Gran Canaria, pp. 13. Editorial Rueda, Madrid, 1978.</ref>\n{{clear|left}}\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Nature of Gran Canaria 2016 03.jpg|Nature of Gran Canaria along the eastern shore in 2016\nFile:Nature of Gran Canaria 2016 1.jpg|Nature of Gran Canaria along the southeastern shore in 2016\n</gallery>\n\n== Vegetation ==\n\nUntil the conquest, Gran Canaria had extensive forests, but then suffered extensive [[deforestation]]<ref name=\"benmagec.org\">[http://www.benmagec.org/turcon/pdf/grancanaria/agy2ocr.pdf Reforestaci\u00f3n de las cumbres de Gran Canaria]</ref> as a result of continuous logging, land divisions and other intensive uses. This reduced the forest cover to just {{convert|56,000|hectare}},<ref name=\"benmagec.org\"/> making the island the most deforested of the Canary Islands.<ref>[http://www.eldiario.es/canariasahora/sociedad/reforestar-Gran-Canaria_0_383211903.html \u201cCon lo que cuesta un Jumbo se puede reforestar toda Gran Canaria\u201d]</ref> However, in the twentieth century reforestation of the ridge of the island was begun, recovering some of the lost forest mass. Much of the summit of the island is forested mostly due to [[reforestation]].<ref name=\"benmagec.org\"/>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Municipios y zonas de Gran Canaria.svg|thumb|Municipalities of Gran Canaria]]\nGran Canaria is in the [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of the [[Canary Islands]] (''Islas Canarias''). It lies within the [[Province of Las Palmas]], a [[Provinces of Spain|Spanish province]] which consists of the eastern part of the Canary Islands community. [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]] is the provincial capital, one of the two capitals of the Canary Islands along with [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref name=\"government\">{{cite web |title=Government of Gran Canaria |url=http://www.spain-grancanaria.com/en/discover/facts/government.html |website=www.spain-grancanaria.com |accessdate=21 November 2018 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nThe island of Gran Canaria is governed by the [[Cabildo insular|Cabildo insular de Gran Canaria]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Historia del Cabildo - Cabildo de Gran Canaria |url=http://cabildo.grancanaria.com/historia-del-cabildo |website=cabildo.grancanaria.com |accessdate=21 November 2018 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Gran Canaria Island itself is divided into twenty-one smaller [[List of municipalities in Las Palmas|municipalities]]:<ref name=\"government\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!Area<br />(km<sup>2</sup>)\n!Population<br />(2001)<ref>Census at 1 November 2001: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Madrid.</ref>\n!Population<br />(2011)<ref>Census at 1 November 2011: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Madrid.</ref>\n!Population<br />(2019)<ref>Estimate at 1 January 2019: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Madrid.</ref>\n|-\n|[[Agaete]]\n| align=\"right\" |45.50\n| align=\"right\" |5,202\n| align=\"right\" |5,735\n| align=\"right\" |5,586\n|-\n|[[Ag\u00fcimes]]\n| align=\"right\" |79.28\n| align=\"right\" |20,124\n| align=\"right\" |29,641\n| align=\"right\" |31,619\n|-\n|[[Artenara, Las Palmas|Artenara]]\n| align=\"right\" |66.70\n| align=\"right\" |1,319\n| align=\"right\" |1,252\n| align=\"right\" |1,069\n|-\n|[[Arucas, Las Palmas|Arucas]]\n| align=\"right\" |33.01\n| align=\"right\" |32,466\n| align=\"right\" |36,771\n| align=\"right\" |38,138\n|-\n|[[Firgas, Las Palmas|Firgas]]\n| align=\"right\" |15.77\n| align=\"right\" |6,865\n| align=\"right\" |7,606\n| align=\"right\" |7,455\n|-\n|[[G\u00e1ldar, Las Palmas|G\u00e1ldar]]\n| align=\"right\" |61.59\n| align=\"right\" |22,154\n| align=\"right\" |24,358\n| align=\"right\" |24,242\n|-\n|[[Ingenio, Las Palmas|Ingenio]]\n| align=\"right\" |38.15\n| align=\"right\" |24,439\n| align=\"right\" |30,022\n| align=\"right\" |31,321\n|-\n|[[Mog\u00e1n]]\n| align=\"right\" |172.44\n| align=\"right\" |12,444\n| align=\"right\" |22,847\n| align=\"right\" |20,072\n|-\n|[[Moya, Las Palmas|Moya]]\n| align=\"right\" |31.87\n| align=\"right\" |8,137\n| align=\"right\" |8,043\n| align=\"right\" |7,696\n|-\n|[[La Aldea de San Nicol\u00e1s]]\n| align=\"right\" |123.58\n| align=\"right\" |7,668\n| align=\"right\" |8,522\n| align=\"right\" |7,504\n|-\n|[[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]\n| align=\"right\" |100.55\n| align=\"right\" |354,863\n| align=\"right\" |381,271\n| align=\"right\" |379,925\n|-\n|[[San Bartolom\u00e9 de Tirajana]]\n| align=\"right\" |333.13\n| align=\"right\" |34,515\n| align=\"right\" |53,440\n| align=\"right\" |53,443\n|-\n|[[Santa Br\u00edgida, Las Palmas|Santa Br\u00edgida]]\n| align=\"right\" |23.81\n| align=\"right\" |17,598\n| align=\"right\" |18,878\n| align=\"right\" |18,263\n|-\n|[[Santa Luc\u00eda de Tirajana]]\n| align=\"right\" |61.56\n| align=\"right\" |47,652\n| align=\"right\" |66,725\n| align=\"right\" |73,328\n|-\n|[[Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria]]\n| align=\"right\" |42.59\n| align=\"right\" |13,893\n| align=\"right\" |14,149\n| align=\"right\" |13,850\n|-\n|[[Tejeda, Las Palmas|Tejeda]]\n| align=\"right\" |103.30\n| align=\"right\" |2,400\n| align=\"right\" |2,136\n| align=\"right\" |1,909\n|-\n|[[Telde, Las Palmas|Telde]]\n| align=\"right\" |102.43\n| align=\"right\" |87,949\n| align=\"right\" |101,080\n| align=\"right\" |102,647\n|-\n|[[Teror, Las Palmas|Teror]]\n| align=\"right\" |25.70\n| align=\"right\" |12,042\n| align=\"right\" |12,857\n| align=\"right\" |12,519\n|-\n|[[Valleseco, Las Palmas|Valleseco]]\n| align=\"right\" |22.11\n| align=\"right\" |3,949\n| align=\"right\" |3,896\n| align=\"right\" |3,749\n|-\n|[[Valsequillo de Gran Canaria]]\n| align=\"right\" |39.15\n| align=\"right\" |7,964\n| align=\"right\" |9,118\n| align=\"right\" |9,340\n|-\n|[[Vega de San Mateo]]\n| align=\"right\" |37.89\n| align=\"right\" |6,979\n| align=\"right\" |7,737\n| align=\"right\" |7,556\n|-\n|''Totals''\n| align=\"right\" |''1,560.11''\n| align=\"right\" |''730,622''\n| align=\"right\" |''846,084''\n| align=\"right\" |''851,231''\n|-\n|}\n\nThe island has a population at the start of 2019 of 851,231 with 379,925 of those in the capital city of [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]. Gran Canaria is the second most populous island of the Canary Islands, after [[Tenerife]].<ref>[http://www.ine.es/jaxi/tabla.do?path=/t20/e260/a2010/l0/&file=is01.px&type=pcaxis&L=0 Population referred to the January 1, 2018] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131145315/https://boe.es/boe/dias/2018/12/29/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-18083.pdf |date=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n===Roads===\n[[File:Gran Canaria GC-1 Bridge over Barranco de Tauro 9558.jpg|thumb|''Autopistas'' in Gran Canaria provide rapid road transport around the coast]]\n[[File:Guaguas Gran Canaria Sur (30956433245).jpg|thumb|A Gran Canaria bus]]\n[[File:Gran Canaria Airport 2015-12-16 a.jpg|thumb|Gran Canaria Airport]]\n[[File:Agaete, Gran Canaria D81 8134 (32250537964).jpg|thumb|The Tenerife catamaran ferry]]\nGran Canaria has roads encircling the whole island and extending into the mountain areas. In the late 20th century, its dual carriageway, among the first in the Canary Islands, were opened and run around Las Palmas de Gran Canaria, and were later extended to the north coast and the airport and subsequently to the south coast in response to increased tourist traffic. The only highway of Gran Canaria are [[GC1 (Gran Canaria)|GC1]]. Dual carriageway is [[GC2 (Gran Canaria)|GC2]], and [[GC31 (Gran Canaria)|GC31]], [[GC4 (Gran Canaria)|GC4]] and [[GC5 (Gran Canaria)|GC5]]. The western and the north-western parts, with the fewest inhabitants, are linked only with main roads.\n\n===Buses===\nPublic transport around Gran Canaria is provided by an extensive bus network, known in the local dialect as ''[[wiktionary:guagua|guaguas]]''. The ''[[Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria]]'' (Gran Canaria Transport Authority, TGC) manages the network and operates a number of bus stations across the island, including San Telmo and Santa Catalina bus stations in Las Palmas, Maspalomas and Galdar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Intercambiadores y Paradas Preferentes {{!}} Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria |url=http://www.autgc.org/transporte-en-gc/intercambiadores-y-paradas-preferentes |website=www.autgc.org |publisher=Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria|language=es}}</ref> Bus tickets may be purchased with cash, and AUTGC also operates a [[Contactless smart card|contactless]] [[electronic ticket]] called the TransGC Card, which is valid across the whole network.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tarjeta TransGC |url=http://www.autgc.org/transporte-en-gc/tarjeta-transgc |website=www.autgc.org |publisher=Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=es}}</ref> \n\nInter-urban bus services across the island are operated by the Global bus company.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gran Canaria - Global SU |url=https://www.guaguasglobal.com/en/lineas-horarios/informacion-turistica/gran-canaria/ |website=Global SU |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=L\u00edneas y Horarios |url=https://www.guaguasglobal.com/lineas-horarios/ |website=Global SU |accessdate=30 January 2019 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Global was created in 2000 after the merger of two bus companies, Utinsa (which operated in the north of the island) and Salcai (the bus operator for the south).<ref>{{cite web |title=La Empresa: Global |url=https://www.guaguasglobal.com/empresa/ |website=Global SU |accessdate=30 January 2019 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Local bus services in Las Palmas are run by the municipal bus company, ''Guaguas Municipales de Las Palmas de Gran Canaria''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guaguas Municipales {{!}} Qui\u00e9nes somos |url=https://www.guaguas.com/empresa/quienes-somos |website=Guaguas Municipales |accessdate=30 January 2019 |language=es}}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\n[[Gran Canaria Airport]] ([[IATA]]: LPA) is the only commercial airport on the island. The large number of aircraft and passengers passing through it each year make it one of the busiest in Spain. Gran Canaria is also responsible for all air traffic control in the Canaries. By destination island, Gran Canaria is the second island that congregates the largest number of passengers in the Canary Islands.<ref name=\"pasajeros\">{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113153256/http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas/sector_servicios/turismo/turistas/5_4_2_2_1.html|url=http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas/sector_servicios/turismo/turistas/5_4_2_2_1.html|archivedate=13 November 2010|title=Entrada en los aeropuertos canarios seg\u00fan islas}}</ref>\n\n===Sea ports===\nThe most important ports in the island are the Port of Las Palmas ''([[Puerto de Las Palmas|Puerto de la Luz]]),'' in the city of [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]; [[Arguinegu\u00edn]], which exports [[cement]] from a large factory; and [[Arinaga]], located in the main industrial zone of Canaries and one of the major ones of Spain.\n\nThe main passenger ports are the Port of La Luz, where [[Trasmediterr\u00e1nea]] operates a weekly ferry route to [[Cadiz]] on the Spanish mainland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Cadiz to Las Palmas ferry tickets, compare times and prices |url=https://www.directferries.co.uk/cadiz_las_palmas_ferry.htm |website=www.directferries.co.uk |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref> and the [[Puerto de las Nieves|Port of Las Nieves]], located in [[Agaete]] on the west side of the island, where [[Fred Olsen Express]] operates a [[catamaran]] ferry service to [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Agaete to Santa Cruz de Tenerife ferry tickets, compare times and prices |url=https://www.directferries.co.uk/agaete_santa_cruz_de_tenerife_ferry.htm |website=www.directferries.co.uk |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Train===\nPlans for a [[Tren de Gran Canaria]] railway network linking the capital with the south have been approved by both the [[Cabildo insular|Gran Canaria Cabildo]] and the autonomous Canary Islands' Government, though the discussion with the central Spanish Government hinges now on budget. The planned {{convert|57|km|abbr=on}} railway line would run between Las Palmas and Meloneras, with the section in the capital running entirely underground as far as the suburb of Jin\u00e1mar. The line is planned to have 11 stations, including an underground station at Gran Canaria Airport. The scheme was first announced in 2009, with a planned operational date in 2015. A public company called ''Ferrocarriles de Gran Canaria'' has been formed by the Cabildo's Gran Canaria Transport Authority. Plans were still being discussed in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gran Canaria train details announced - Gran Canaria - Gran Canaria - ISLANDCONNECTIONS.EU |url=http://www.islandconnections.eu/1000003/1000023/0/26465/gran-canaria-article.html |accessdate=12 November 2018 |work=Island Connections}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Estado y Cabildo pactan cerrar los proyectos del tren en 2018 |url=https://www.canarias7.es/siete-islas/gran-canaria/estado-y-cabildo-pactan-cerrar-los-proyectos-del-tren-en-2018-EH3382116 |accessdate=12 November 2018 |work=www.canarias7.es |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\n\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Gran Canaria is considered to have a desert climate (Bwh) due to its consistent warm temperatures and severe lack of precipitation. Gran Canaria is noted for its rich variety of [[microclimate]]s. Generally speaking though, the average daytime high ranges from {{convert|20|C|F}} in winter to {{convert|26|C|F}} in summer. Some cool nights occur in winter, but lows below {{convert|10|C|F}} are unknown near the coast. Inland the climate is still mild but mountainous areas see the occasional frost or snow. Annual rainfall averages {{convert|228|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}, most of this falling in the cooler months, with July, August and September normally rainless. Rainfall is unevenly distributed through the island with some areas being much drier than others.\nCloud cover and sunshine is often quite variable during the cooler months, and there can be several rather cloudy days at times in winter. Summers are generally quite sunny however, with the south of the island being most favoured.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gran Canaria Airport (1981\u20132010)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 20.8\n|Feb high C = 21.2\n|Mar high C = 22.3\n|Apr high C = 22.6\n|May high C = 23.6\n|Jun high C = 25.3\n|Jul high C = 26.9\n|Aug high C = 27.5\n|Sep high C = 27.2\n|Oct high C = 26.2\n|Nov high C = 24.2\n|Dec high C = 22.2\n|year high C = 24.2\n|Jan mean C = 17.9\n|Feb mean C = 18.2\n|Mar mean C = 19.0\n|Apr mean C = 19.4\n|May mean C = 20.4\n|Jun mean C = 22.2\n|Jul mean C = 23.8\n|Aug mean C = 24.6\n|Sep mean C = 24.3\n|Oct mean C = 23.1\n|Nov mean C = 21.2\n|Dec mean C = 19.2\n|year mean C = 21.2\n|Jan low C = 15.0\n|Feb low C = 15.0\n|Mar low C = 15.7\n|Apr low C = 16.2\n|May low C = 17.3\n|Jun low C = 19.2\n|Jul low C = 20.8\n|Aug low C = 21.6\n|Sep low C = 21.4\n|Oct low C = 20.1\n|Nov low C = 18.1\n|Dec low C = 16.2\n|year low C = 18.2\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 25\n|Feb precipitation mm = 24\n|Mar precipitation mm = 13\n|Apr precipitation mm = 6\n|May precipitation mm = 1\n|Jun precipitation mm = 0\n|Jul precipitation mm = 0\n|Aug precipitation mm = 0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 9\n|Oct precipitation mm = 16\n|Nov precipitation mm = 22\n|Dec precipitation mm = 31\n|year precipitation mm = 151\n|Jan precipitation days = 3\n|Feb precipitation days = 3\n|Mar precipitation days = 2\n|Apr precipitation days = 1\n|May precipitation days = 0\n|Jun precipitation days = 0\n|Jul precipitation days = 0\n|Aug precipitation days = 0\n|Sep precipitation days = 1\n|Oct precipitation days = 2\n|Nov precipitation days = 4\n|Dec precipitation days = 5\n|unit precipitation days = 1&nbsp;mm\n|year precipitation days = 21\n|Jan sun = 184\n|Feb sun = 191\n|Mar sun = 229\n|Apr sun = 228\n|May sun = 272\n|Jun sun = 284\n|Jul sun = 308\n|Aug sun = 300\n|Sep sun = 241\n|Oct sun = 220\n|Nov sun = 185\n|Dec sun = 179\n|year sun = 2821\n|source 1 = [[Agencia Estatal de Meteorolog\u00eda]] ,<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.aemet.es/en/serviciosclimaticos/datosclimatologicos/valoresclimatologicos?l=C649I&k=coo\n  |title=Standard Climate Values. Gran Canaria Aeropuerto\n  |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Agencia Estatal de Meteorolog\u00eda]]<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.aemet.es/en/conocermas/publicaciones/detalles/guia_resumida_2010 \n |title=Gu\u00eda resumida del clima en Espa\u00f1a (1981\u20132010) \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118081428/http://www.aemet.es/en/conocermas/publicaciones/detalles/guia_resumida_2010 \n |archivedate=2012-11-18 \n}}</ref>\n|date=March 2016}}\n\n== Agriculture ==\n\nGran Canaria agriculture is unique among the Canaries islands in that it was traditionally dominated by plantations, with much of these being grains as well as [[sugarcane]], rather than by stock-breeding.<ref name=\"arqu\">[http://www.arqueologiacanaria.com/Arqueologia_Canaria/Cenobio_de_Valeron.html Cenobio de Valeron], section \"''El yacimiento arqueologico''\". On ''arqueologiacanaria.com''.</ref> The [[caves of Valer\u00f3n]] (a [[property of cultural interest]] in the \"archaeological site\" category) in the municipality of [[Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria|Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda]] bears testimony of it by being the largest pre-Hispanic collective granary of the Canaries.\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:Puerto de Mog\u00e1n 2016 02.jpg|thumb|[[Puerto de Mog\u00e1n]]]]\n[[File:Lighthouse Maspalomas.jpg|thumb|[[Maspalomas Lighthouse]] at the southern end of the island.]]\n[[File:RoqueNublo2.jpg|thumb|[[Roque Nublo]] in the interior of the island]]\nThis island is called a \"miniature continent\" due to the different climates and variety of landscapes found, with long beaches and dunes of white sand, contrasting with green ravines and picturesque villages.<ref>[http://www.turismodecanarias.com/canary-islands-spain/tourism-office/gran-canaria-island/index.html Gran Canaria \u2013 Official Canary Islands Tourism]</ref> A third of the island is under protection as a [[Man and the Biosphere Programme|Biosphere Reserve]] by [[UNESCO]].\n\nThe number of annual visitors was 3.6 million in 2014 (of which 450.000 Spaniards).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.grancanaria.com/patronato_turismo/typo3conf/ext/naw_securedl/secure.php?u=0&file=fileadmin/PDF/informes/ICT_cierre_14_EN.pdf&t=1457890821&hash=d2691cfd6d0e8c8417e39f39fc6a3b49 |title=Situation Of The Tourism Sector, Year Ending 2014 |website=The Official Gran Canaria Tourist Website |publisher= [[Cabildo insular|Cabildo de Gran Canaria]]|access-date=12 March 2016 |quote=}}</ref> Most of the tourists visit the southern part of the island. The north tends to be cooler, while the south is warmer and sunny. The east coast of the island is flat, dotted with beaches, while the western coast is rockier and mountainous.\n\nThe island possesses 32 Natural Protected Spaces,<ref name=\"listEspaces\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.gobcan.es/cmayot/espaciosnaturales/informacion/grancan_todo.html |title=Espacios Naturales Protegidos de Gran Canaria Font: Gobierno de Canarias |access-date=2007-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070323182846/http://www.gobcan.es/cmayot/espaciosnaturales/informacion/grancan_todo.html |archive-date=2007-03-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref> notably the Rural Park of Nublo, The Doramas Jungle, the Azuaje Ravine, Tamadaba, Pino Santo, etc.\n\nIn the south there is a large bird park, [[Palmitos Park]], as well as many beach resort communities. Resorts are concentrated in the central eastern part of the southern coast in the [[Maspalomas]] area, which includes the towns of [[San Agustin, Las Palmas|San Agust\u00edn]], [[Playa del Ingl\u00e9s]] and [[Meloneras]]. The [[Maspalomas Dunes]] are located between Playa del Ingl\u00e9s (\"The Englishman's Beach\") and the distinctive 19th century [[Maspalomas Lighthouse|Maspalomas lighthouse]]. Playa del Ingles is home to the Yumbo Centre,<ref>http://yumbocentrum.com/home/</ref> which was opened in 1982 and has almost 200 shops, including bars, restaurants, cafes, fashion boutiques, electronic outlets and jewellery stores.\n\nIn Tarajalillo, an Aeroclub exists from where tourist flights can be taken over the island.\n\nStill further to the west along the southern shore, in the Municipality of Mog\u00e1n, are the communities of [[Puerto Rico, Las Palmas|Puerto Rico]] and [[Puerto de Mog\u00e1n]], a village referred to as \"Little Venice\" on account of its many canals.\n\nOther attractions include Cocodrilos Park, [[Roque Nublo]] (an 80&nbsp;m monolith), [[Cenobio de Valer\u00f3n]] with more than 350 storage cavities, [[Painted Cave, Galdar|Painted cave of Galdar]] the most important archaeological park in Canary Islands, or the botanical gardens ''[[Jard\u00edn Bot\u00e1nico Canario Viera y Clavijo|Jard\u00edn Canario]]'' (in Tafira Alta) and ''Cactualdea'' (in [[La Aldea de San Nicol\u00e1s]]).\n\n[[El Dedo de Dios]], or \"God's Finger\", was a rocky spire jutting from the sea in [[Puerto de las Nieves]], and was previously the signature attraction of the Canary Islands until it was destroyed by [[Tropical Storm Delta (2005)|tropical storm Delta]] that crossed the archipelago on November 2005.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4482384.stm BBC NEWS - ''Tropical Storm Delta batters Canaries''].</ref>\n\nOther well-known rock formations are El Cura (also known as El Fraile), The Frog (La Rana), [[Roque Bentayga]], the Roque de Gando, and the Pe\u00f1\u00f3n Bermejo. Traditionally, the highest peak of the island has been considered to be the [[Pico de las Nieves]], at {{convert|1949|m}}; however, [[Morro de la Agujereada]] is taller, at {{convert|1956|m}}.\n\nThe capital city is [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]. ''Las Canteras'' beach, a protected area and diving zone, lies in the heart of the city. Las Palmas de Gran Canaria is also known for its annual ''[[Carnival|carnaval]]''. It was the first stop of Christopher Columbus' expedition on his way back from the Americas,{{sfn|Andrews & Quintero|2007|p=29}} a commemoration of which is the Hermitage of San Antonio Abad, where the navigator prayed, and the ''Casa de Col\u00f3n''. Other attractions in the capital city include the ''Museo Canario'' (the most important archaeology museum in the archipelago), the cathedral and the ''Plaza del Esp\u00edritu Santo''. In [[Teror]] the shrine of ''[[Virgen del Pino]]'' (\"Virgin of the Pine\"), patron saint of Gran Canaria, can be found. Its feast is celebrated on September 8.\n\nThe town of [[Ag\u00fcimes]], on the eastern part of the island, has been carefully restored and its town centre, centered on its old church and a peaceful square, now evokes the quiet living of a traditional Canarian town. The district also has some of the best preserved cave dwellings, in the protected area of the [[Guayadeque ravine]], where even the church has been built into the mountainside and visitors can find a number of popular cave restaurants. The district also includes the most renowned scuba diving area on the island: the marine reserve at the ''playa de El Cabr\u00f3n'' just outside the town of Arinaga.\n\nOther important towns are [[Telde]], known among other things for their [[Surfing|surf]] schools in Salinetas, Vecindario (within the municipality of Santa Luc\u00eda de Tirajana) and [[G\u00e1ldar]], that contains an important diving zone. In [[Arucas]] there is a Neogothic temple, popularly known as \"Arucas' Cathedral\", as well as a large fertile plain where bananas are grown. In [[G\u00e1ldar]] and its surroundings there is also a banana-growing plain and some remarkable archaeological remains,<ref name=\"estodotuyoMap\">[http://www.estodotuyo.com/mapa-del-patrimonio/ Interactive map of Heritage sites on Grand Canary island] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818133842/http://www.estodotuyo.com/mapa-del-patrimonio/ |date=2016-08-18 }}. On ''estodotuyo.com'', site on Heritage assets by the council of Grand Canary.</ref> such as the [[Painted Cave, Galdar|Painted cave of Galdar]] or the [[cenobio de Valer\u00f3n]]'s communal silos, ancient tombs (among which the [[necropolis of Maip\u00e9s, Agaete|necropolis of Maip\u00e9s]]), and the port of Sardina del Norte (one of the island's ports where, as in Las Palmas', [[Christopher Columbus]] used to get supplies for his ships).\n\nHeading west along the southern coast is the fishing city of [[Arguinegu\u00edn]] in the [[Mog\u00e1n, Las Palmas|Municipality of Mog\u00e1n]].\n\n== Natural symbols ==\n{{Main|List of animal and plant symbols of the Canary Islands}}\nThe official natural symbols associated with Gran Canaria are ''[[Perro de Presa Canario|Canis lupus familiaris]]'' (Canary Mastiff) and ''[[Euphorbia canariensis]]'' (Card\u00f3n)<ref>[http://www.gobcan.es/boc/1991/061/001.html Ley 7/1991, de 30 de abril, de s\u00edmbolos de la naturaleza para las Islas Canarias]</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Dogo Canario bearb.jpg|''[[Perro de Presa Canario|Canis lupus familiaris]]''\nFile:Euphorbia canariensis (La Fajana) 11.jpg|''[[Euphorbia canariensis]]''\n</gallery>\n\n== Protected natural areas ==\n[[File:Dunas de Maspalomas.jpg|thumb|The \"[[Maspalomas Dunes|Dunas de Maspalomas]]\", in southern Gran Canaria]]\nNearly half of the island territory&nbsp;\u2014 667&nbsp;km\u00b2 (42.7% of island)&nbsp;\u2014 is under protection from the Red Canaria de Espacios Naturales Protegidos ([[Canary Islands Network for Protected Natural Areas]]). Of the 146 protected sites under control of network in the Canary Islands archipelago,<ref>[http://www.gobcan.es/cmayot/espaciosnaturales/informacion/quees.html Red Canaria de Espacios Naturales Protegidos] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121081945/http://www.gobcan.es/cmayot/espaciosnaturales/informacion/quees.html |date=2016-11-21 }}</ref> a total of 33 are located in Gran Canaria, the second most protected island in the group.\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gobcan.es/cmayot/espaciosnaturales/informacion/grancan_todo.html |title=Relaci\u00f3n de los Espacios Naturales protegidos de Gran Canaria |access-date=2007-03-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070323182846/http://www.gobcan.es/cmayot/espaciosnaturales/informacion/grancan_todo.html |archive-date=2007-03-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  There are seven different categories of protection:\n# Six [[nature reserve]]s&nbsp;\u2014 El Brezal, Azuaje, Los Tilos de Moya, Los Marteles, Las Dunas de Maspalomas and G\u00fcig\u00fci (total 7,153.1 ha)\n# Two integral nature reserves&nbsp;\u2014 Inagua and Barranco Oscuro (total 3,955,5 ha)\n# Two [[nature park|natural park]]s&nbsp;\u2014 Tamadaba and [[Pilancones]] (total 13,333 ha)\n# Two rural parks&nbsp;\u2014 Nublo and Doramas (total 29,893.4 ha)\n# Ten [[natural monument]]s&nbsp;\u2014 Amagro, Bandama, Monta\u00f1\u00f3n Negro, Roque de Aguayro, Tauro, Arinaga, [[Barranco de Guayadeque]], Riscos de Tirajana, Roque Nublo and Barranco del Draguillo (total 5,264.9 ha)\n# Seven [[Protected area|protected landscapes]]&nbsp;\u2014 La Isleta (in the capital [[Las Palmas|Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]), Pino Santo, Tafira, Las Cumbres, Lomo Magullo, Fataga and Monta\u00f1a de Ag\u00fcimes (total 12,680.9 ha)\n# Four [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|sites of scientific interest]]&nbsp;\u2014 Jin\u00e1mar, Tufia, Roque de Gando and Juncalillo del Sur (total 276.2 ha).<ref name=\"listEspaces\"/>\n\n==Science and technology==\n[[File:Erdfunkstelle Gran Canaria-3.JPG|thumb|Gran Canaria space tracking station]]\nIn the 1960s, Gran Canaria was selected as the location for one of the 14 [[ground stations]] in the [[Manned Space Flight Network]] (MSFN) to support the [[NASA]] space program. [[Maspalomas Station]], located in the south of the island, took part in a number of space missions including the [[Apollo 11]] Moon landings and [[Skylab]]. Today it continues to support satellite communications as part of the [[ESA]] network.<ref name=\"esa-page\">{{cite web |title=Maspalomas station |url=http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Operations/Estrack/Maspalomas_station |website=European Space Agency |accessdate=8 February 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190208113652/http://www.esa.int/Our_Activities/Operations/Estrack/Maspalomas_station |archivedate=8 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Sports ==\n[[File:Partido Basket Herbalife Gran Canaria - Unicaja ( 67- 65).jpg|thumb|right|2014 game between [[CB Gran Canaria|Herbalife Gran Canaria]] and [[Baloncesto M\u00e1laga|Unicaja]].]]\nThe island is home to [[CB Gran Canaria]] \u2013 a basketball club playing in [[Liga ACB]] at the [[Gran Canaria Arena]], with a capacity of 11,000.\nThe island is also home to [[UD Las Palmas]] \u2013 a football club playing in [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] at the [[Estadio de Gran Canaria]], with a capacity of 32,392.\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Spain|Islands}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n\n* {{cite book\n | last1=Andrews\n | first1=Sarah\n | last2=Quintero\n | first2=Josephine\n | title=Canary Islands\n | url=https://books.google.fr/books?id=RNSwXN3-LZMC\n | year=2007\n | publisher=Lonely Planet\n | isbn=978-1741045956\n | ref={{harvid|Andrews & Quintero|2007}}\n}}\n\n=== References ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{Commons and category|Gran Canaria}}\n\n*[http://www.grancanaria.com/patronato_turismo Gran Canaria Tourist Board official site]\n*{{Wikivoyage-inline|Gran Canaria}}\n\n{{Gran Canaria}}\n{{Islands and provinces of the Canary Islands}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Biosphere reserves of Spain]]\n[[Category:Fissure vents]]\n[[Category:Gran Canaria| ]]\n[[Category:Islands of the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Volcanoes of the Canary Islands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish island of the Canary Islands}}\n{{redirect|Grand Canary|the novel by A. J. Cronin|Grand Canary (novel)|the film adaptation of the novel|Grand Canary (film)}}\n{{Infobox islands\n|name                             = Gran Canaria\n|image_name                       = Gran Canaria wildfire (48590670831).jpg\n|image_caption                    =\n|map_image                        = File:Spain Canary Islands location map Gran Canaria.svg\n|native_name                      = \n|native_name_link                 =\n|location                         = [[Atlantic Ocean]]\n|coordinates                      = {{coord|27|58|N|15|36|W|display=it}}\n|archipelago                      = \n|total_islands                    = \n|major_islands                    = \n|area_km2                         = 1560.11\n|highest_mount                    = {{interlanguage link|Morro de la Agujereada|es}}\n| elevation_m                      = 1949\n| country_admin_divisions         = [[Spain]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1 = Region\n| country_admin_divisions_1       = [[Macaronesia]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2 = [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Community]]\n| country_admin_divisions_2       = [[Canary Islands]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_3 = [[Provinces of Spain|Province]]\n| country_admin_divisions_3       = [[Province of Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n|country_largest_city             = [[Las Palmas]]\n|country_largest_city_population  = 379,925\n|population                       = 851,231<ref>[http://www.ine.es/jaxi/tabla.do?path=/t20/e260/a2010/l0/&file=is01.px&type=pcaxis&L=0 Population referred to the January 1, 2019] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131145315/https://boe.es/boe/dias/2018/12/29/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-18083.pdf |date=31 January 2019 }}</ref>\n|population_as_of                 = 2019\n|density_km2                      = 545.6\n|ethnic_groups                    =\n}}\n[[File:Flag of Gran Canaria.svg|thumb|250px|Flag of Gran Canaria.]]\n'''Gran Canaria''' ({{IPAc-en|uk|\u02cc|\u0261|r|\u00e6|n|_|k|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u025b\u0259r|i|\u0259|,_|-|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0r|-}}, {{IPAc-en|us|\u02cc|\u0261|r|\u0251\u02d0|n|_|k|\u0259|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0r|i|\u0259|,_|-|\u02c8|n|\u025b\u0259r|-}};<ref>\n{{cite book|last=Wells|first=John C.|year=2008|title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary|edition=3rd|publisher=Longman|isbn=978-1-4058-8118-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Roach|first=Peter|year=2011|title=Cambridge English Pronouncing Dictionary|edition=18th|place=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-15253-2}}</ref> {{IPA-es|\u0261\u027ea\u014b ka\u02c8na\u027eja}}), also '''Grand Canary Island''', is the second most populous of the [[Canary Islands]], an [[archipelago]] off the Atlantic coast of [[Northwest Africa]] which is part of [[Spain]]. {{As of|2019}} the island had a population of {{formatnum:851231}} that constitutes approximately 40% of the population of the archipelago. \n\nGran Canaria is located in the [[Atlantic Ocean]] about {{convert|150|km}} off the northwestern coast of [[Africa]] and about {{convert|1350|km|abbr=on}} from [[Europe]].<ref>[http://www.laspalmasgc.es/lpgc/idcplg?IdcService=SS_GET_PAGE&nodeId=137 Situaci\u00f3n y Clima. Ayuntamiento de Las Palmas de Gran Canaria.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629205852/http://www.laspalmasgc.es/lpgc/idcplg?IdcService=SS_GET_PAGE&nodeId=137 |date=2010-06-29 }}</ref> With an area of {{formatnum:1560}} km<sup>2</sup> ({{formatnum:602}} sq. mi)<ref>[http://www.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas.html ISTAC: ''Estad\u00edsticas de la Comunidad Aut\u00f3noma de Canarias''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101114080725/http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas.html |date=2010-11-14 }} (Statistics for the Canaries) on ''gobiernodecanarias.org''.</ref> and an altitude of {{convert|1956|m|abbr=on}} at [[Morro de la Agujereada]], Gran Canaria is the third largest island of the archipelago in both area and altitude. Gran Canaria is also the third most populated island in Spain after [[Tenerife]] and [[Mallorca]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boe.es/boe/dias/2018/12/29/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-18083.pdf|title=Bolet\u00edn Oficial del Estado|date=29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn [[Classical antiquity|antiquity]], Gran Canaria was populated by the North African [[Guanches|Canarii]], who may have arrived as early as 500 BC. The Canarii called the island '''Tamar\u00e1n''' ('land of the brave\").\n\nIn the [[Middle Ages|medieval period]], after over a century of European incursions and attempts at conquest, the island was conquered on April 29, 1483 by the [[Crown of Castile]], under [[Isabella I of Castile|Queen Isabella I]]. The conquest succeeded after a campaign that lasted five years, and it was an important step towards the expansion of the unified Spain.\n\nThe capital city of [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]] was founded on June 24, 1478, under the name \"Real de Las Palmas\", by [[Juan Rej\u00f3n]], head of the invading [[Crown of Castile|Castilian]] army. In 1492, [[Christopher Columbus]] anchored in the [[Port of Las Palmas]] (and spent some time on the island) on his first trip to the Americas. Las Palmas de Gran Canaria is, jointly with [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]], the capital of the [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of the Canary Islands.\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Gc01.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Topography of Gran Canaria]]\n[[File:Gran Canaria 3D version1.gif|thumb|left|Gran Canaria 3D]]\n\nGran Canaria is located in the [[Canary Islands]] archipelago southeast of [[Tenerife]] and west of [[Fuerteventura]]. The island is of [[volcano|volcanic]] origin, mostly made of [[fissure vent]]s. It has a round shape, with a diameter of approximately {{convert|50|km|abbr=on}} and a surface area of {{convert|1,560|km2|abbr=on}}. Gran Canaria's maximum elevation is {{convert|1,956|m}} at [[Morro de la Agujereada]], although the nearby [[Pico de las Nieves]] has traditionally been considered the island's tallest peak.\n\n=== Geology ===\nAbout 80% of the volume of the island was formed during the [[Miocene]] period eruptions, between 14 and 9 million years ago. This is called the \"Old Cycle\" and is estimated to have lasted some 200,000 years and have emitted about {{convert|1000|km3|abbr=on}}, mostly of fissural [[alkali basalt]]. This cycle continued with the emission of [[trachyte]]s, [[phonolite]]s and [[peralkaline]] rocks. This period was followed by one of erosion, which lasted some 4 million years.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes\">Ara\u00f1a, V and Carracedo, J.C: ''Canarian Volcanoes'', Volume 3: Gran Canaria, pp. 8, 24. Editorial Rueda, Madrid, 1978.</ref>\n\nA second cycle of volcanic eruptions, known as the \"Roque Nublo cycle\", took place between 4.5 and 3.4 million years ago. This shorter cycle emitted about {{convert|100|km3|abbr=on}}. Most of the inland peaks were formed by erosion from these materials. This period also started with fissural basalts, but ended with violent eruptions of [[pyroclastic flows]]. Some phonolitic features, like the Risco Blanco, were also formed in its last stages.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes\"/>\n\nThe third or recent cycle is held to have started some 2.8 million years ago and is considered to be still active. The last eruptions are held to have occurred some 3,500 years ago.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes\"/>\n\nThe changes in volume and, therefore, weight of the island have also caused the island to rise above the previous sea level during erosive periods and to sink during eruptive periods. Some of these \"fossil beaches\" can be seen in the cliff faces of the more eroded northern coast.<ref name=\"canarian_volcanoes_sealevel\">Oscillations of up to {{convert|400|m|ft|abbr=on}} in the level corresponding to sea level have occurred in geological history. The highest point known is in the Bay of El Confital, Las Palmas ({{convert|130|m|ft|disp=comma|abbr=on}} above current sea level) while subaerial materials have been extracted from a well at {{convert|230|m|ft|abbr=on}} below sea level in the area of La Aldea. Ara\u00f1a, V and Carracedo, J.C: ''Canarian Volcanoes'', Volume 3: Gran Canaria, pp. 13. Editorial Rueda, Madrid, 1978.</ref>\n{{clear|left}}\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Nature of Gran Canaria 2016 03.jpg|Nature of Gran Canaria along the eastern shore in 2016\nFile:Nature of Gran Canaria 2016 1.jpg|Nature of Gran Canaria along the southeastern shore in 2016\n</gallery>\n\n== Vegetation ==\n\nUntil the conquest, Gran Canaria had extensive forests, but then suffered extensive [[deforestation]]<ref name=\"benmagec.org\">[http://www.benmagec.org/turcon/pdf/grancanaria/agy2ocr.pdf Reforestaci\u00f3n de las cumbres de Gran Canaria]</ref> as a result of continuous logging, land divisions and other intensive uses. This reduced the forest cover to just {{convert|56,000|hectare}},<ref name=\"benmagec.org\"/> making the island the most deforested of the Canary Islands.<ref>[http://www.eldiario.es/canariasahora/sociedad/reforestar-Gran-Canaria_0_383211903.html \u201cCon lo que cuesta un Jumbo se puede reforestar toda Gran Canaria\u201d]</ref> However, in the twentieth century reforestation of the ridge of the island was begun, recovering some of the lost forest mass. Much of the summit of the island is forested mostly due to [[reforestation]].<ref name=\"benmagec.org\"/>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Municipios y zonas de Gran Canaria.svg|thumb|Municipalities of Gran Canaria]]\nGran Canaria is in the [[autonomous communities of Spain|autonomous community]] of the [[Canary Islands]] (''Islas Canarias''). It lies within the [[Province of Las Palmas]], a [[Provinces of Spain|Spanish province]] which consists of the eastern part of the Canary Islands community. [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]] is the provincial capital, one of the two capitals of the Canary Islands along with [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref name=\"government\">{{cite web |title=Government of Gran Canaria |url=http://www.spain-grancanaria.com/en/discover/facts/government.html |website=www.spain-grancanaria.com |accessdate=21 November 2018 |language=English}}</ref>\n\nThe island of Gran Canaria is governed by the [[Cabildo insular|Cabildo insular de Gran Canaria]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Historia del Cabildo - Cabildo de Gran Canaria |url=http://cabildo.grancanaria.com/historia-del-cabildo |website=cabildo.grancanaria.com |accessdate=21 November 2018 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Gran Canaria Island itself is divided into twenty-one smaller [[List of municipalities in Las Palmas|municipalities]]:<ref name=\"government\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Name\n!Area<br />(km<sup>2</sup>)\n!Population<br />(2001)<ref>Census at 1 November 2001: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Madrid.</ref>\n!Population<br />(2011)<ref>Census at 1 November 2011: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Madrid.</ref>\n!Population<br />(2019)<ref>Estimate at 1 January 2019: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Madrid.</ref>\n|-\n|[[Agaete]]\n| align=\"right\" |45.50\n| align=\"right\" |5,202\n| align=\"right\" |5,735\n| align=\"right\" |5,586\n|-\n|[[Ag\u00fcimes]]\n| align=\"right\" |79.28\n| align=\"right\" |20,124\n| align=\"right\" |29,641\n| align=\"right\" |31,619\n|-\n|[[Artenara, Las Palmas|Artenara]]\n| align=\"right\" |66.70\n| align=\"right\" |1,319\n| align=\"right\" |1,252\n| align=\"right\" |1,069\n|-\n|[[Arucas, Las Palmas|Arucas]]\n| align=\"right\" |33.01\n| align=\"right\" |32,466\n| align=\"right\" |36,771\n| align=\"right\" |38,138\n|-\n|[[Firgas, Las Palmas|Firgas]]\n| align=\"right\" |15.77\n| align=\"right\" |6,865\n| align=\"right\" |7,606\n| align=\"right\" |7,455\n|-\n|[[G\u00e1ldar, Las Palmas|G\u00e1ldar]]\n| align=\"right\" |61.59\n| align=\"right\" |22,154\n| align=\"right\" |24,358\n| align=\"right\" |24,242\n|-\n|[[Ingenio, Las Palmas|Ingenio]]\n| align=\"right\" |38.15\n| align=\"right\" |24,439\n| align=\"right\" |30,022\n| align=\"right\" |31,321\n|-\n|[[Mog\u00e1n]]\n| align=\"right\" |172.44\n| align=\"right\" |12,444\n| align=\"right\" |22,847\n| align=\"right\" |20,072\n|-\n|[[Moya, Las Palmas|Moya]]\n| align=\"right\" |31.87\n| align=\"right\" |8,137\n| align=\"right\" |8,043\n| align=\"right\" |7,696\n|-\n|[[La Aldea de San Nicol\u00e1s]]\n| align=\"right\" |123.58\n| align=\"right\" |7,668\n| align=\"right\" |8,522\n| align=\"right\" |7,504\n|-\n|[[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]\n| align=\"right\" |100.55\n| align=\"right\" |354,863\n| align=\"right\" |381,271\n| align=\"right\" |379,925\n|-\n|[[San Bartolom\u00e9 de Tirajana]]\n| align=\"right\" |333.13\n| align=\"right\" |34,515\n| align=\"right\" |53,440\n| align=\"right\" |53,443\n|-\n|[[Santa Br\u00edgida, Las Palmas|Santa Br\u00edgida]]\n| align=\"right\" |23.81\n| align=\"right\" |17,598\n| align=\"right\" |18,878\n| align=\"right\" |18,263\n|-\n|[[Santa Luc\u00eda de Tirajana]]\n| align=\"right\" |61.56\n| align=\"right\" |47,652\n| align=\"right\" |66,725\n| align=\"right\" |73,328\n|-\n|[[Santa Mar\u00eda de Gu\u00eda de Gran Canaria]]\n| align=\"right\" |42.59\n| align=\"right\" |13,893\n| align=\"right\" |14,149\n| align=\"right\" |13,850\n|-\n|[[Tejeda, Las Palmas|Tejeda]]\n| align=\"right\" |103.30\n| align=\"right\" |2,400\n| align=\"right\" |2,136\n| align=\"right\" |1,909\n|-\n|[[Telde, Las Palmas|Telde]]\n| align=\"right\" |102.43\n| align=\"right\" |87,949\n| align=\"right\" |101,080\n| align=\"right\" |102,647\n|-\n|[[Teror, Las Palmas|Teror]]\n| align=\"right\" |25.70\n| align=\"right\" |12,042\n| align=\"right\" |12,857\n| align=\"right\" |12,519\n|-\n|[[Valleseco, Las Palmas|Valleseco]]\n| align=\"right\" |22.11\n| align=\"right\" |3,949\n| align=\"right\" |3,896\n| align=\"right\" |3,749\n|-\n|[[Valsequillo de Gran Canaria]]\n| align=\"right\" |39.15\n| align=\"right\" |7,964\n| align=\"right\" |9,118\n| align=\"right\" |9,340\n|-\n|[[Vega de San Mateo]]\n| align=\"right\" |37.89\n| align=\"right\" |6,979\n| align=\"right\" |7,737\n| align=\"right\" |7,556\n|-\n|''Totals''\n| align=\"right\" |''1,560.11''\n| align=\"right\" |''730,622''\n| align=\"right\" |''846,084''\n| align=\"right\" |''851,231''\n|-\n|}\n\nThe island has a population at the start of 2019 of 851,231 with 379,925 of those in the capital city of [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]. Gran Canaria is the second most populous island of the Canary Islands, after [[Tenerife]].<ref>[http://www.ine.es/jaxi/tabla.do?path=/t20/e260/a2010/l0/&file=is01.px&type=pcaxis&L=0 Population referred to the January 1, 2018] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131145315/https://boe.es/boe/dias/2018/12/29/pdfs/BOE-A-2018-18083.pdf |date=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Transportation ==\n===Roads===\n[[File:Gran Canaria GC-1 Bridge over Barranco de Tauro 9558.jpg|thumb|''Autopistas'' in Gran Canaria provide rapid road transport around the coast]]\n[[File:Guaguas Gran Canaria Sur (30956433245).jpg|thumb|A Gran Canaria bus]]\n[[File:Gran Canaria Airport 2015-12-16 a.jpg|thumb|Gran Canaria Airport]]\n[[File:Agaete, Gran Canaria D81 8134 (32250537964).jpg|thumb|The Tenerife catamaran ferry]]\nGran Canaria has roads encircling the whole island and extending into the mountain areas. In the late 20th century, its dual carriageway, among the first in the Canary Islands, were opened and run around Las Palmas de Gran Canaria, and were later extended to the north coast and the airport and subsequently to the south coast in response to increased tourist traffic. The only highway of Gran Canaria are [[GC1 (Gran Canaria)|GC1]]. Dual carriageway is [[GC2 (Gran Canaria)|GC2]], and [[GC31 (Gran Canaria)|GC31]], [[GC4 (Gran Canaria)|GC4]] and [[GC5 (Gran Canaria)|GC5]]. The western and the north-western parts, with the fewest inhabitants, are linked only with main roads.\n\n===Buses===\nPublic transport around Gran Canaria is provided by an extensive bus network, known in the local dialect as ''[[wiktionary:guagua|guaguas]]''. The ''[[Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria]]'' (Gran Canaria Transport Authority, TGC) manages the network and operates a number of bus stations across the island, including San Telmo and Santa Catalina bus stations in Las Palmas, Maspalomas and Galdar.<ref>{{cite web |title=Intercambiadores y Paradas Preferentes {{!}} Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria |url=http://www.autgc.org/transporte-en-gc/intercambiadores-y-paradas-preferentes |website=www.autgc.org |publisher=Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria|language=es}}</ref> Bus tickets may be purchased with cash, and AUTGC also operates a [[Contactless smart card|contactless]] [[electronic ticket]] called the TransGC Card, which is valid across the whole network.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tarjeta TransGC |url=http://www.autgc.org/transporte-en-gc/tarjeta-transgc |website=www.autgc.org |publisher=Autoridad \u00danica del Transporte de Gran Canaria |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=es}}</ref> \n\nInter-urban bus services across the island are operated by the Global bus company.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gran Canaria - Global SU |url=https://www.guaguasglobal.com/en/lineas-horarios/informacion-turistica/gran-canaria/ |website=Global SU |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=L\u00edneas y Horarios |url=https://www.guaguasglobal.com/lineas-horarios/ |website=Global SU |accessdate=30 January 2019 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Global was created in 2000 after the merger of two bus companies, Utinsa (which operated in the north of the island) and Salcai (the bus operator for the south).<ref>{{cite web |title=La Empresa: Global |url=https://www.guaguasglobal.com/empresa/ |website=Global SU |accessdate=30 January 2019 |language=es-ES}}</ref> Local bus services in Las Palmas are run by the municipal bus company, ''Guaguas Municipales de Las Palmas de Gran Canaria''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Guaguas Municipales {{!}} Qui\u00e9nes somos |url=https://www.guaguas.com/empresa/quienes-somos |website=Guaguas Municipales |accessdate=30 January 2019 |language=es}}</ref>\n\n===Airport===\n[[Gran Canaria Airport]] ([[IATA]]: LPA) is the only commercial airport on the island. The large number of aircraft and passengers passing through it each year make it one of the busiest in Spain. Gran Canaria is also responsible for all air traffic control in the Canaries. By destination island, Gran Canaria is the second island that congregates the largest number of passengers in the Canary Islands.<ref name=\"pasajeros\">{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101113153256/http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas/sector_servicios/turismo/turistas/5_4_2_2_1.html|url=http://www2.gobiernodecanarias.org/istac/estadisticas/sector_servicios/turismo/turistas/5_4_2_2_1.html|archivedate=13 November 2010|title=Entrada en los aeropuertos canarios seg\u00fan islas}}</ref>\n\n===Sea ports===\nThe most important ports in the island are the Port of Las Palmas ''([[Puerto de Las Palmas|Puerto de la Luz]]),'' in the city of [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]; [[Arguinegu\u00edn]], which exports [[cement]] from a large factory; and [[Arinaga]], located in the main industrial zone of Canaries and one of the major ones of Spain.\n\nThe main passenger ports are the Port of La Luz, where [[Trasmediterr\u00e1nea]] operates a weekly ferry route to [[Cadiz]] on the Spanish mainland,<ref>{{cite web |title=Cadiz to Las Palmas ferry tickets, compare times and prices |url=https://www.directferries.co.uk/cadiz_las_palmas_ferry.htm |website=www.directferries.co.uk |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref> and the [[Puerto de las Nieves|Port of Las Nieves]], located in [[Agaete]] on the west side of the island, where [[Fred Olsen Express]] operates a [[catamaran]] ferry service to [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Agaete to Santa Cruz de Tenerife ferry tickets, compare times and prices |url=https://www.directferries.co.uk/agaete_santa_cruz_de_tenerife_ferry.htm |website=www.directferries.co.uk |accessdate=20 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Train===\nPlans for a [[Tren de Gran Canaria]] railway network linking the capital with the south have been approved by both the [[Cabildo insular|Gran Canaria Cabildo]] and the autonomous Canary Islands' Government, though the discussion with the central Spanish Government hinges now on budget. The planned {{convert|57|km|abbr=on}} railway line would run between Las Palmas and Meloneras, with the section in the capital running entirely underground as far as the suburb of Jin\u00e1mar. The line is planned to have 11 stations, including an underground station at Gran Canaria Airport. The scheme was first announced in 2009, with a planned operational date in 2015. A public company called ''Ferrocarriles de Gran Canaria'' has been formed by the Cabildo's Gran Canaria Transport Authority. Plans were still being discussed in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gran Canaria train details announced - Gran Canaria - Gran Canaria - ISLANDCONNECTIONS.EU |url=http://www.islandconnections.eu/1000003/1000023/0/26465/gran-canaria-article.html |accessdate=12 November 2018 |work=Island Connections}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Estado y Cabildo pactan cerrar los proyectos del tren en 2018 |url=https://www.canarias7.es/siete-islas/gran-canaria/estado-y-cabildo-pactan-cerrar-los-proyectos-del-tren-en-2018-EH3382116 |accessdate=12 November 2018 |work=www.canarias7.es |language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\n== Climate ==\n\nAccording to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], Gran Canaria is considered to have a desert climate (Bwh) due to its consistent warm temperatures and severe lack of precipitation. Gran Canaria is noted for its rich variety of [[microclimate]]s. Generally speaking though, the average daytime high ranges from {{convert|20|C|F}} in winter to {{convert|26|C|F}} in summer. Some cool nights occur in winter, but lows below {{convert|10|C|F}} are unknown near the coast. Inland the climate is still mild but mountainous areas see the occasional frost or snow. Annual rainfall averages {{convert|228|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}, most of this falling in the cooler months, with July, August and September normally rainless. Rainfall is unevenly distributed through the island with some areas being much drier than others.\nCloud cover and sunshine is often quite variable during the cooler months, and there can be several rather cloudy days at times in winter. Summers are generally quite sunny however, with the south of the island being most favoured.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gran Canaria Airport (1981\u20132010)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan high C = 20.8\n|Feb high C = 21.2\n|Mar high C = 22.3\n|Apr high C = 22.6\n|May high C = 23.6\n|Jun high C = 25.3\n|Jul high C = 26.9\n|Aug high C = 27.5\n|Sep high C = 27.2\n|Oct high C = 26.2\n|Nov high C = 24.2\n|Dec high C = 22.2\n|year high C = 24.2\n|Jan mean C = 17.9\n|Feb mean C = 18.2\n|Mar mean C = 19.0\n|Apr mean C = 19.4\n|May mean C = 20.4\n|Jun mean C = 22.2\n|Jul mean C = 23.8\n|Aug mean C = 24.6\n|Sep mean C = 24.3\n|Oct mean C = 23.1\n|Nov mean C = 21.2\n|Dec mean C = 19.2\n|year mean C = 21.2\n|Jan low C = 15.0\n|Feb low C = 15.0\n|Mar low C = 15.7\n|Apr low C = 16.2\n|May low C = 17.3\n|Jun low C = 19.2\n|Jul low C = 20.8\n|Aug low C = 21.6\n|Sep low C = 21.4\n|Oct low C = 20.1\n|Nov low C = 18.1\n|Dec low C = 16.2\n|year low C = 18.2\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm =