{"title_page": "1976 Toronto municipal election", "text_new": "The '''Toronto municipal election of 1976''' was held on December 6, 1976 in [[Metropolitan Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]].  Mayors, city councillors and school board trustees were elected in the municipalities of [[Toronto]], [[York, Toronto|York]], [[East York]], [[North York]], [[Etobicoke]] and [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]].\n\nToronto Mayor [[David Crombie]] and North York Mayor [[Mel Lastman]] were both re-elected without serious opposition.\n\n==Toronto==\n\n===Mayoral race===\nAs in the [[1974 Toronto municipal election|1974 election]] incumbent [[David Crombie]] faced no real opposition in his bid for reelection.\n\n;Results\n:'''[[David Crombie]]''' - 112,763\n:[[Don Andrews]] - 7,126\n:Henry Argasinski - 3,760\n:Richard Sanders - 2,373\n:Judy Lucko - 1,863\n:Ronald Rodgers - 1,613\n:Bill Zock - 1,506\n:Harry Dahme - 1,223\n:Robert Simms - 1,152\n:Andreis Murvieks - 962\n\n===City council===\n[[File:Toronto Ward Map 1969.png|right|thumb|300px|Ward boundaries used in the 1976 election]]\nCity council was mostly stable, the only notable upset was the defeat of long serving Old Guard member [[William Boytchuk]] by NDPer David White in Ward 1. The conservative membership remained stable as retiring moderate NDPer [[Reid Scott]] was replaced by conservative [[Thomas Alfred Wardle|Tom Wardle Jr.]].\n\n;Ward 1 ([[Swansea, Toronto|Swansea]] and [[Bloor West Village]])\n:'''[[Elizabeth Eayrs]]''' (incumbent) - 7,656\n:'''David White''' - 5,932\n:[[William Boytchuk]] (incumbent) - 5,883\n:[[Ben Grys]] - 4,420\n:Amonsen - 1,314\n:Ed Homonyla - 1,237\n\n;Ward 2 ([[Parkdale, Toronto|Parkdale]] and [[Brockton, Toronto|Brockton]])\n:'''[[Tony O'Donohue]]''' (incumbent) - 7,656\n:'''[[Ed Negridge]]''' (incumbent) - 4,545\n:Barbara Adams - 3,005\n:Glen Bany - 2,912\n:Pat Bator - 1,786\n\n;Ward 3 ([[Davenport, Toronto|Davenport]] and [[Corso Italia, Toronto|Corso Italia]])\n:'''[[Joseph Piccininni]]''' (incumbent) - 5,826\n:'''[[Richard Gilbert (politician)|Richard Gilbert]]''' - 4,651\n:Tony Amond - 1,464\n:Slough Bolton - 1,457\n:Domenic Tersigni - 545\n\n;Ward 4 ([[Trinity-Bellwoods]] and [[Little Italy]])\n:'''[[Art Eggleton]]''' (incumbent) - 4,615\n:'''[[George Ben]]''' (incumbent) - 2,957\n:[[Joe Pantalone]] - 2,713\n:Lee Zaslofsky - 1,940\n:Sydney Pimentel - 563\n:Brian Ashley - 379\n\n;Ward 5 ([[The Annex]] and [[Yorkville, Toronto|Yorkville]])\n:'''[[Ying Hope]]''' (incumbent) - 7,097\n:'''[[Susan Fish]]''' - 5,201\n:Fiona Nelson - 4,731\n:Barbara Jacob - 2,061\n:[[Brian Ashton (politician)|Brian Ashton]] - 1,796\n:Alex McDonald - 1,199\n:Norman Elder - 1,086\n\n;Ward 6 ([[Financial District, Toronto]] - [[University of Toronto]])\n:'''[[Dan Heap]]''' (incumbent) - 8,503\n:'''[[Allan Sparrow]]''' (incumbent) - 8,103\n:Peter Budd - 4,448\n:Arnold Linelsky - 2,046\n\n;Ward 7 ([[Regent Park]] and [[Riverdale, Toronto|Riverdale]])\n:'''[[John Sewell]]''' (incumbent) - 8,786\n:'''[[Janet Howard]]''' (incumbent) - 6,460\n:Gary Stamm - 4,419\n:Ronald Taylor - 770\n:Charles Rolfe - 767\n\n;Ward 8 ([[Riverdale, Toronto|Riverdale]])\n:'''[[Fred Beavis]]''' (incumbent) - 7,193\n:'''[[Thomas Clifford (Toronto)|Thomas Clifford]]''' (incumbent) - 6,883\n:Beatrice Zaverucha - 1,062\n:Louis Kesten - 951\n:John Bizzell - 771\n:Joe Dabonte - 458\n\n;Ward 9 ([[The Beaches]])\n:'''[[Pat Sheppard]]''' - 4,949\n:'''[[Tom Wardle, Jr.]]''' - 4,948\n:Bruce Budd - 4,665\n:Joe McNulty - 4,446\n:William Ross - 3,094\n:[[Neil Young (politician)|Neil Young]] - 2,114\n:John Oliver - 1,766\n:Sharon Meecham - 735\n:Edmond Cameron - 432\n:George Sloan - 344\n:Tom Last - 232\n\n;Ward 10 ([[Rosedale, Toronto|Rosedale]] and [[North Toronto]])\n:'''[[John Bosley (politician)|John Bosley]]''' (incumbent) - 11,638\n:'''[[June Rowlands]]''' - 11,307\n:Robert Perkins - 5,079\n:David White - 1,517\n\n;Ward 11 ([[Forest Hill, Toronto|Forest Hill]] and [[North Toronto]])\n:'''[[David Smith (Canadian Senator)|David Smith]]''' (incumbent) - 12,441\n:'''[[Anne Johnston]]''' (incumbent) - 11,600\n:Russ Tandler - 1,412\n:Fay MacPerson - 1,283\n\n===Changes===\nMayor [[David Crombie]] resigned on August 31, 1978 to contest a Federal by-election for [[Toronto Centre|Rosedale]] on October 16, 1978. On September 1, 1978 City Council met to appoint a new Mayor. The right-wingers stood Ward 8 Alderman [[Fred Beavis]] while the left-wingers stood Ward 11 Alderman [[Anne Johnston]]. When the vote was held the two candidates were tied with 11 votes each so in accordance with the Municipal Act put both names into a hat, and the name picked out of the hat would officially be pronounced interim mayor. Fred Beavis was the name chosen and he became mayor. [[Thomas Clifford (Toronto)|Thomas Clifford]] now became Ward 8's sole Alderman and was appointed Metro Councillor on September 11.\n\n==Metro boroughs==\n\n===East York===\nResults from the borough of East York. Two aldermen were elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: East York |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:[[Alan Redway]]\n\n;Ward 1\n:[[David Johnson (Canadian politician)|Dave Johnson]]\n:[[Leslie Saunders]]\n\n;Ward 2\n:John Flowers\n:Norman Crane\n\n;Ward 3\n:Ray Ireland\n:Don van Mierlo\n\n;Ward 4\n:Edna Beange\n:Peter Oyler\n\n===Etobicoke===\nResults from Etobicoke. Four members were elected to the Board of Control. Two aldermen were elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: Etobicoke |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:(x)[[Dennis Flynn]]\n\n;Board of Control\n:(x)Bill Stockwell\n:(x)[[Bruce Sinclair (politician)|Bruce Sinclair]]\n:(x)Nora Pownall\n:(x)E. H. (Pete) Farrow\n\n;Ward 1\n:Helen Wursta\n:[[Morley Kells]]\n\n;Ward 2\n:Alex Marchetti\n:Stewart East\n\n;Ward 3\n:Dick O'Brien\n:Alex McNeil\n\n;Ward 4\n:[[Lois Griffin (politician)|Lois Griffin]]\n:John Hanna\n\n;Ward 5\n:[[Ruth Grier]]\n:Pat Keaveney\n\n===North York===\n;Mayor\n:(x)'''[[Mel Lastman]]''' - 60,093\n:[[William Sutherland (Ontario politician)|William Sutherland]] - 15,634\n:Pallotta - 3,376\n:Obadia - 1,088\n:Minty - 920\n(1019 out of 1305 polls)\n\nLastman is re-elected defeating a challenge by Controller William Sutherland\n\n;Board of Control\n:(x)'''[[Barbara Greene]]''' - 52,053\n:'''[[Esther Shiner]]''' - 39,768\n:'''Ron Summers''' - 32,616\n:'''[[Robert Yuill|Bob Yuill]]''' - 31,050\n:Alex McGivern - 30,110\n:Jack Bedder - 20,267\n:Bernadette Michael - 13,803\n:Angelo Natale -10,281\n(1019 out of 1305 polls)\n\n;Ward 1\n:Gord Risk\n\n;Ward 2\n:[[Mario Gentile]]\n\n;Ward 3\n:Pat O'Neill\n\n{{Toronto municipal election, 1976/Position/North York Councillor, Ward Four}}\n\n*Hugh Montgomerie was a forty-three-year-old film technician.  He recommended a ban on high-density development projects that did not have adequate recreation facilities.<ref name=\"autogenerated1976\">\"North York\", ''Toronto Star'', 3 December 1976, A7.</ref>\n*Martin Lewin was a thirty-two-year-old sales manager.  He argued that shoppers in major plazas should not be forced to pay parking fees.<ref name=\"autogenerated1976\"/>\n*Harbans Rai Varma was a fifty-year-old supply teacher.  He called for lower employment and inflation levels, and for improved race relations.<ref name=\"autogenerated1976\"/>  He campaigned for the North York Board of Education in [[1980 Toronto municipal election|1980]], and lost to [[Elsa Chandler]] in Ward Four.  A candidate named \"Rai Varma\" ran for the [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]] Board of Control in [[1991 Markham general election|1991]]; this may be the same person.\n\n;Ward 5\n:Marilyn Meshberg\n\n;Ward 6\n:Milton Berger\n\n;Ward 7\n:Irving Chapley\n\n;Ward 8\n:[[Alan Heisey]]\n\n;Ward 9\n:[[Norm Gardner]]\n\n;Ward 10\n:Marie Laballe\n\n;Ward 11\n:Peter Clarke\n\n;Ward 12\n:Barry Burton\n\n;Ward 13\n:Mike Smith\n\n;Ward 14\n:Betty Sutherland\n\n===Scarborough===\nResults from the Borough of Scarborough. Four members were elected to the Board of Control. One alderman was elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: Scarborough |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:(x)'''[[Paul Cosgrove]]''' - 51,859\n:Lois James - 6,526\n\n;Board of Control\n:(x)'''[[Gus Harris]]''' - 35,525\n:(x)'''[[Ken Morrish]]''' - 35,243\n:(x)'''[[Joyce Trimmer]]''' - 31,358\n:(x)'''Brian Harrison''' - 30,956\n:Shirley Eidt - 28,363\n:Grant Boucher - 10,061\n:Larry Calcutt - 8,321\n:John Fletcher - 7,770\n\n;Ward 1\n:Bill Belfontaine\n\n;Ward 2\n:Carol Ruddell\n\n;Ward 3\n:[[Norm Kelly]]\n\n;Ward 4\n:Jack Goodlad\n\n;Ward 5\n:[[Frank Faubert]]\n\n;Ward 6\n:Frederick Samuel Bland\n\n;Ward 7\n:[[Ed Fulton]]\n\n;Ward 8\n:Tom Brazier\n\n;Ward 9\n:Doug Colling\n\n;Ward 10\n:Ron Watson\n\n;Ward 11\n:John Wimbs\n\n;Ward 12\n:Joe De Kort\n\n===York===\nResults from the borough of York. Two members were elected to the Board of Control. One alderman was elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: York |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Results in Metro's five boroughs |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=December 7, 1976 |page=4}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:'''[[Philip White (mayor)|Philip White]]''' 14,711\n:[[Fergy Brown]] 14,443\n\n;Board of Control (2 elected)\n:'''Doug Saunders''' 14,549\n:'''[[Alan Tonks]]''' 11,998\n:Patrick Canavan 7,479\n:Gordon 6,229\n:Ciardullo 3,572\n\n;Ward 1\n:Ben Nobleman (acclaimed)\n\n;Ward 2\n:Oscar Kogan (acclaimed)\n\n;Ward 3\n:Ron Bradd\n:Mizzoni 934\n:D'Aprile 825\n\n;Ward 4\n:Clifford Ward 1,532\n:Howells 693\n\n;Ward 5\n:[[Christopher Alexander Tonks|Chris Tonks]] (acclaimed)\n\n;Ward 6\n:Floyd Sainsbury 2,386\n:Dodds 2,187\n\n;Ward 7\n:[[Gayle Christie]] 2,853\n:Gallichan 1,484\n:McMahon 373\n\n;Ward 8\n:Mike Waclawski 2,987\n:[[John Nunziata]] 1,920\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Toronto elections}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toronto Municipal Election, 1976}}\n[[Category:Municipal elections in Toronto|1976]]\n[[Category:1976 elections in Canada]]\n[[Category:1976 in Toronto]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Toronto municipal election of 1976''' was held on December 6, 1976 in [[Metropolitan Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]].  Mayors, city councillors and school board trustees were elected in the municipalities of [[Toronto]], [[York, Toronto|York]], [[East York]], [[North York]], [[Etobicoke]] and [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]].\n\nToronto Mayor [[David Crombie]] and North York Mayor [[Mel Lastman]] were both re-elected without serious opposition.\n\n==Toronto==\n\n===Mayoral race===\nAs in the [[1974 Toronto municipal election|1974 election]] incumbent [[David Crombie]] faced no real opposition in his bid for reelection.\n\n;Results\n:'''[[David Crombie]]''' - 112,763\n:[[Don Andrews]] - 7,126\n:Henry Argasinski - 3,760\n:Richard Sanders - 2,373\n:Judy Lucko - 1,863\n:Ronald Rodgers - 1,613\n:Bill Zock - 1,506\n:Harry Dahme - 1,223\n:Robert Simms - 1,152\n:Andreis Murvieks - 962\n\n===City council===\n[[File:Toronto Ward Map 1969.png|right|thumb|300px|Ward boundaries used in the 1976 election]]\nCity council was mostly stable, the only notable upset was the defeat of long serving Old Guard member [[William Boytchuk]] by NDPer David White in Ward 1. The conservative membership remained stable as retiring moderate NDPer [[Reid Scott]] was replaced by conservative [[Thomas Alfred Wardle|Tom Wardle Jr.]].\n\n;Ward 1 ([[Swansea, Toronto|Swansea]] and [[Bloor West Village]])\n:'''[[Elizabeth Eayrs]]''' (incumbent) - 7,656\n:'''David White''' - 5,932\n:[[William Boytchuk]] (incumbent) - 5,883\n:[[Ben Grys]] - 4,420\n:Amonsen - 1,314\n:Ed Homonyla - 1,237\n\n;Ward 2 ([[Parkdale, Toronto|Parkdale]] and [[Brockton, Toronto|Brockton]])\n:'''[[Tony O'Donohue]]''' (incumbent) - 7,656\n:'''[[Ed Negridge]]''' (incumbent) - 4,545\n:Barbara Adams - 3,005\n:Glen Bany - 2,912\n:Pat Bator - 1,786\n\n;Ward 3 ([[Davenport, Toronto|Davenport]] and [[Corso Italia, Toronto|Corso Italia]])\n:'''[[Joseph Piccininni]]''' (incumbent) - 5,826\n:'''[[Richard Gilbert (politician)|Richard Gilbert]]''' - 4,651\n:Tony Amond - 1,464\n:Slough Bolton - 1,457\n:Domenic Tersigni - 545\n\n;Ward 4 ([[Trinity-Bellwoods]] and [[Little Italy]])\n:'''[[Art Eggleton]]''' (incumbent) - 4,615\n:'''[[George Ben]]''' (incumbent) - 2,957\n:[[Joe Pantalone]] - 2,713\n:Lee Zaslofsky - 1,940\n:Sydney Pimentel - 563\n:Brian Ashley - 379\n\n;Ward 5 ([[The Annex]] and [[Yorkville, Toronto|Yorkville]])\n:'''[[Ying Hope]]''' (incumbent) - 7,097\n:'''[[Susan Fish]]''' - 5,201\n:Fiona Nelson - 4,731\n:Barbara Jacob - 2,061\n:[[Brian Ashton (politician)|Brian Ashton]] - 1,796\n:Alex McDonald - 1,199\n:Norman Elder - 1,086\n\n;Ward 6 ([[Financial District, Toronto]] - [[University of Toronto]])\n:'''[[Dan Heap]]''' (incumbent) - 8,503\n:'''[[Allan Sparrow]]''' (incumbent) - 8,103\n:Peter Budd - 4,448\n:Arnold Linelsky - 2,046\n\n;Ward 7 ([[Regent Park]] and [[Riverdale, Toronto|Riverdale]])\n:'''[[John Sewell]]''' (incumbent) - 8,786\n:'''[[Janet Howard]]''' (incumbent) - 6,460\n:Gary Stamm - 4,419\n:Ronald Taylor - 770\n:Charles Rolfe - 767\n\n;Ward 8 ([[Riverdale, Toronto|Riverdale]])\n:'''[[Fred Beavis]]''' (incumbent) - 7,193\n:'''[[Thomas Clifford (Toronto)|Thomas Clifford]]''' (incumbent) - 6,883\n:Beatrice Zaverucha - 1,062\n:Louis Kesten - 951\n:John Bizzell - 771\n:Joe Dabonte - 458\n\n;Ward 9 ([[The Beaches]])\n:'''[[Pat Sheppard]]''' - 4,949\n:'''[[Tom Wardle, Jr.]]''' - 4,948\n:Bruce Budd - 4,665\n:Joe McNulty - 4,446\n:William Ross - 3,094\n:[[Neil Young (politician)|Neil Young]] - 2,114\n:John Oliver - 1,766\n:Sharon Meecham - 735\n:Edmond Cameron - 432\n:George Sloan - 344\n:Tom Last - 232\n\n;Ward 10 ([[Rosedale, Toronto|Rosedale]] and [[North Toronto]])\n:'''[[John Bosley (politician)|John Bosley]]''' (incumbent) - 11,638\n:'''[[June Rowlands]]''' - 11,307\n:Robert Perkins - 5,079\n:David White - 1,517\n\n;Ward 11 ([[Forest Hill, Toronto|Forest Hill]] and [[North Toronto]])\n:'''[[David Smith (Canadian Senator)|David Smith]]''' (incumbent) - 12,441\n:'''[[Anne Johnston]]''' (incumbent) - 11,600\n:Russ Tandler - 1,412\n:Fay MacPerson - 1,283\n\n===Changes===\nMayor [[David Crombie]] resigned on August 31, 1978 to contest a Federal by-election for [[Toronto Centre|Rosedale]] on October 16, 1978. On September 1, 1978 City Council met to appoint a new Mayor. The right-wingers stood Ward 8 Alderman [[Fred Beavis]] while the left-wingers stood Ward 11 Alderman [[Anne Johnston]]. When the vote was held the two candidates were tied with 11 votes each so in accordance with the Municipal Act put both names into a hat, and the name picked out of the hat would officially be pronounced interim mayor. Fred Beavis was the name chosen and he became mayor. [[Thomas Clifford (Toronto)|Thomas Clifford]] now became Ward 8's sole Alderman and was appointed Metro Councillor on September 11.\n\n==Metro boroughs==\n\n===East York===\nResults from the borough of East York. Two aldermen were elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: East York |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:[[Alan Redway]]\n\n;Ward 1\n:[[David Johnson (Canadian politician)|Dave Johnson]]\n:[[Leslie Saunders]]\n\n;Ward 2\n:John Flowers\n:Norman Crane\n\n;Ward 3\n:Ray Ireland\n:Don van Mierlo\n\n;Ward 4\n:Edna Beange\n:Peter Oyler\n\n===Etobicoke===\nResults from Etobicoke. Four members were elected to the Board of Control. Two aldermen were elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: Etobicoke |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:(x)[[Dennis Flynn]]\n\n;Board of Control\n:(x)Bill Stockwell\n:(x)[[Bruce Sinclair (politician)|Bruce Sinclair]]\n:(x)Nora Pownall\n:(x)E. H. (Pete) Farrow\n\n;Ward 1\n:Helen Wursta\n:[[Morley Kells]]\n\n;Ward 2\n:Alex Marchetti\n:Stewart East\n\n;Ward 3\n:Dick O'Brien\n:Alex McNeil\n\n;Ward 4\n:[[Lois Griffin (politician)|Lois Griffin]]\n:John Hanna\n\n;Ward 5\n:[[Ruth Grier]]\n:Pat Keaveney\n\n===North York===\n;Mayor\n:(x)'''[[Mel Lastman]]''' - 60,093\n:[[William Sutherland (Ontario politician)|William Sutherland]] - 15,634\n:Pallotta - 3,376\n:Obadia - 1,088\n:Minty - 920\n(1019 out of 1305 polls)\n\nLastman is re-elected defeating a challenge by Controller William Sutherland\n\n;Board of Control\n:(x)'''[[Barbara Greene]]''' - 52,053\n:'''[[Esther Shiner]]''' - 39,768\n:'''Ron Summers''' - 32,616\n:'''[[Robert Yuill|Bob Yuill]]''' - 31,050\n:Alex McGivern - 30,110\n:Jack Bedder - 20,267\n:Bernadette Michael - 13,803\n:Angelo Natale -10,281\n(1019 out of 1305 polls)\n\n;Ward 1\n:Gord Risk\n\n;Ward 2\n:[[Mario Gentile]]\n\n;Ward 3\n:Pat O'Neill\n\n{{Toronto municipal election, 1976/Position/North York Councillor, Ward Four}}\n\n*Hugh Montgomerie was a forty-three-year-old film technician.  He recommended a ban on high-density development projects that did not have adequate recreation facilities.<ref name=\"autogenerated1976\">\"North York\", ''Toronto Star'', 3 December 1976, A7.</ref>\n*Martin Lewin was a thirty-two-year-old sales manager.  He argued that shoppers in major plazas should not be forced to pay parking fees.<ref name=\"autogenerated1976\"/>\n*Harbans Rai Varma was a fifty-year-old supply teacher.  He called for lower employment and inflation levels, and for improved race relations.<ref name=\"autogenerated1976\"/>  He campaigned for the North York Board of Education in [[1980 Toronto municipal election|1980]], and lost to [[Elsa Chandler]] in Ward Four.  A candidate named \"Rai Varma\" ran for the [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]] Board of Control in [[1991 Markham general election|1991]]; this may be the same person.\n\n;Ward 5\n:Marilyn Meshberg\n\n;Ward 6\n:Milton Berger\n\n;Ward 7\n:Irving Chapley\n\n;Ward 8\n:[[Alan Heisey]]\n\n;Ward 9\n:[[Norm Gardner]]\n\n;Ward 10\n:Marie Laballe\n\n;Ward 11\n:Peter Clarke\n\n;Ward 12\n:Barry Burton\n\n;Ward 13\n:Mike Smith\n\n;Ward 14\n:Betty Sutherland\n\n===Scarborough===\nResults from the Borough of Scarborough. Four members were elected to the Board of Control. One alderman was elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: Scarborough |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:(x)'''[[Paul Cosgrove]]''' - 51,859\n:Lois James - 6,526\n\n;Board of Control\n:(x)'''[[Gus Harris]]''' - 35,525\n:(x)'''[[Ken Morrish]]''' - 35,243\n:(x)'''[[Joyce Trimmer]]''' - 31,358\n:(x)'''Brian Harrison''' - 30,956\n:Shirley Eidt - 28,363\n:Grant Boucher - 10,061\n:Larry Calcutt - 8,321\n:John Fletcher - 7,770\n\n;Ward 1\n:Bill Belfontaine\n\n;Ward 2\n:Carol Ruddell\n\n;Ward 3\n:[[Norm Kelly]]\n\n;Ward 4\n:Jack Goodlad\n\n;Ward 5\n:[[Frank Faubert]]\n\n;Ward 6\n:Frederick Samuel Bland\n\n;Ward 7\n:[[Ed Fulton]]\n\n;Ward 8\n:Tom Brazier\n\n;Ward 9\n:Doug Colling\n\n;Ward 10\n:Ron Watson\n\n;Ward 11\n:John Wimbs\n\n;Ward 12\n:Joe De Kort\n\n===York===\nResults from the borough of York. Two members were elected to the Board of Control. One alderman was elected to each ward.<ref>{{cite news |title=Voting Results: York |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=December 7, 1976 |page=A11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Results in Metro's five boroughs |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=December 7, 1976 |page=4}}</ref>\n\n;Mayor\n:'''[[Philip White (mayor)|Philip White]]''' 14,711\n:[[Fergy Brown]] 14,443\n\n;Board of Control (2 elected)\n:'''Doug Saunders''' 14,549\n:'''[[Alan Tonks]]''' 11,998\n:Patrick Canavan 7,479\n:Gordon 6,229\n:Ciardullo 3,572\n\n;Ward 1\n:Ben Nobleman (acclaimed)\n\n;Ward 2\n:Oscar Kogan (acclaimed)\n\n;Ward 3\n:Ron Bradd\n:Mizzoni 934\n:D'Aprile 825\n\n;Ward 4\n:Clifford Ward 1,532\n:Howells 693\n\n;Ward 5\n:[[Christopher Alexander Tonks|Chris Tonks]] (acclaimed)\n\n;Ward 6\n:Floyd Sainsbury 2,386\n:Dodds 2,187\n\n;Ward 7\n:[[Gayle Christie]] 2,853\n:Gallichan 1,484\n:McMahon 373\n\n;Ward 8\