{"title_page": "Islam and cats", "text_new": "[[File:Cat outside Gazi Husrev-Bey Mosque (6086909198).jpg|thumb|270px|[[Feral cat]] in the courtyard of [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]] in [[Sarajevo]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]]]\nThe [[cat|domestic cat]] is a revered [[Islam and animals|animal]] in [[Islam]].<ref name=Cyril/> Admired for its cleanliness as well as for being loved by [[Muhammad]], the cat is considered \"the quintessential pet\" by Muslims.<ref name=Campo/>\n\n== Origins of reverence ==\nCats have been venerated in the [[Near East]] since [[ancient Near East|antiquity]], a tradition adopted by Islam, albeit in a much modified form.<ref name=Baldick>{{cite book |title=Mystical Islam: An Introduction to Sufism |last=Baldick |first=J. |publisher=I.B. Tauris & Co. Ltd. |location=London, New York |year=2012 |isbn=9781860646317 |chapter=Into the modern world |pages=132\u2212168 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=nYOh6T-sw9IC&lpg=PP1&pg=P132}}</ref> According to many [[hadith]], [[Muhammad]] prohibited the persecution and killing of cats.<ref name=Campo/>\n\n[[File:Interior of a school in Cairo (detail).jpg|upright|thumb|Cat resting on a pillow next to an imam in Cairo, by [[John Frederick Lewis]]]]\nOne of Muhammad's [[sahabah|companions]] was known as [[Abu Hurairah]] (literally: \"Father of the Kitten\") for his attachment to cats.<ref name=Cyril/> Abu Hurairah claimed that he had heard Muhammad declare that a woman went to [[Jahannam|Hell]] for starving a female kitten and not providing her with any water.<ref name=Kurzman>{{cite book|title=Liberal Islam: A Source Book|last=Kurzman|first=Charles|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1998|isbn=0195116224|pages=121}}</ref> According to legend, Abu Saeed's cat saved Muhammad from a snake.<ref name=Campo/>.\n\n== History ==\nThe American poet and travel author [[Bayard Taylor]] (1825\u20131878) was astonished when he discovered a [[Syria]]n hospital where cats roamed freely. The institution, in which domestic felines were sheltered and nourished, was funded by a [[waqf]], along with caretakers' wages, [[veterinary care]] and [[cat food]]. [[Edward William Lane]] (1801\u20131876), a British Orientalist who resided in [[Cairo]], described a cat garden originally endowed by the 13th-century Egyptian sultan [[Baibars]], whose European contemporaries held a very different attitude towards cats, eating them or killing them under [[Papal bull|papal decrees]].<ref name=Campo/> [[Wilfred Thesiger]], in his book ''The Marsh Arabs'', notes that cats were allowed free entry to community buildings in villages in the [[Mesopotamian Marshes]], and even fed. <ref>Thesiger, Wilfried. The Marsh Arabs : Longman : London, 1964</ref> Aside from protecting granaries and food stores from pests, cats were valued by the paper-based Arab-Islamic cultures for preying on mice that destroyed books. For that reason, cats are often depicted in paintings alongside Islamic scholars and bibliophiles. The medieval Egyptian zoologist [[Al-Damiri]] (1344\u20131405) wrote that the first cat was created when [[God in Islam|God]] caused a [[lion]] to sneeze, after animals on [[Noah's Ark]] complained of mice.<ref name=Campo>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Islam|last=Campo|first=Juan Eduardo|pages=131|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=2009|isbn=1438126964}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Hygiene and neutering ==\n[[File:Cat outside a mosque.jpg|thumb|A cat on the doorstep of a mosque in [[\u015eirince]], [[Turkey]]]]\nIn Islamic tradition, cats are admired for their cleanliness. They are thought to be [[Muslim hygienical jurisprudence|ritually clean]], and are thus allowed to enter homes<ref name=Campo/> and even [[mosque]]s, including [[Masjid al-Haram]]. Food sampled by cats is considered [[halal]], in the sense that their consumption of the food does not make it impermissible for Muslims to eat, and water from which cats have drunk is permitted for [[wudu]].<ref name=Campo/> Furthermore, there is a belief among some Muslims that cats seek out people who are [[salat|praying]].<ref name=Cyril>{{cite book|title=The New Encyclopedia of Islam|last=Glass\u00e9|first=Cyril|publisher=Rowman Altamira|year=2003|isbn=0759101906|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/102 102]|url=https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/102}}</ref>\n\n[[Ulama|Muslim scholars]] are divided on the issue of [[neutering]] animals. Most, however, maintain that [[neutering]] cats is allowed \"if there is some benefit in neutering the cat and if that will not cause its death\".<ref name=Saed>{{cite book|title=Islam: Questions and Answers\u2014Jurisprudence and Islamic Rulings: General and Transactions, Part 1|author=Muhammad Saed Abdul-Rahman|publisher=MSA Publication Limited|year=2004|pages=323\u2013325|isbn=1861794118}}</ref> [[Muhammad ibn al Uthaymeen]], a 20th-century [[Saudi Arabia]]n [[Sunni]] [[imam]], preached:\n\n{{quote|If there are too many cats and they are a nuisance, and if the operation will not harm them, then there is nothing wrong with it, because this is better than killing them after they have been created. But if the cats are ordinary cats and are not causing a nuisance, perhaps it is better to leave them alone to reproduce.<ref name=Saed/>}}\n[[File:Muslim playing with kitten and praying beads in Al Azhar mosque in Cairo.webm|alt=A man teasing a cat with prayer beads in a mosque|thumb|A man teasing a cat with [[misbaha]] in [[Al-Azhar Mosque]] in Cairo]]\n\nthis whole forum is wrong give hadith about this\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cats|Islam}}\n* [[Cats in ancient Egypt]]\n* [[Animals in Islam#Felidae|''Felidae'' (domestic cats, lions, etc.) in Islam]]\n* [[Islam and dogs]]\n* [[Cultural depictions of cats|History of cats]]\n* [[Human interaction with cats]]\n* [[Moral status of animals in the ancient world]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.thegreatcat.org/history-of-the-cat-in-the-dark-ages-part-6/ History of the Cat in Islam]\n\n{{Cat nav}}\n\n[[Category:Cats as pets]]\n[[Category:Animals in Islam]]\n[[Category:Animals in Islamic history]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Cat outside Gazi Husrev-Bey Mosque (6086909198).jpg|thumb|270px|[[Feral cat]] in the courtyard of [[Gazi Husrev-beg Mosque]] in [[Sarajevo]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]]]\nThe [[cat|domestic cat]] is a revered [[Islam and animals|animal]] in [[Islam]].<ref name=Cyril/> Admired for its cleanliness as well as for being loved by [[Muhammad]], the cat is considered \"the quintessential pet\" by Muslims.<ref name=Campo/>\n\n== Origins of reverence ==\nCats have been venerated in the [[Near East]] since [[ancient Near East|antiquity]], a tradition adopted by Islam, albeit in a much modified form.<ref name=Baldick>{{cite book |title=Mystical Islam: An Introduction to Sufism |last=Baldick |first=J. |publisher=I.B. Tauris & Co. Ltd. |location=London, New York |year=2012 |isbn=9781860646317 |chapter=Into the modern world |pages=132\u2212168 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=nYOh6T-sw9IC&lpg=PP1&pg=P132}}</ref> According to many [[hadith]], [[Muhammad]] prohibited the persecution and killing of cats.<ref name=Campo/>\n\n[[File:Interior of a school in Cairo (detail).jpg|upright|thumb|Cat resting on a pillow next to an imam in Cairo, by [[John Frederick Lewis]]]]\nOne of Muhammad's [[sahabah|companions]] was known as [[Abu Hurairah]] (literally: \"Father of the Kitten\") for his attachment to cats.<ref name=Cyril/> Abu Hurairah claimed that he had heard Muhammad declare that a woman went to [[Jahannam|Hell]] for starving a female kitten and not providing her with any water.<ref name=Kurzman>{{cite book|title=Liberal Islam: A Source Book|last=Kurzman|first=Charles|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1998|isbn=0195116224|pages=121}}</ref> According to legend, Abu Saeed's cat saved Muhammad from a snake.<ref name=Campo/>.\n\n== History ==\nThe American poet and travel author [[Bayard Taylor]] (1825\u20131878) was astonished when he discovered a [[Syria]]n hospital where cats roamed freely. The institution, in which domestic felines were sheltered and nourished, was funded by a [[waqf]], along with caretakers' wages, [[veterinary care]] and [[cat food]]. [[Edward William Lane]] (1801\u20131876), a British Orientalist who resided in [[Cairo]], described a cat garden originally endowed by the 13th-century Egyptian sultan [[Baibars]], whose European contemporaries held a very different attitude towards cats, eating them or killing them under [[Papal bull|papal decrees]].<ref name=Campo/> [[Wilfred Thesiger]], in his book ''The Marsh Arabs'', notes that cats were allowed free entry to community buildings in villages in the [[Mesopotamian Marshes]], and even fed. <ref>Thesiger, Wilfried. The Marsh Arabs : Longman : London, 1964</ref> Aside from protecting granaries and food stores from pests, cats were valued by the paper-based Arab-Islamic cultures for preying on mice that destroyed books. For that reason, cats are often depicted in paintings alongside Islamic scholars and bibliophiles. The medieval Egyptian zoologist [[Al-Damiri]] (1344\u20131405) wrote that the first cat was created when [[God in Islam|God]] caused a [[lion]] to sneeze, after animals on [[Noah's Ark]] complained of mice.<ref name=Campo>{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Islam|last=Campo|first=Juan Eduardo|pages=131|publisher=Infobase Publishing|year=2009|isbn=1438126964}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Hygiene and neutering ==\n[[File:Cat outside a mosque.jpg|thumb|A cat on the doorstep of a mosque in [[\u015eirince]], [[Turkey]]]]\nIn Islamic tradition, cats are admired for their cleanliness. They are thought to be [[Muslim hygienical jurisprudence|ritually clean]], and are thus allowed to enter homes<ref name=Campo/> and even [[mosque]]s, including [[Masjid al-Haram]]. Food sampled by cats is considered [[halal]], in the sense that their consumption of the food does not make it impermissible for Muslims to eat, and water from which cats have drunk is permitted for [[wudu]].<ref name=Campo/> Furthermore, there is a belief among some Muslims that cats seek out people who are [[salat|praying]].<ref name=Cyril>{{cite book|title=The New Encyclopedia of Islam|last=Glass\u00e9|first=Cyril|publisher=Rowman Altamira|year=2003|isbn=0759101906|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/102 102]|url=https://archive.org/details/newencyclopediao0000glas/page/102}}</ref>\n\n[[Ulama|Muslim scholars]] are divided on the issue of [[neutering]] animals. Most, however, maintain that [[neutering]] cats is allowed \"if there is some benefit in neutering the cat and if that will not cause its death\".<ref name=Saed>{{cite book|title=Islam: Questions and Answers\u2014Jurisprudence and Islamic Rulings: General and Transactions, Part 1|author=Muhammad Saed Abdul-Rahman|publisher=MSA Publication Limited|year=2004|pages=323\u2013325|isbn=1861794118}}</ref> [[Muhammad ibn al Uthaymeen]], a 20th-century [[Saudi Arabia]]n [[Sunni]] [[imam]], preached:\n\n{{quote|If there are too many cats and they are a nuisance, and if the operation will not harm them, then there is nothing wrong with it, because this is better than killing them after they have been created. But if the cats are ordinary cats and are not causing a nuisance, perhaps it is better to leave them alone to reproduce.<ref name=Saed/>}}\n[[File:Muslim playing with kitten and praying beads in Al Azhar mosque in Cairo.webm|alt=A man teasing a cat with prayer beads in a mosque|thumb|A man teasing a cat with [[misbaha]] in [[Al-Azhar Mosque]] in Cairo]]\n\n== Muezza ==\n\nAccording to Islamic tradition, Muezza (or Mu\u02bfizza; {{lang-ar|\u0645\u0639\u0632\u0629}}) was [[Muhammad]]'s favorite cat.<ref name=\"Muezza1\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/whencatsreignedl00geor|url-access=registration|quote=Muezza.|title=When Cats Reigned Like Kings: On the Trail of the Sacred Cats|last=Geyer|first=Georgie Anne|date=|publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing|others=|year=2004|isbn=0-7407-4697-9|editor=|edition=|series=|location=|pages=|language=|format=|doi=|oclc=|id=|authorlink=|accessdate=|origyear=|coauthors=|month=}}</ref><ref name=\"Muezza2\">{{cite book |last=Stall |first=Sam |authorlink= |coauthors= |editor= |others= |title=100 Cats Who Changed Civilization: History's Most Influential Felines |year=2007 |month= |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=coXIF8WbEKEC&lpg=PA40&pg=PA40#v=onepage |format= |accessdate= |edition= |series= |date= |publisher=Quirk Books |location= |language= |isbn=978-1-59474-163-0 |oclc= |doi= |id=}}</ref> Muhammad awoke one day to the sounds of the [[adhan]]. Preparing to attend prayer, he began to dress himself; however, he soon discovered his cat Muezza sleeping on the sleeve of his prayer robe. Rather than wake her, he used a pair of scissors to cut the sleeve off, leaving the cat undisturbed. Another story is, upon returning from the mosque, [[Muhammad]] received a bow from Muezza. He then smiled and gently stroked his beloved cat three times.<ref name=\"Muezza1\" /><ref name=\"Muezza2\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cats|Islam}}\n* [[Cats in ancient Egypt]]\n* [[Animals in Islam#Felidae|''Felidae'' (domestic cats, lions, etc.) in Islam]]\n* [[Islam and dogs]]\n* [[Cultural depictions of cats|History of cats]]\n* [[Human interaction with cats]]\n* [[Moral status of animals in the ancient world]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.thegreatcat.org/history-of-the-cat-in-the-dark-ages-part-6/ History of the Cat in Islam]\n\n{{Cat nav}}\n\n[[Category:Cats as pets]]\n[[Category:Animals in Islam]]\n[[Category:Animals in Islamic history]]\n", "name_user": "51.252.124.244", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMuezza:is wrong)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islam_and_cats"}
{"title_page": "Foxit Reader", "text_new": "{{Infobox software\n| name                   = Foxit Reader\n| logo                   = FoxitReader.png\n| screenshot             = Foxit Reader 6 Screenshot.png\n| caption                = Foxit Reader on [[Windows 8.1]]\n| developer              = [[Foxit Software, Inc.]]\n| released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| programming language   = \n| platform               = {{unbulleted list|[[Windows ME]] (up to 2.3 Build 4015)|[[Windows 2000]] (up to version 4.3.1.0323)|[[Windows XP]] (up to version 7)|[[Windows Vista]] (version 3.0-7)|[[Windows 7]] (version 3.1.4 or later)|[[Windows 8]] (version 5.4.5.0124 or later)|[[Windows 10]] (versions 7 or later)|[[Windows CE]] 4.2-5.0 (version 1.0.0820)|[[Windows Mobile]] 5-6 for Smartphone (version 1.2.0602)/for [[Pocket PC]] (version 2.0.0701)|[[Symbian]] UIQ 3 (version 1.0.0910)|[[U3 (software)|U3]] (version 3.0)|[[Linux]] (versions 1.0 or later)|[[mac OS X 10.8]] (version 7 or later)|[[mac OS X 10.12]] (version 8 or later)|[[iOS]]||[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Windows Phone]]|[[Citrix XenApp]] 6-7.6 (version 7)|[[Citrix XenApp]] 7.13 (version 8 or later)}}\n| size                   = 59 [[Megabyte|MB]]\n| language               = English, French, German, Italian, Portuguese, Russian, Spanish and 35 other languages\n| genre                  = [[Desktop publishing software]] \n| license                = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n* '''Reader:''' [[Freeware]]\n* '''MobilePDF:''' Freeware\n| website                = {{url|www.foxitsoftware.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Foxit Reader''' is a multilingual [[freemium]] [[Portable Document Format|PDF]] tool that can create, view, edit, digitally sign, and print PDF files.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.softpedia.com/get/Office-tools/PDF/Foxit-PDF-Reader.shtml|title = Foxit Reader|date = 1 December 2014|accessdate = |website = [[Softpedia]]|publisher = SoftNews|last = Popa|first = Bogdan}}</ref> Foxit Reader is developed by Fremont, California-based [[Foxit Software]]. Early versions of Foxit Reader were notable for startup performance and small file size.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Foxit Software Foxit Reader 3.0|url = http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/review/foxit_software/foxit_reader_3_0/298071/|website = PC World|accessdate = 2015-07-24}}</ref> Foxit v3.0 was found to be comparable to [[Adobe Reader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcworld.com/downloads/file/fid,62648-order,1-page,1-c,alldownloads/description.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724115809/http://www.pcworld.idg.com.au/review/foxit_software/foxit_reader_3_0/298071/|archivedate=1 August 2015 |title=PC World, Foxit (PDF) Reader review |publisher=Pcworld.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-02}}</ref> The Windows version allows annotating and saving unfinished PDF forms, [[XFDF|FDF]] import/export, converting to text, highlighting and drawing.\n\n==Editions==\n{{As of|2015}} Foxit Reader was available for [[Windows Vista]] and later,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxitsoftware.com/downloads/ |title=Foxit Software - Downloads (Latest Version)|publisher=Foxitsoftware.com |date=2009-11-26 |accessdate=2013-12-03}}</ref> Apple [[iOS]], [[Windows RT]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[Windows Phone]]. Earlier Foxit versions support earlier operating systems ([[Windows 9x]] and later, [[Windows Mobile]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://foxit-reader-sp.en.softonic.com/windowsmobile/download |title=Download Foxit Reader (Windows Mobile) |date= |author= |accessdate= 5 December 2015}}Web site offering Foxit for Windows CE from 2008</ref> Foxit Reader 4.1.1 can be installed on unsupported versions of [[Windows]] such as [[Windows 98SE]], by installing [[KernelEX]] 4.5 first.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/alt.windows98/fCgOxFA9ea8 |title=Google Groups |publisher=}}</ref> Version history with release notes is available from Foxit, although not including release dates.<ref>{{cite web |title=Version History |url=https://www.foxitsoftware.com/products/pdf-reader/version-history.php |publisher=[[Foxit Corporation]] |date=2013-12-20 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>  However, other sites do provide release dates, some with more detail on changes.<ref>{{cite web |title=Foxit Reader Changelog |url=http://www.softpedia.com/progChangelog/Foxit-PDF-Reader-Changelog-16191.html |publisher=[[Softpedia]]| date=2013-12-27 |accessdate =2014-05-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Old Version of Foxit Reader ''(also includes current version)'' |url=http://www.oldapps.com/foxit_reader.php| publisher=[[OldApps]] |date=2013-12-26 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>\n \n==Issues==\nWith version 6.1.4, the Foxit installer was bundled with [[potentially unwanted program]]s like [[OpenCandy]] which installed the browser-hijacking malware [[Conduit (publisher network and platform)|Conduit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wilderssecurity.com/threads/foxit-reader-upgrade-warning.360532/|title=Foxit Reader upgrade warning|publisher=Wilders Security Forums}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://discuss.howtogeek.com/t/foxit-reader-installs-malware/13662|title=Foxit Reader installs malware!|publisher=How-To Geek}}</ref> Following complaints from users, it was removed after version 6.2.1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.foxitsoftware.com/forum/portable-document-format-pdf-tools/foxit-reader/18349-does-foxit-reader-free-6-1-4-0217-have-malware|title=Does Foxit Reader free 6.1.4.0217 have malware? - Foxit Corporation Forums|publisher=forums.foxitsoftware.com}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, the [[Internet Storm Center]] reported that the mobile version for [[iPhone]] was transmitting unencrypted telemetry and other data to remote servers located in [[China]] despite users attempting to opt out of such data collection.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesemann|first1=Daniel|title=App \"telemetry\"|url=http://isc.sans.edu/diary/18425|work=InfoSec Handlers Diary|publisher=[[SANS Institute]]|date=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of PDF software]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{PDF readers}}\n{{ebooks}}\n\n[[Category:Freeware]]\n[[Category:PDF readers]]\n[[Category:Portable software]]\n[[Category:Technical communication tools]]\n[[Category:Windows text-related software]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n  | name                   = Foxit Reader\n  | logo                   = FoxitReader.png\n  | screenshot             = Foxit Reader 6 Screenshot.png\n  | caption                = Foxit Reader on [[Windows 8.1]]\n  | developer              = [[Foxit Software, Inc.]]\n  | released               = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n  | programming language   = \n  | platform               = {{unbulleted list|[[Windows ME]] (up to 2.3 Build 4015)|[[Windows 2000]] (up to version 4.3.1.0323)|[[Windows XP]] (up to version 7)|[[Windows Vista]] (version 3.0-7)|[[Windows 7]] (version 3.1.4 or later)|[[Windows 8]] (version 5.4.5.0124 or later)|[[Windows 10]] (versions 7 or later)|[[Windows CE]] 4.2-5.0 (version 1.0.0820)|[[Windows Mobile]] 5-6 for Smartphone (version 1.2.0602)/for [[Pocket PC]] (version 2.0.0701)|[[Symbian]] UIQ 3 (version 1.0.0910)|[[U3 (software)|U3]] (version 3.0)|[[Linux]] (versions 1.0 or later)|[[mac OS X 10.8]] (version 7 or later)|[[mac OS X 10.12]] (version 8 or later)|[[iOS]]||[[Android (operating system)|Android]]|[[Windows Phone]]|[[Citrix XenApp]] 6-7.6 (version 7)|[[Citrix XenApp]] 7.13 (version 8 or later))}}\n  | size                   = 59 [[Megabyte|MB]]\n  | language               = English, French, German, Italian, Portuguese, Russian, Spanish and 35 other languages\n  | genre                  = [[Desktop publishing software]] \n  | license                = [[Proprietary software|Proprietary]]\n* '''Reader:''' [[Freeware]]\n* '''MobilePDF:''' Freeware\n  | website                = {{url|www.foxitsoftware.com}}\n}}\n'''Foxit Reader''' is a multilingual [[freemium]] [[Portabl