] was transmitting unencrypted telemetry and other data to remote servers located in [[China]] despite users attempting to opt out of such data collection.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wesemann|first1=Daniel|title=App \"telemetry\"|url=http://isc.sans.edu/diary/18425|work=InfoSec Handlers Diary|publisher=[[SANS Institute]]|date=22 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of PDF software]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{PDF readers}}\n{{ebooks}}\n\n[[Category:Freeware]]\n[[Category:PDF readers]]\n[[Category:Portable software]]\n[[Category:Technical communication tools]]\n[[Category:Windows text-related software]]\n", "name_user": "Dieter123", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foxit_Reader"}
{"title_page": "Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing", "text_new": "{{Infobox protocol|name=Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing|image=|caption=|standard=|developer={{Unbulleted list|[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]]|[[ETH Zurich]]|[[KU Leuven]]|[[Delft University of Technology]]|[[University College London]]|Helmholtz Centre for Information Security|University of Torino|ISI Foundation<ref name=\"whitepaper\">{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/documents/blob/master/DP3T%20White%20Paper.pdf|title=DP-3T whitepaper|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>}}|introdate={{Start date|2020|04|04}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/documents/commit/3b6024918f8980d2be10eeeaf7a43d6d52b64a38|title=Initial commit|last=|first=|date=2020-04-04|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>|industry=[[Digital contact tracing]]|hardware=Android & iOS smartphones|range=~{{convert|10|m|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.nordicsemi.com/getconnected/things-you-should-know-about-bluetooth-range|title=Things You Should Know About Bluetooth Range|last=Spon\u00e5s|first=Jon Gunnar|website=blog.nordicsemi.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>|website={{URL|https://www.pepp-pt.org/}}}}\n{{Distinguish|Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing}}\n\n'''Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing''' (DP-3T, stylized as <math>DP^3T</math>) is an [[open source]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/dp3t-app-android/blob/develop/LICENSE|title=DP-3T License|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> protocol developed in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] to facilitate [[digital contact tracing]] of infected participants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/20/technology/20reuters-health-coronavirus-europe-tech.html|title=Rift Opens Over European Coronavirus Contact Tracing Apps|date=2020-04-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The protocol, like competing protocol [[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]] (PEPP-PT), uses [[Bluetooth Low Energy]] to track and log encounters with other users.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://bluetrace.io/static/bluetrace_whitepaper-938063656596c104632def383eb33b3c.pdf|title=BlueTrace: A privacy-preserving protocol for community-driven contact tracing across borders|last=Jason Bay, Joel Kek, Alvin Tan, Chai Sheng Hau, Lai Yongquan, Janice Tan, Tang Anh Quy|first=|date=|website=Government Technology Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-google-contact-tracing-strengths-weaknesses/|title=Is Apple and Google's Covid-19 Contact Tracing a Privacy Risk?|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecurrencyanalytics.com/13404/zcash-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app-on-blockchain-the-temporary-contact-number-tcn-coalition/|title=ZCash Privacy Preserving Contact Tracing App on Blockchain the Temporary Contact Number TCN Coalition|date=2020-04-12|website=Cryptocurrency News - TCAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The protocols differ in their reporting mechanism, with PEPP-PT requiring clients to upload contact logs to a central reporting server and whereas with DP-3T, the central reporting server never has access to contact logs nor is it responsible for processing and informing clients of contact.<ref name=\"whitepaper\" /> Because contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, it has major privacy benefits over the PEPP-PT approach,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/20/coronavirus-contact-tracing-privacy-europe-pepp-pt-dp3t-covid-19-tracking/|title=Controversy around privacy splits Europe's push to build COVID-19 contact-tracing apps|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coindesk.com/european-contact-tracing-consortium-faces-wave-of-defections-over-centralization-concerns|title=European Contact Tracing Consortium Faces Wave of Defections|date=2020-04-20|website=CoinDesk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-europe-tech-idUKKBN2221U6|title=Rift opens over European coronavirus contact tracing apps|date=2020-04-20|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinternetofthings.eu/aisshwarya-tiwar-covid-19-zcash-zec-and-tcn-developing-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app|title=Aisshwarya Tiwar: COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App\u00a0{{!}} IoT Council|last=|first=|date=|website=www.theinternetofthings.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://btcmanager.com/covid-19-zcash-zec-tcn-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app/|title=COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App {{!}} BTCMANAGER|last=|first=|date=2020-04-12|website=btcmanager|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> however this comes at the cost of requiring more computing power on the client side to process infection reports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/documents/blob/master/DP3T%20-%20Simplified%20Three%20Page%20Brief.pdf|title=DP-3T 3 page brief|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nOn the 21 April 2020, the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Federal Office of Public Health]] announced that the Swiss national coronavirus contact tracing app will be based on DP-3T.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/sci-tech/digital-solution_contact-tracing-app-could-be-launched-in-switzerland-within-weeks/45706296|title=Contact tracing app could be launched in Switzerland within weeks|last=swissinfo.ch|first=S. W. I.|last2=Corporation|first2=a branch of the Swiss Broadcasting|website=SWI swissinfo.ch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> On the 22 April 2020, the [[Austrian Red Cross]], leading on the national digital contact tracing app, announced its migration to the approach of DP-3T.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ots.at/presseaussendung/OTS_20200422_OTS0052/stopp-corona-app-weiterentwicklung-mit-hilfe-der-zivilgesellschaft|title=Stopp Corona-App: Weiterentwicklung mit Hilfe der Zivilgesellschaft|website=OTS.at|language=de|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nThe DP-3T protocol works off the basis of Ephemeral IDs (EphID), semi-random rotating strings that uniquely identify clients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2020/04/20/frances-inria-and-germanys-fraunhofer-detail-their-robert-contact-tracing-protocol/|title=France\u2019s Inria and Germany\u2019s Fraunhofer detail their ROBERT contact-tracing protocol|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> When two clients encounter each other, they exchange EphIDs and store them locally in a contact log.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncase.me/contact-tracing/|title=Protecting Lives & Liberty: How Contact Tracing Can Foil COVID-19 & Big Brother|website=ncase.me|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Then, once a user tests positive for infection, a report is sent to a central server. Each client on the network then collects the reports from the server and independently checks their local contact logs for a EphID contained in the report. If a matching EphID is found, then the user has come in close contact with an infected patient, and is warned by the client. Since each device locally verifies contact logs, and thus contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, the central reporting server cannot by itself ascertain the identity or contact log of any client in the network. This is in contrast to competing protocols like PEPP-PT, where the central reporting server receives and processes client contact logs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@frankvolkel/tracetogether-under-the-hood-7d5e509aeb5d|title=TraceTogether: under the hood|last=Liauw|first=\ud83c\uddf8\ud83c\uddec Frank|date=2020-04-09|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Ephemeral ID ==\nSimilar to the [[TCN Protocol]] and its Temporary Contact Numbers, the DP-3T protocol makes use of 16 byte ''Ephemeral IDs'' (EphID) to uniquely identify devices in the proximity of a client. These EphIDs are logged locally on a receiving client's device and is never transmitted to third parties.\n\nTo generate an EphID, first a client generates a secret key that rotates daily (<math>SK_t</math>) by computing <math>SK_t = H(SK_{t-1})</math>, where <math>H()</math> is a cryptographic hash function such as [[SHA-2|SHA-256]]. <math>SK_0</math> is calculated by a standard secret key algorithm such as [[Ed25519]]. The client will use <math>SK_t</math> during day <math>t</math> to generate a list of EphIDs. At the beginning of the day, a client generates a local list of size <math>n=(24*60)/l</math> new EphIDs to broadcast throughout the day, where <math>l</math> is the lifetime of a EphID in minutes. To prevent malicious third parties from establishing patterns of movement by tracing static identifiers over a large area, EphIDs are rotated frequently. Given the secret day key <math>SK_t</math>, each device computes <math>EphID_n(BK) = PRG(PRF(SK_t, BK))</math>, where <math>BK</math> is a global fixed string, <math>PRF()</math> is a pseudo-random function like [[HMAC-SHA256]], and <math>PRG()</math> is a stream cipher producing <math>n * 16</math> bytes. This stream is then split into 16-byte chunks and randomly sorted to obtain the EphIDs of the day.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[BlueTrace]]\n* [[TCN Protocol]]\n* [[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]]\n* [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://github.com/DP-3T DP-3T Github]\n\n[[Category:Application layer protocols]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:Software associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Software using the MPL license]]\n[[Category:Digital contact tracing protocols]]\n[[Category:Software using the Apache license]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protocol|name=Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing|image=DP-3T_Logo.jpg|caption=|standard=|developer={{Unbulleted list|[[\u00c9cole Polytechnique F\u00e9d\u00e9rale de Lausanne]]|[[ETH Zurich]]|[[KU Leuven]]|[[Delft University of Technology]]|[[University College London]]|Helmholtz Centre for Information Security|University of Torino|ISI Foundation<ref name=\"whitepaper\">{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/documents/blob/master/DP3T%20White%20Paper.pdf|title=DP-3T whitepaper|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>}}|introdate={{Start date|2020|04|04}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/documents/commit/3b6024918f8980d2be10eeeaf7a43d6d52b64a38|title=Initial commit|last=|first=|date=2020-04-04|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>|industry=[[Digital contact tracing]]|hardware=Android & iOS smartphones|range=~{{convert|10|m|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.nordicsemi.com/getconnected/things-you-should-know-about-bluetooth-range|title=Things You Should Know About Bluetooth Range|last=Spon\u00e5s|first=Jon Gunnar|website=blog.nordicsemi.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>|website={{URL|https://www.pepp-pt.org/}}}}\n{{Distinguish|Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing}}\n\n'''Decentralized Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing''' (DP-3T, stylized as <math>DP^3T</math>) is an [[open source]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/dp3t-app-android/blob/develop/LICENSE|title=DP-3T License|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> protocol developed in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] to facilitate [[digital contact tracing]] of infected participants.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Reuters|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/20/technology/20reuters-health-coronavirus-europe-tech.html|title=Rift Opens Over European Coronavirus Contact Tracing Apps|date=2020-04-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The protocol, like competing protocol [[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]] (PEPP-PT), uses [[Bluetooth Low Energy]] to track and log encounters with other users.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://bluetrace.io/static/bluetrace_whitepaper-938063656596c104632def383eb33b3c.pdf|title=BlueTrace: A privacy-preserving protocol for community-driven contact tracing across borders|last=Jason Bay, Joel Kek, Alvin Tan, Chai Sheng Hau, Lai Yongquan, Janice Tan, Tang Anh Quy|first=|date=|website=Government Technology Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-google-contact-tracing-strengths-weaknesses/|title=Is Apple and Google's Covid-19 Contact Tracing a Privacy Risk?|work=Wired|access-date=2020-04-18|language=en|issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecurrencyanalytics.com/13404/zcash-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app-on-blockchain-the-temporary-contact-number-tcn-coalition/|title=ZCash Privacy Preserving Contact Tracing App on Blockchain the Temporary Contact Number TCN Coalition|date=2020-04-12|website=Cryptocurrency News - TCAT|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The protocols differ in their reporting mechanism, with PEPP-PT requiring clients to upload contact logs to a central reporting server and whereas with DP-3T, the central reporting server never has access to contact logs nor is it responsible for processing and informing clients of contact.<ref name=\"whitepaper\" /> Because contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, it has major privacy benefits over the PEPP-PT approach,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/2020/04/20/coronavirus-contact-tracing-privacy-europe-pepp-pt-dp3t-covid-19-tracking/|title=Controversy around privacy splits Europe's push to build COVID-19 contact-tracing apps|website=Fortune|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.coindesk.com/european-contact-tracing-consortium-faces-wave-of-defections-over-centralization-concerns|title=European Contact Tracing Consortium Faces Wave of Defections|date=2020-04-20|website=CoinDesk|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-europe-tech-idUKKBN2221U6|title=Rift opens over European coronavirus contact tracing apps|date=2020-04-20|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theinternetofthings.eu/aisshwarya-tiwar-covid-19-zcash-zec-and-tcn-developing-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app|title=Aisshwarya Tiwar: COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App\u00a0{{!}} IoT Council|last=|first=|date=|website=www.theinternetofthings.eu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://btcmanager.com/covid-19-zcash-zec-tcn-privacy-preserving-contact-tracing-app/|title=COVID-19: Zcash (ZEC) and TCN Developing Privacy-Preserving Contact Tracing App {{!}} BTCMANAGER|last=|first=|date=2020-04-12|website=btcmanager|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> however this comes at the cost of requiring more computing power on the client side to process infection reports.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://github.com/DP-3T/documents/blob/master/DP3T%20-%20Simplified%20Three%20Page%20Brief.pdf|title=DP-3T 3 page brief|last=|first=|date=|website=GitHub|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\nOn the 21 April 2020, the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Federal Office of Public Health]] announced that the Swiss national coronavirus contact tracing app will be based on DP-3T.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.swissinfo.ch/eng/sci-tech/digital-solution_contact-tracing-app-could-be-launched-in-switzerland-within-weeks/45706296|title=Contact tracing app could be launched in Switzerland within weeks|last=swissinfo.ch|first=S. W. I.|last2=Corporation|first2=a branch of the Swiss Broadcasting|website=SWI swissinfo.ch|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> On the 22 April 2020, the [[Austrian Red Cross]], leading on the national digital contact tracing app, announced its migration to the approach of DP-3T.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ots.at/presseaussendung/OTS_20200422_OTS0052/stopp-corona-app-weiterentwicklung-mit-hilfe-der-zivilgesellschaft|title=Stopp Corona-App: Weiterentwicklung mit Hilfe der Zivilgesellschaft|website=OTS.at|language=de|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n== Overview ==\nThe DP-3T protocol works off the basis of Ephemeral IDs (EphID), semi-random rotating strings that uniquely identify clients.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://social.techcrunch.com/2020/04/20/frances-inria-and-germanys-fraunhofer-detail-their-robert-contact-tracing-protocol/|title=France\u2019s Inria and Germany\u2019s Fraunhofer detail their ROBERT contact-tracing protocol|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> When two clients encounter each other, they exchange EphIDs and store them locally in a contact log.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ncase.me/contact-tracing/|title=Protecting Lives & Liberty: How Contact Tracing Can Foil COVID-19 & Big Brother|website=ncase.me|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Then, once a user tests positive for infection, a report is sent to a central server. Each client on the network then collects the reports from the server and independently checks their local contact logs for a EphID contained in the report. If a matching EphID is found, then the user has come in close contact with an infected patient, and is warned by the client. Since each device locally verifies contact logs, and thus contact logs are never transmitted to third parties, the central reporting server cannot by itself ascertain the identity or contact log of any client in the network. This is in contrast to competing protocols like PEPP-PT, where the central reporting server receives and processes client contact logs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@frankvolkel/tracetogether-under-the-hood-7d5e509aeb5d|title=TraceTogether: under the hood|last=Liauw|first=\ud83c\uddf8\ud83c\uddec Frank|date=2020-04-09|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n== Ephemeral ID ==\nSimilar to the [[TCN Protocol]] and its Temporary Contact Numbers, the DP-3T protocol makes use of 16 byte ''Ephemeral IDs'' (EphID) to uniquely identify devices in the proximity of a client. These EphIDs are logged locally on a receiving client's device and is never transmitted to third parties.\n\nTo generate an EphID, first a client generates a secret key that rotates daily (<math>SK_t</math>) by computing <math>SK_t = H(SK_{t-1})</math>, where <math>H()</math> is a cryptographic hash function such as [[SHA-2|SHA-256]]. <math>SK_0</math> is calculated by a standard secret key algorithm such as [[Ed25519]]. The client will use <math>SK_t</math> during day <math>t</math> to generate a list of EphIDs. At the beginning of the day, a client generates a local list of size <math>n=(24*60)/l</math> new EphIDs to broadcast throughout the day, where <math>l</math> is the lifetime of a EphID in minutes. To prevent malicious third parties from establishing patterns of movement by tracing static identifiers over a large area, EphIDs are rotated frequently. Given the secret day key <math>SK_t</math>, each device computes <math>EphID_n(BK) = PRG(PRF(SK_t, BK))</math>, where <math>BK</math> is a global fixed string, <math>PRF()</math> is a pseudo-random function like [[HMAC-SHA256]], and <math>PRG()</math> is a stream cipher producing <math>n * 16</math> bytes. This stream is then split into 16-byte chunks and randomly sorted to obtain the EphIDs of the day.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[BlueTrace]]\n* [[TCN Protocol]]\n* [[Pan-European Privacy-Preserving Proximity Tracing]]\n* [[Google / Apple contact tracing project]]\n\n== References ==\n\n<references />{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [https://github.com/DP-3T DP-3T Github]\n\n[[Category:Application layer protocols]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:Software associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Software using the MPL license]]\n[[Category:Digital contact tracing protocols]]\n[[Category:Software using the Apache license]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Mirive", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing logo pending verification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decentralized_Privacy-Preserving_Proximity_Tracing"}
